\b Software requirements
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 To author Windows Help version 4.0 files, you need the following software on your computer:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Help Workshop (Hcw.exe and Hcrtf.exe)
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab WinHelp version 4.0 (Winhlp32.exe)
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab A word processor that saves files in rich-text format (RTF), inserts custom footnotes, supports single and double underlining, and allows hidden text.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Windows\'a095 or Windows\'a0NT.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \b Notes
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab Although you can author Help files on any version of Windows\'a0NT, WinHelp version 4.0 runs only on Windows\'a0NT version 3.51 or later. Help Workshop runs on Windows\'a095 or later, and on any version of Windows\'a0NT.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab If you are familiar with RTF coding, you can prepare and save your topic files using any word processor or text editor that can retain the files in that format.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Do not use Microsoft WordPad to author topic files.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("COMPRESS;FTS;RTFHelpRTFStatements")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("COMPRESS;FTS;RTFHelpRTFStatements")}
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 1OTGU5L}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 To return to the list of topics, click Help Topics.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:006b}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} New Help Topics dialog box}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} NEW_WINHELP_INTERFACE}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} NEW_USER;NEW_WINHELP_INTERFACE;whats_new}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} Contents tab;Contents tab, about the Contents tab;dialog boxes;dialog boxes, Help Topics dialog box;Find tab;Find tab, about the Find tab;Help Topics dialog box;Help Topics dialog box, about the Help Topics dialog box;Index tab;Index tab, about the Index tab;new features;new features, Help Topics dialog box;tabs;tabs, about tabs in the Help Topics dialog box;WinHelp,;WinHelp, new features}
\b New Help Topics dialog box
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The Help Topics dialog box contains a Contents tab, an Index tab, and a Find tab. This dialog box appears when users:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Click Help Topics on the Help menu in a program 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Double-click a Help file in Windows Explorer or My Computer or a Help shortcut icon on the desktop. The Help file must be associated with a contents (.cnt) file that specifies a Contents tab.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 The Contents tab contains information that is specified by the new contents (.cnt) file. The Index tab contains the keywords for one or more Help files. The Find tab provides full-text search capability for all Help files.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`PRO_CNT_CREATE')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`PRO_CNT_CREATE')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:006c}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} New context menu}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} NEW_WINHELP_CONTEXT_MENUS}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} NEW_USER;NEW_WINHELP_CONTEXT_MENUS;whats_new}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} context menus;context menus, for Help windows;new features;new features, context menu;pop-up menus;pop-up menus, for Help windows;right mouse button;right mouse button, accessing a context menu for Help windows;WinHelp,;WinHelp, new features}
\b New context menu
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 When users click a Help window using their right mouse button, a menu that contains the following commands appears:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Annotate
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Copy
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Print Topic
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Font
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Keep Help On Top
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Use System Colors
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 These commands also appear if users click the Options button in a Help window. An Options button appears on a Help window's button bar if you specify it in your project (hpj) file.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \b Notes
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab When you are viewing a Help file in \ul Help Author mode,\plain\f1\fs16 {\v PZJ46U} two additional commands appear on the menu:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Topic Information
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Ask On Hotspots
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`askonhot')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`askonhot')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:006d}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} New Options menu}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} NEW_WINHELP_OPTIONS_MENU}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} NEW_USER;NEW_WINHELP_OPTIONS_MENU;whats_new}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} colors;colors, Use System Colors option for Help windows;Display History Window option;fonts,;fonts, changing from Options menu in Help windows;Help windows;Help windows, Keep Help On Top option;History window, option for displaying;Keep Help On Top option;new features;new features, Options menu;Options menu for Help windows;Use System Colors option;WinHelp,;WinHelp, new features}
\b New Options menu
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 A new Options menu in the \ul main Help window\plain\f1\fs16 {\v O8.Q2} contains four commands:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Keep Help On Top
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Display History Window
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Font
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Use System Colors
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 Most of these commands also appear when users click a Help window using their right mouse button, and when users click the Options button in a Help window. An Options button appears on a Help window's button bar if you specify it in your project (hpj) file.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:006e}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} New annotation capabilities}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} New_annotation}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} NEW_ANNOTATION}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} annotations, read-only;Help topics,;Help topics, annotations in;new features;new features, annotations, read-only;paper-clip icon;read-only annotation files;topics,;topics, annotations in;WinHelp,;WinHelp, new features}
\b New annotation capabilities
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 WinHelp version 4.0 supports read-only annotation files. System administrators can insert annotations in a Help file, and then add a read-only attribute to the annotation (.ann) file. This prevents users from adding or editing annotations, but enables them to view annotations by clicking the paper-clip icon in annotated topics.
\par System administrators can place annotation files in network locations.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:006f}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Improved copying}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} NEW_WINHELP_COPY}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} NEW_USER;NEW_WINHELP_COPY;whats_new}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} copying text in Help topics;drag and drop;Help topics,;Help topics, copying text in;new features;new features, copying text in Help topics;pop-up windows;pop-up windows, copying text in;right mouse button;right mouse button, copying text in Help windows;selecting text in Help topics;WinHelp,;WinHelp, new features}
\b Improved copying
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Users can now copy Help text to the clipboard by selecting the text and then clicking the Copy command on the Edit menu of a \ul main window,\plain\f1\fs16 {\v O8.Q2} the Options button (if it is included on the window's button bar), or the \ul context menu.\plain\f1\fs16 {\v JNVVI2} To copy the contents of a \ul pop-up window,\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 8XSV6X} users can use the right mouse button to click the window and then click Copy on the context menu. 
\par Users can also drag and drop selected text from a Help window to any program that supports drag-and-drop functions for OLE.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0070}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} New printing capabilities}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} NEW_WINHELP_PRINTING}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} NEW_USER;NEW_WINHELP_PRINTING;whats_new}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} EndMPrint macro;InitMPrint macro;macros,;macros, EndMPrint;macros, InitMPrint;new features;new features, printing options;printing;printing, multiple Help topics;printing, pop-up window contents;WinHelp,;WinHelp, new features}
\b New printing options
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Users can now print multiple topics by clicking a book on the Contents tab, and then clicking the Print button. Users can also print topics by clicking an author-defined \ul hotspot\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 7BM6.K} in a topic that has been set up to run the InitMPrint and EndMPrint macros.
\par To print the contents of a \ul pop-up window,\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 8XSV6X} users can click the pop-up using their right mouse button, and then click Print Topic.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0071}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} New ESC key function}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} New_key}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} NEW_KEY;NEW_USER;whats_new}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} closing;closing, Help windows;closing, WinHelp;ESC key;Help windows;Help windows, closing;new features;new features, ESC key function;WinHelp,;WinHelp, closing;WinHelp, new features}
\b New ESC key function
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The \scaps esc\plain\f1\fs16  key now closes the current Help window when no dialog box or \ul pop-up window\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 8XSV6X} is open. If the current Help window is the only Help window that is open, WinHelp closes.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0072}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Background color override}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} NEW_COLOR}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} NEW_COLOR;NEW_USER;whats_new}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} background color;background color, overriding;colors;colors, overriding background colors;new features;new features, background color override;WinHelp,;WinHelp, new features}
\b Background color override
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 If users set the \ul high contrast flag\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 2EOL3C} or change the background or text colors for windows in Display properties, WinHelp ignores any window background colors that you defined in your project (.hpj) file.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0073}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Context-sensitive Help access}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} NEW_CONTEXT}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} NEW_CONTEXT;NEW_USER;whats_new}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} context-sensitive Help;context-sensitive Help, access to;dialog boxes;dialog boxes, accessing context-sensitive Help in;F1 key;new features;new features, access to context-sensitive Help;pop-up windows;pop-up windows, accessing from a dialog box;question mark button in dialog box title bars;right mouse button;right mouse button, accessing context-sensitive Help;What's This? command access;WinHelp,;WinHelp, new features}
\b Context-sensitive Help access
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 In addition to using the F1 key to access context-sensitive Help for an item in a dialog box, users can click the \{bmc bm0.bmp\} button on the title bar of a dialog box, and then click the item. Users can also use their right mouse button to click an item, and then click What's This.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0074}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Graphical interfaces}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} NEW_AUTHOR_HCW_UI}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} NEW_AUTHOR;NEW_AUTHOR_HCW_UI}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} Help Workshop;Help Workshop, new features;new features;new features, graphical interface in Help Workshop;WinHelp 3.x files}
\b Graphical interfaces
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Help Workshop has a new graphical interface that enables you to compile your Help files and to create and edit project (.hpj) and contents (.cnt) files. Using the graphical interface, you can easily specify or change settings. If you don't understand what a setting is for, you can use context-sensitive Help to learn more about it. 
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Note
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab Help Workshop can read (.hpj) files that were created for version 3.x of WinHelp. However, if you use Help Workshop to edit these files, they are saved in a slightly different format, and the MS-DOS\plain\f0\fs16 \'96\f1 based compiler will be unable to process them.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0075}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} New topic file features}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} New_topic_file}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} NEW_AUTHOR;NEW_TOPIC_FILE}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} authorable buttons;avi files in Help topics;buttons,;buttons, authorable;creating;creating, authorable buttons;Help Workshop;Help Workshop, new features;multimedia;multimedia, adding to topics;new features;new features, new topic file features;topic files;topic files, new features}
\b New topic file features
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Help Workshop provides two new topic statements and allows longer \ul hotspot\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 7BM6.K} definitions.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Authorable buttons
\par \plain\f1\fs16 You can create an authorable button by using the \{\-button\'7d command in the topic (.rtf) file. Any WinHelp macro(s) can be assigned to the button. The width of the button is determined by the text defined for it. If no text is specified, WinHelp will create a 12-by-12\plain\f0\fs16 \'96\f1 pixel button.
\par \b Multimedia support
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 You can include multimedia files (.avi) in Help topics by using the \{\-mci\'7d command in the topic file.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Increased hotspot capacity
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The size limitation for a \ul hotspot\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 7BM6.K} has been raised to 4095 characters.
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} New window-type footnote}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} New_window_type}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} footnotes;footnotes, window type footnote;new features;new features, new window-type footnote;window types;windows,;windows, specifying type;WinHelp,;WinHelp, new features}
\b New window-type footnote
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Topics are usually displayed in the main or current window type unless another window type is specified in jump instructions for a \ul hotspot\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 7BM6.K} or for an item on the Contents tab. However, you can override the window type when the topic is accessed from the Index or Find tabs, or by an \ul ALink\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 7V8V.U} or \ul KLink\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 1R9H33X} macro.
\par You can use the greater-than sign (>) footnote in your topic (.rtf) files to specify a window type for any given topic. The window type you specify must be defined in the project (.hpj) file.
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Secondary-window features}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 1BQUZJT}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} absolute position;Back button;button bar;button bar, in secondary windows;new features;new features, secondary-window features;secondary windows;secondary windows, new features;window types;windows,;windows, secondary;windows, specifying type;WinHelp,;WinHelp, new features}
\b Secondary-window features
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\ul\fs16 Secondary windows\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 2ZK4PT} can now contain a button bar, which is completely configurable in the project (.hpj) file. You can use standard buttons and add your own.
\par You can now specify as many as 255 secondary-window types in your project file. Up to nine of these secondary windows can be displayed at the same time. You can also specify an \ul absolute position\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 9UIBLJ} for a Help window.
\par You can add a Back button to a secondary window. Each window type has its own history list and will display only the history of topics that were displayed in that window type. This functionality is designed for Help files that use a secondary window exclusively. You can use either the Back() macro or add the Back button to the secondary window's button bar.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 You can set secondary windows to automatically adjust to the length of a topic. In addition, users can more easily specify that secondary windows should stay on top of other windows.
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} New macros and enhanced macro processing}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} New_macros}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} Help Workshop;Help Workshop, new features;long names for macros;macros,;macros, long names for;macros, new features;new features;new features, enhanced macro processing;new features, new macros;quotation marks;quotation marks, unnecessary in macros;WinHelp,;WinHelp, new features}
\b New macros and enhanced macro processing
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 More than 20 new macros are available for WinHelp version 4.0 Help files, and Help Workshop has fewer limitations on macro processing. In addition, there is no practical limit to the number of macros that can be nested.
\par Help Workshop now automatically changes macro names to their short form. (Using long names for macros in .rtf files greatly enhances the readability of those files.) For macros requiring numeric arguments, you can use more descriptive string values instead. In most cases, quotation marks are no longer necessary. If the final parameter for a macro is 0 or " ", that parameter can be omitted.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Hotspot macros can now use as many as 4096 characters.
\par For a list of macros, see the \uldb Macro Quick Reference.\plain\f1\fs16 {\v MACRO_REF_OVR}
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Bitmaps supplied by Help Workshop}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 149DTIV}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} bitmaps,;bitmaps, supplied by Help Workshop;Help Workshop;Help Workshop, new features;new features;new features, bitmaps supplied by Help Workshop}
\b Bitmaps supplied by Help Workshop
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Help Workshop comes with new bitmaps that you can use. You can specify the filename for any of these bitmaps in your topic (.rtf) files, even though the bitmap is not in your bitmaps folder. If your bitmaps folder contains a bitmap that has the same filename as one specified below, that bitmap is used instead of the one supplied by Help Workshop.
