\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Greater color support}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} HH396.}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} bitmaps,;bitmaps, color depth;color depth;colors;colors, bitmaps;Help Workshop;Help Workshop, new features;new features;new features, greater color support;WinHelp,;WinHelp, new features}
\b Greater color support
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 WinHelp version 4.0 supports any color depth that the operating system supports (256 colors, 24-bit color, and so on). If you use 16-color bitmaps, you are no longer limited to the standard 16 colors. 
\par Help Workshop version enables you to specify more than one color-depth version of a graphic in a single \{\-bmx\'7d bitmap statement in your topic (.rtf) file. WinHelp determines the color-depth capability of a user's monitor, and then uses the most appropriate bitmap file.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Note
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab You can now make the white background color in bitmaps transparent, so the colored background of a Help topic shows through.
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} New default buttons}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} New_default_button}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} browse buttons;browse buttons, in secondary windows;button bar;button bar, new default buttons;buttons,;buttons, new default buttons;default buttons;Find button;Help Topics button;Help Workshop;Help Workshop, new features;new features;new features, new default buttons;secondary windows;secondary windows, new features;WinHelp,;WinHelp, new features}
\b New default buttons
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 In addition to the regular default buttons, you can add a Find button to the button bar, and you can use a Help Topics button instead of the Contents and Index buttons. In addition, browse buttons are now available in \ul secondary windows.\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 2ZK4PT} 
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Duplicate accelerators}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} E6G33D}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} accelerator keys;accelerator keys, duplicate;duplicate accelerators;new features;new features, duplicate accelerators;WinHelp,;WinHelp, new features}
\b Duplicate accelerators
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 If two or more buttons use the same accelerator, WinHelp now attempts to move the accelerator of the second button so that the letter chosen does not conflict with the accelerator of any other button. If WinHelp cannot create a unique accelerator and the user presses that accelerator key, WinHelp displays a dialog box containing the text of every button that contains the duplicated accelerator and asks the user to choose.
\par If no accelerator is specified for the text of a button, WinHelp automatically chooses the first letter that does not conflict with any other button. If WinHelp cannot find a unique accelerator, WinHelp uses the first letter of the text string. WinHelp ignores conflicts with menu accelerators.
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} New topic-linking features}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 35SG_9Q}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} ALinks;ALinks, new topic-linking features;interfile jumps;jumps;jumps, new topic-linking features;jumps, to another Help file;KLinks;KLinks, new topic-linking features;linking multiple Help files;linking topics;new features;new features, new topic-linking features;WinHelp,;WinHelp, new features}
\b New topic-linking features
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 WinHelp version 4.0 provides two new linking macros, \ul KLink\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 1R9H33X} and \ul ALink,\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 7V8V.U} that enable you to provide jumps to multiple topics based on \ul keywords\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 9ML77Q} rather than specific context strings.
\par These jumps are resolved when the user clicks them instead of when the file is compiled. This enables you to create interfile jumps for Help files that might change after the original jump was created or for Help files that might or might not have been installed at the time the program was released.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 KLink macros use K-keywords \plain\f0\fs16 \'97\f1  the same keywords that you use to create the index. If a user clicks a \ul hotspot\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 7BM6.K} that runs the KLink macro, WinHelp displays the Topics Found dialog box, which contains a list of all the topics that have the associated keywords throughout the family of Help files. The macro can be configured so that if only one topic is found, the jump occurs immediately without displaying the Topics Found dialog box. KLink (and ALink) macros can access multiple Help files if they are properly specified in the contents file.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 ALink macros function similarly to KLink macros except A-keywords never appear in the index. Jumps using ALink macros are unaffected by any changes to the index.
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} New WinHelp API commands}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} New_API}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} tables}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} new features;new features, new WinHelp API commands;WinHelp API commands, new;WinHelp function;WinHelp,;WinHelp, new features}
\b New WinHelp API commands
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The following new commands are available for the WinHelp function.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li2155\ri125\fi-2025\brdrb\brdrs\tx2155 \b Command\tab Purpose
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li2155\ri125\fi-2025\tx2155 \plain\f1\fs16 HELP_CONTEXTMENU\tab Displays context-sensitive Help when the right mouse button is clicked.
\par HELP_FINDER\tab Displays the Help Topics dialog box in its last state.
\par HELP_SETPOPUP_POS\tab Sets the position for the next pop-up window. Overrides the actual mouse position.
\par HELP_TCARD\tab Indicates that a command is for a training-card instance of the WinHelp program. A program combines the HELP_TCARD flag with other commands by using the bitwise OR operator.
\par HELP_WM_HELP\tab Displays context-sensitive Help when the F1 key is pressed.
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} New author-specified font capability}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} Q5GYJT}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} Contents tab;Contents tab, default font;default fonts;dialog boxes;dialog boxes, Topics Found dialog box;font handling features;fonts,;fonts, default;Help Workshop;Help Workshop, new features;Index tab;Index tab, default font;new features;new features, new author-specified font capability;Topics Found dialog box;Topics Found dialog box, default font;WinHelp,;WinHelp, new features}
\b New author-specified font capability
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 WinHelp version 4.0 enables you to set the default fonts for lists that appear on the Contents and Index tabs and in the Topics Found dialog box. You can set default fonts while editing your project (.hpj) file by clicking the Options button, and then clicking the Fonts tab.
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Character set as part of font description}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 74Z0SU}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} character sets;character sets, including as part of font description;font handling features;Help Workshop;Help Workshop, new features;new features;new features, character set as part of font description;WinHelp,;WinHelp, new features}
\b Character set as part of font description
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 WinHelp version 4.0 expects Help files to include the character set as part of the font description. If you are using a word processor that includes this information as part of the font table description (for example, Microsoft Word for Windows version 6.0), Help Workshop includes this information automatically. If the information is not supplied in the topic (.rtf) file, Help Workshop uses default values for the character set.
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Longer font names}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 2ZR9RVV}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} font handling features;font names;fonts, international;fonts, Script;fonts, Wingdings;Help Workshop;Help Workshop, new features;international fonts;new features;new features, longer font names;Script fonts;Wingdings font support;WinHelp,;WinHelp, new features}
\b Longer font names
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Help Workshop increases the limit for font names from 20 to 31 characters.
\par WinHelp also stores the character set, making it possible to use fonts like Script and various international fonts. The Wingdings font is now fully supported.
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Greater RTF character support}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 7.0B3X}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} characters;characters, greater RTF character support;font handling features;Help Workshop;Help Workshop, new features;new features;new features, greater RTF character support}
\b Greater RTF character support
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Help Workshop now supports the following RTF statements:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab \uldb \'5cemdash\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 1_S4HV.>tables}
