\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Automatic localization of quotation marks}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 2APQ_RY}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} characters;characters, automatic localization of quotation marks;font handling features;Help Workshop;Help Workshop, new features;localizing;localizing, quotation marks;new features;new features, automatic localization of quotation marks;quotation marks;quotation marks, automatic localization of}
\b Automatic localization of quotation marks
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The \uldb \'5cldblquote\plain\f1\fs16 {\v XC5Y79>tables} and \uldb \'5crdblquote\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 12UI60T>tables} RTF statements\b  \plain\f1\fs16 are used for generating quotation marks. The actual characters that are displayed in the Help file are determined by the language specified in the project (.hpj) file.
\par WinHelp displays French-style quotation marks for the following character sets:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Algerian
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Belgian
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab French Canadian
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab French (Luxembourg)
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab French (Standard)
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab French (Swiss)
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Moroccan
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Tunisian
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 WinHelp displays German-style quotation marks for the following character sets:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab German (Austrian)
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab German (Liechtenstein)
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab German (Luxembourg)
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab German (Standard)
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab German (Swiss)
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 All other non \plain\f0\fs16 \'96\f1  double-byte character sets display the standard curly quotation marks. Curly quotation marks are displayed in Times Roman, using the current font's point size.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \b Examples
\par \pard\sb115\sa115\li115\ri125\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 \{bmc bm11.bmp\}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0076}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} New context-sensitive help features}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} New_context_sensitive}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} NEW_AUTHOR;NEW_CONTEXT_SENSITIVE}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} context-sensitive Help;context-sensitive Help, new features;dialog boxes;dialog boxes, new context-sensitive Help features;new features;new features, new context-sensitive Help features;overview topics for dialog boxes;pop-up windows;pop-up windows, new context-sensitive Help features;WinHelp,;WinHelp, new features}
\b New context-sensitive help features
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 In WinHelp 4.0, the procedure for applying context-sensitive \ul pop-up\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 8XSV6X} Help topics to interface elements and controls has been greatly simplified. At the same time, it is now possible to apply context-sensitive Help directly to a greater range of individual interface elements. This increase in ease and range encourages Help authors and developers to make fuller use of context-sensitive Help. Where conceptual overviews are needed for dialog boxes, an overview topic can be linked to a Help button in those dialog boxes.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`cs_help')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`cs_help',0,`main')}
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Help Author command}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} IV.JR3}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} Help Author command;Help Workshop;Help Workshop, new features;new features;new features, Help Author command;numbers;numbers, in title bar;title bar;title bar, numbers in;WinHelp,;WinHelp, new features}
\b Help Author command
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 A new Help Author command provides additional authoring information and debugging capabilities. When you check the Help Author command on the File menu in Help Workshop:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The text on the title bar of the Help topic is replaced with the topic number. This number is determined by the order in which topics appear in your topic (.rtf) files, as listed in the project (.hpj) file.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab You can press \scaps ctrl+shift+right\'a0arrow\plain\f1\fs16 , and \scaps ctrl+shift+left\'a0arrow \plain\f1\fs16 to step through the topics in your Help file and \scaps ctrl+shift+home \plain\f1\fs16 and\scaps  ctrl+shift+end \plain\f1\fs16 to move to the beginning or end of your Help file.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab WinHelp displays specific information about problems in the Help (.hlp) or contents (.cnt) file.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Topic Information and Ask On Hotspots commands appear when you click a topic using your right mouse button. The Topic Information command displays information about the current topic, including the text of the title ($) footnote, the macros specified in the entry macro (!) footnote, the name of the current window type, and the Help filename and path. The Ask On Hotspots command changes the effect of clicking a \ul hotspot.\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 7BM6.K} If this command is checked, WinHelp displays the topic ID or macro syntax of any hotspot you click and prompts you to specify whether the macro or hotspot jump should be carried out.
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Report command}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} HLKB15}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} Help Workshop;Help Workshop, new features;new features;new features, Report command;Report command;reports, generating}
\b Report command
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 You can generate a report that contains information about a Help file by clicking the File menu in Help Workshop, and then clicking Report. Reports can contain information about a Help file's topic titles, hash numbers, and \ul keywords.\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 9ML77Q} You can also request a report containing all the ASCII text in a Help file.
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} New test commands}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} New_test_command}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} Help Workshop;Help Workshop, new features;new features;new features, new test commands}
\b New test commands
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The following commands are available on the Help Workshop Test menu:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Contents File.  Checks the contents file for parameter limits, level coherence, nesting depth, duplicate elements, missing parameters, file availability, and other components. 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Send A Macro.  Enables you to see how a specific macro will perform in a Help file.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab WinHelp API.  Enables you to call a WinHelp API as if it were invoked from another program.
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Easy jumping to topics}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} .ZI3U2}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} dialog boxes;dialog boxes, Jump dialog box;Jump dialog box;new features;new features, easy jumping to topics;WinHelp,;WinHelp, new features}
\b Easy jumping to topics
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 A new Jump dialog box enables you to jump directly to a topic by specifying its \ul topic ID.\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 7.61TY} You can open the Jump dialog box by pressing \scaps ctrl+shift+j\plain\f1\fs16  in any topic window except \ul pop-up windows.\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 8XSV6X}
\par You can run any macro from the Jump dialog box by specifying a macro string, preceded by an exclamation point (!), instead of a topic ID. You can specify several macros by separating them with colons (:) or semicolons (;).
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Missing-bitmaps error message}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 8062D5}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} bitmaps;bitmaps, missing-bitmap error message;Help Workshop;Help Workshop, new features;messages;messages, missing-bitmap error message;missing-bitmap error message;new features;new features, missing-bitmaps error message}
\b Missing-bitmaps error
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 When Help Workshop cannot find a bitmap, it inserts its own bitmap in its place and includes the name of the missing bitmap. In this way, you can readily tell the difference between a missing bitmap and a bitmap that WinHelp cannot display.
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Improved error handling}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} A4US7A}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} error handling;Help Workshop;Help Workshop, new features;messages;messages, improved error handling;new features;new features, improved error handling}
\b Improved error handling
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Errors are no longer reported by levels. Accordingly, Help Workshop ignores the WARNINGS= option in the project (.hpj) file. Problems are now divided into Notes, Warnings, and Errors. All message identifiers begin with the letters "HC" and end with a 4-digit number, for example, "HC1000." You can look up a message identifier in this Help file for more information. Help Workshop displays:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Notes for problems that probably do not affect the Help file adversely.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Warnings if a Help file contains problems but can still be compiled.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Errors if the Help file cannot be compiled.
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} New monitoring of WinHelp messages}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} K0QAEU}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} Help Workshop;Help Workshop, new features;messages;messages, monitoring WinHelp messages;monitoring WinHelp messages;new features;new features, new monitoring of WinHelp messages;WinHelp messages}
\b New monitoring of WinHelp messages
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 You can now monitor the WinHelp messages that are processed while a Help file is running. Help Workshop displays information about WinHelp API calls, context-sensitive calls, \ul hotspot\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 7BM6.K} jumps, embedded window commands, which macros are being executed, which topics and \ul pop-up windows\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 8XSV6X} are current, and which configuration (.gid) file is being read. To access this feature, click the View menu in Help Workshop, and then click WinHelp Messages.
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Help file search path}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 12CTJPQ}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} new features;new features, Help file search path;WinHelp,;WinHelp, new features}
\b Help file search path
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 WinHelp now searches for Help files in the following locations, in the order listed.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab If a path is specified, WinHelp first searches for the file in the specified path. If the file is not found, the path is removed and the following locations are searched.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The folder of the current Help file.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The current folder.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The System subfolder of the Windows folder.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The Windows folder.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The folders listed in the PATH environment.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The location specified in the Winhelp.ini file.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The registry.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 If WinHelp cannot find a Help file, it displays a dialog box that enables the user to specify the location of the Help file. If the users finds the file, WinHelp will add the location information in the registry.
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Bitmap search path}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 13CIKRD}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} bitmaps,;bitmaps, search path;Help Workshop;Help Workshop, new features;new features;new features, bitmap search path;search path}
\b Bitmap search path
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Help Workshop now searches in three locations for a bitmap. If a path for a bitmap is specified, it first searches in that location. If it cannot find the bitmap, the path is removed and the following locations are searched:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The folder(s) specified in the project (.hpj) file for bitmaps
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The folder(s) specified in the project file for topic (.rtf) files
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The folder that contains the topic file in which the bitmap is specified
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The folder that contains the project file
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0077}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Training cards}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} NEW_WINHELP_TCARDS}
{\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} NEW_USER;NEW_WINHELP_TCARDS;whats_new}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} new features;new features, training cards;WinHelp,;WinHelp, new features}
\b Training cards
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Training cards are a new feature that enables WinHelp to determine which Help topic to display by communicating with another program. You can use this feature when the topic that should be displayed next is dependent on the actions a user takes in a program. For example, you could create a topic that contains only the first step of a procedure. When the user carries out that step, the program tells WinHelp to display the topic that contains the next step. 
\par When you use the training cards feature, you must work with a program developer to set it up in the program's code.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0065}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Help macros}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} MACRO_OVERVIEW}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} MACRO_OVERVIEW;new_macro}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} macros,;macros, about Help macros;running macros}
\b\fs24 Help macros
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 WinHelp provides a set of macros that enable you to control and customize Help functionality. Macro reference topics describe the macros included with WinHelp and explain how to use them in your Help file.
\par When creating your Help files, you can make your Help macros run by:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \f1\fs16 Placing macros in the project (.hpj) file, so WinHelp runs the macros whenever a user opens the Help file or a particular window type.
\par \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \f1\fs16 Placing macros in the project file, so WinHelp runs the macros whenever a user chooses a keyword from the Index tab in the Help Topics dialog box.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \f1\fs16 Placing macros in a topic footnote, so the macros run when a user displays that topic.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Placing macros in the contents (.cnt) file, so WinHelp runs the macros whenever a user double-clicks the associated page icon.
\par \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \f1\fs16 Configuring the menu bar and button bar, so WinHelp runs a macro when a user clicks the menu item or button.
\par \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \f1\fs16 Adding hotspots to your topic, so the macro runs when a user clicks the hotspot.
\par \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \f1\fs16 Using an external program to send a function call that prompts WinHelp to run a Help macro.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 Help macros are designed to imitate standard C-language format; however, standard Help macros do not support variables or expression evaluation.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \b Note
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab If you find that the standard Help macro set falls short of your ultimate goal, you can also create your own Help macros by using DLL functions.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("macro_syntax;macro_dlls;macro_error_chk;macro_return_vals;macro_from_app")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("macro_syntax;macro_dlls;macro_error_chk;macro_return_vals;macro_from_app")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0110}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Macro syntax}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} JLUVN5}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} macro_all;macro_syntax;new_macro}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} characters;characters, in macro statements;macros,;macros, syntax;syntax of macro statements}
\b\fs24 Macro syntax
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Help macro statements have two main components: the macro name and the macro parameters enclosed in parentheses. The macro name must be spelled exactly as it is shown in the syntax and the parameters must be used in the order they are given in the syntax. Parameters provide information for the macro; for example, the JumpId macro, which jumps to a topic with a specific topic ID, has parameters for the name of the Help file and the topic's ID.
\par All Help macros use the following syntax:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab MacroName(parameter1, parameter2, ...)
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 The opening parenthesis, closing parenthesis, and commas are required characters when included in the syntax statement for a macro. Macro names are not case sensitive. Help Workshop automatically changes macro names to their short form and removes all unnecessary white space. This enables you to use long names for macros in your topic (.rtf) file to enhance readability.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 Parameters can be text strings or numbers, and are separated by commas. If the final parameter for a macro is 0 or "", that parameter can be omitted.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 Some macros have no parameters, but the parentheses are still required.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 If you create custom macros, the macro name should begin with an alphabetic character, followed by any combination of alphabetic characters, numbers, or the underscore character, as in this example:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab PlayAudio()
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 You can include more than one macro in a macro string by placing a colon or semicolon between each macro. WinHelp runs the macros sequentially.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 Backslashes are used as an escape character, allowing you to include quotes as part of a macro parameter. If you need a literal backslash (for example, in a path specification) you must double the backslash for every level of macro nesting. For path specifications, use a forward slash instead of backslashes.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("syntax_more;conventions")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("syntax_more;conventions")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0111}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Macro error checking}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} LYON0T}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} macro_error_check}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} macros;macros, error checking}
\b\fs24 Macro error checking
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Help Workshop checks the validity of each macro included in a Help file as it compiles. If it finds an error, it displays an error message and stops processing that macro. Help Workshop checks whether you:\fs24 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2\fs18 \'b7\tab \f1\fs16 Spelled the macro's name correctly
\par \f2\fs18 \'b7\tab \f1\fs16 Specified the correct macro syntax (for example, the number of opening and closing parentheses and quotation marks should match)
\par \f2\fs18 \'b7\tab \f1\fs16 Specified the required number of macro parameters
\par \f2\fs18 \'b7\tab \f1\fs16 Specified types that match the parameter types (for example, you specified numeric parameters with numerals)
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0112}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Using string parameters}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 1VGFC2P}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} new_macro;syntax_more}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} macros,;macros, using string parameters;quotation marks;quotation marks, using in string parameters;string parameters;string parameters, using string parameters}
\b\fs24 Using string parameters
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Some macros require that string parameters be enclosed within quotation marks. In most cases, quotation marks are not necessary if the macro is in a topic (.rtf) or project (.hpj) file. Quotation marks can be either double quotation marks (") or matching single quotation marks(`').
\par Using single quotation marks eliminates ambiguities in situations where strings are nested within other strings.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Note
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab When calling a macro from an external program or from a contents (.cnt) file, string parameters must be enclosed within quotation marks, and numeric parameters must use a number.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0113}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Using numeric parameters}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} NVKD5D}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} syntax_more}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} macros,;macros, using numeric parameters;numeric parameters}
\b\fs24 Using numeric parameters
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 WinHelp and Help Workshop recognize decimal and hexadecimal numbers for numeric parameters. Use a prefix of 0x to indicate a hexadecimal number. For example, the following numbers both represent decimal 64:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab 64\line
0x40
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 To specify a negative number, add a minus sign before the number.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0114}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Using special characters in macro strings}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} KXPPDQ}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} syntax_more}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} characters;characters, in macro strings;macros,;macros, using special characters in strings;special characters}
\b\fs24 Using special characters in macro strings
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 To use the following characters within a macro as part of a parameter value, you must preface the character with a backslash. 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f3\fs10 \tab \f1\fs16 Double quotation mark (")
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Single opening quotation mark (`)
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Single closing quotation mark (')
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Backslash (\'5c)
\par Commas or parentheses do not need to be preceded by a backslash within a macro string.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \b Note
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab For every level of nested macros that you use, you must double the backslashes. To specify a filename path, use forward slashes rather then backslashes, as in c:/myapp/myapp.exe.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0115}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Making DLL calls in Help macros}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} _6X2RP}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} macro_dlls}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} DLLs;DLLs, calls in macros;macros,;macros, making DLL calls in}
\b\fs24 Making DLL calls in Help macros
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 You can call functions in a DLL if you inform WinHelp about the call by using the RegisterRoutine macro. For example, you could register the MessageBox function that is part of Windows with the following:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab [CONFIG]\line
RegisterRoutine("user", "MessageBox", "USSU")
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 Having registered this function, you could display a message box with a call similar to the following:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab MessageBox(hwndContext, "This is my message", "Help Message", 0)
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("DLL_WRITE_OVERVIEW;RegisterRoutine")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("DLL_WRITE_OVERVIEW;RegisterRoutine")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0116}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Return values in Help macros}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 2LS_6W1}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} macro_return_vals}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} macros,;macros, return values in;return values in macros}
\b\fs24 Return values in Help macros
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Generally, Help Workshop ignores return values in macros. However, the IsMark and IfThenElse macros can be used together to test a condition and run a macro if the condition evaluates to a non-zero, or true, value. The following example shows a typical use of IsMark and IfThenElse:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab IfThenElse(FileExist(myapp.exe), ExecFile(myapp.exe),  JumpId(how to install myapp))
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 The first parameter of the IfThenElse macro is a boolean value (zero or non-zero number). Since FileExist returns a boolean value, it can be used as the first parameter. Help runs this macro as follows:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 1\tab WinHelp runs the FileExist macro and obtains a boolean result from it (non-zero if the file exists, zero if it doesn\'92t).
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 2\tab The IfThenElse macro runs. WinHelp passes the value returned from FileExist to the first parameter and passes the ExecFile and JumpId macro strings to the second and third parameters.
\par 3\tab If the number passed to the first parameter is not zero, the IfThenElse macro runs the ExecFile macro; otherwise, it runs the JumpId macro.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("FileExist;ExecFile;IfThenElse;JumpId")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("FileExist;ExecFile;IfThenElse;JumpId")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0117}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Using DLL functions as Help macros}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} A_WUB0}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} macro_dlls}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} DLLs;DLLs, using DLL functions as macros;macros,;macros, using DLL functions as}
\b\fs24 Using DLL functions as Help macros
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 If you want to add a feature to your Help file that WinHelp does not support, and you have programming experience for Windows, you can develop custom extensions to support the functions you need. You can use calls to functions in the DLLs as Help macros by registering the functions in the project (.hpj) file using the RegisterRoutine macro.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("DLL_WRITE_OVERVIEW;registerroutine")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("DLL_WRITE_OVERVIEW;registerroutine")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0066}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Calling macros from a contents file}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 1_IUN22}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} macro_from_cnt}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} calling macros;contents files;contents files, calling macros from;macros,;macros, calling from contents files}
\b\fs24 Calling macros from a contents file
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 When you call a macro from a contents (.cnt) file, you cannot use Help Workshop to turn macros into a format that WinHelp can understand. This means you must use the short name for the macro, use quotation marks around all string parameters, use numeric values for numeric parameters, and supply all the parameters for a macro . You cannot omit most parameters as you can in your topic (.rtf) file. The only parameters you can omit are trailing arguments that would have a value of 0 or "".
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("macro_from_app ")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("macro_from_app ")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0118}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Calling macros from a program}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 1_IUL3Y}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} macro_from_app}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} calling macros;macros,;macros, calling from program;programs, calling macros from}
\b\fs24 Calling macros from a program
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 A program can send a HELP_COMMAND parameter in the WinHelp API call that specifies a macro to run. This WinHelp call would look like the following: 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \b \tab \plain\f1\fs16 WinHelp(hwndProgram, "HelpFile[>WindowName]", HELP_COMMAND, "macro");
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 The following example uses the ALink macro in the Myhelp.hlp file:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295\tx445 \tab case IDM_HELP_KEYBOARD:\line
\tab WinHelp (hwnd, "myhelp.hlp", HELP_COMMAND, (DWORD)  "AL(`HELP_KEYBOARD\'5c\'92)");\line
\tab return 0;
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295\tx445 When you call a macro from a program, you cannot use Help Workshop to turn macros into a format that WinHelp can understand. This means you must use the short name for the macro, use quotation marks around all string parameters, use numeric values for numeric parameters, and supply all the parameters for a macro . You cannot omit most parameters as you can in your topic (.rtf) file. The only parameters you can omit are trailing arguments that would have a value of 0 or "".
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,KL("winhelp")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("winhelp")}\uldb 
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0119}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Nested macros and nested string parameters}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} E8ZVQL}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} macro_nested}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} macros,;macros, using nested macros;macros, using nested string parameters;string parameters,;string parameters, nested}
\plain\f1\b\fs24 Nested Macros and Nested String Parameters
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Help Workshop supports nested macros, a macro that is included in another macro as a parameter value. Because nested macros often have their own string parameters, you must frequently specify a string enclosed within another string.
\par For example, the following macro creates a button called Time that uses the ExecFile macro as a parameter. When the user clicks the button, the Microsoft Windows Clock program starts. Because the ExecFile macro takes a string as its first parameter, the string is enclosed in single quotation marks:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab CreateButton("btn_time", "&Time", "ExecFile(`clock', 0)")
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 If the nested macro has any string parameters, they must have quotation marks that are different from the enclosing macro quotation marks. In other words, if double quotation marks enclose a macro, you must enclose any nested strings in single quotation marks.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 You can also use single quotation marks for the outermost parameters. You can avoid confusion with nested string parameters by using single quotation marks for all string parameters. Just be sure to match the opening and closing quotation marks correctly.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 If a nested macro contains a path, be sure to double each backslash for every level that the macro is nested, starting with double the typical number of backslashes in a macro nested one level. Double the backslashes again for a macro nested two levels, and so on. Alternatively, you might be able to use forward slashes in place of backslashes. You do not need to double forward slashes in paths in nested macros. Forward slashes, however, are not compatible with all networks. Make sure forward slashes are compatible with your network before using them.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("ExecFile")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("ExecFile")}\uldb 
\par \plain\f1\fs16 
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0093}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} To create a topic file}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} PRO_CREATE_TOPIC_FILE}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} PRO_CREATE_TOPIC_FILE}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} creating;creating, topic files;Help topics,;Help topics, creating;topic files;topic files, creating;topics,;topics, creating}
\b To create a topic file
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 1\tab Open a new file in a word processor or text editor that can handle rich text format.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 2\tab Write your individual topics, separating each topic with a hard page break.
\par 3\tab Add appropriate footnotes at the beginning of the file.
\par \tab See Related Topics below.
\par 4\tab Save the file in rich text format with the .rtf filename extension.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \b Tip
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab Before creating a complete topic file, test the compatibility of your word processor or text editor by compiling a short test topic file.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \{button ,AL(`POP_OVERVIEW_TOPIC;BAS_TOPIC_FOOTNOTE;PRO_ADD_TOPIC_ID;PRO_ADD_TITLE;PRO_ADD_INDEX_ENTRIES')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`POP_OVERVIEW_TOPIC;BAS_TOPIC_FOOTNOTE;;PRO_ADD_TOPIC_ID;PRO_ADD_TITLE;PRO_ADD_INDEX_ENTRIES')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0094}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} To add a topic ID to a topic}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} PRO_ADD_TOPIC_ID}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} PRO_ADD_TOPIC_ID;PRO_TOPIC}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} # (number sign) footnotes;adding;adding, footnotes to topics;footnotes;footnotes, adding to topics;footnotes, number sign (#);footnotes, topic ID footnote;number sign (#) footnote;topic IDs;topic IDs, adding to topics;topics,;topics, adding footnotes to}
\b To add a topic ID to a topic
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 1\tab Place the insertion point at the beginning of the topic you want to add a \ul topic ID\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 7.61TY} to.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 2\tab Insert a number sign (#) as a footnote mark.
\par 3\tab Type the topic ID name as the footnote text, observing these restrictions:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li455\ri125\fi-155\tx455 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Topic IDs can contain spaces, but avoid leading and trailing spaces.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Do not use reserved characters (# = + @ * % !).
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Use no more than 255 characters.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Do not begin a topic ID with a number if the ID will also be used in the [MAP] section.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx455 \b Notes
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab To enable Help Workshop to track errors, start all topics IDs that will be called from a program with IDH_ . Help Workshop will list any undefined topics that begin with IDH_ in the [MAP] section of the project file, and will warn of any topic of any IDH_ topic IDs that do not appear in the [MAP] section.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab If you want users to jump to a specific location in a topic, you can insert a topic ID at that location. 
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0095}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} To add a title footnote to a topic}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} PRO_ADD_TITLE}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} PRO_ADD_TITLE;PRO_TOPIC}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} $ (dollar sign) footnotes;adding;adding, footnotes to topics;dollar sign ($) footnote;footnotes;footnotes, adding to topics;footnotes, dollar sign ($);footnotes, title footnote;title footnotes;topic title footnotes;topics,;topics, adding footnotes to}
\b To add a title footnote to a topic
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 1\tab Place the insertion point at the beginning of the topic you want to add a\ul  title footnote\plain\f1\fs16 {\v ALPG0Y} to.
\par 2\tab Insert a dollar sign ($) as a footnote mark.
\par 3\tab Type the title as the footnote text
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \b Note
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab Titles can have up to 255 characters (127 for DBCS characters). Spaces count as characters.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0096}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} To mark a topic as an ALink target}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} PRO_ADD_KEYWORD}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} PRO_ADD_KEYWORD;PRO_TOPIC}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} adding;adding, footnotes to topics;A-footnotes;A-keywords;ALinks;ALinks, marking a topic as an ALink target;footnotes;footnotes, adding to topics;footnotes, A-footnote;keywords;keywords, adding A-keywords to topics;topic keywords;topics,;topics, adding footnotes to}
\b To mark a topic as an ALink target
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 1\tab Place the insertion point at the beginning of the topic.
\par 2\tab Insert an A as a footnote mark.
\par 3\tab Type one or more keywords as the footnote text, observing the following restrictions:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li455\ri125\fi-155\tx455 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Separate keywords with a semicolon.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Spaces before and after keywords are removed.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Do not use carriage returns.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Use no more than 255 characters per keyword.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx455 \b Notes
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab The \ul ALink\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 7V8V.U} macro searches for topics containing an A-keyword.\f2 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \'b7\f1 \tab Keywords are case-sensitive, but Help Workshop assumes that two keywords that differ only in case are meant to be the same keyword. Help Workshop changes one of the keywords to agree with the other and displays a warning message.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0097}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} To create index entries for a topic}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 25J8VDH}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} PRO_ADD_KEYWORD;PRO_TOPIC}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} adding;adding, footnotes to topics;adding, index entries;creating;creating, index entries;footnotes;footnotes, adding to topics;footnotes, K-footnote;index entries, creating;index,;index, creating entries for;keywords;keywords, adding K-keywords to topics;K-footnotes;K-keywords;topic keywords;topics,;topics, adding footnotes to}
\b To create index entries for a topic
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 1\tab Place the insertion point at the beginning of the topic.
\par 2\tab Insert a K as a footnote mark.
\par 3\tab Type a list of keywords as the corresponding footnote text. Observe the following restrictions:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li455\ri125\fi-155\tx455 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Separate keywords with a semicolon.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Spaces before and after keywords are removed.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Do not use carriage returns.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Use no more than 255 characters per keyword.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx455 \b Notes
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab The \ul KLink\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 7V8V.U} macro searches for topics containing a K-keyword.\f2 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \'b7\f1 \tab Keywords are case-sensitive, but Help Workshop assumes that two keywords that differ only in case are meant to be the same keyword. Help Workshop changes one of the keywords to agree with the other and displays a warning message.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \{button ,AL(`BAS_ADDING_KEYWORDS;PRO_ADD_LEVEL2_KEYWORDS;BAS_WRITE_INDEX')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`BAS_ADDING_KEYWORDS;PRO_ADD_LEVEL2_KEYWORDS;BAS_WRITE_INDEX')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0098}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} To create second-level index entries for a topic}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} PRO_ADD_LEVEL2_KEYWORDS}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} PRO_ADD_LEVEL2_KEYWORDS}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} adding;adding, index entries;creating;creating, index entries;index entries, creating;index,;index, creating entries for;keywords;keywords, adding K-keywords to topics;K-keywords;second-level index entries;topic keywords}
\b To create second-level index entries for a topic
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 1\tab In the K-footnote of a topic, type the first-level keyword entry followed by a semicolon (;).
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 2\tab Immediately after the semicolon, type the first-level entry again, followed by a comma (,) or a colon (:), a space, the second-level entry, and a semicolon.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \b Example
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 The following K-footnote text results in the index entries shown below it:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 macro; macro, library; macro, automatic; macro, complex; macro, simple
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295\tx445 \tab macro\line
\tab \tab automatic\line
\tab \tab complex\line
\tab \tab library\line
\tab \tab simple
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295\tx445 \b Notes
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab Entries appear alphabetically in the index, regardless of their order in footnote text.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Spaces before and after keywords are removed.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab You can change the characters you use to identify second-level index entries. For more information, click Related Topics.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \{button ,AL(`PRO_SPECIFY_SEP_CHAR;PRO_ADD_INDEX_ENTRIES;BAS_WRITE_INDEX;BAS_ADDING_KEYWORDS')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`PRO_SPECIFY_SEP_CHAR;PRO_ADD_INDEX_ENTRIES;BAS_WRITE_INDEX;BAS_ADDING_KEYWORDS')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0099}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} To add a topic to a browse sequence}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} PRO_ADD_BROWSE_CODE}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} PRO_ADD_BROWSE_CODE;PRO_TOPIC}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} + (plus sign) footnotes;adding;adding, browse sequences;adding, footnotes to topics;browse sequences;footnotes;footnotes, adding to topics;footnotes, browse sequence footnote;footnotes, plus sign (+);plus sign ($) footnote;topics,;topics, adding footnotes to;topics, adding to a browse sequence}
\b To add a topic to a browse sequence
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 1\tab At the beginning of the topic that you want to include in a \ul browse sequence,\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 1SRKR1R} insert a plus sign (+) as a footnote mark.
\par 2\tab Type a \ul browse code\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 6KLNWH} as the footnote text. Observe the following restrictions:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li455\ri125\fi-155\tx455 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Do not use reserved characters (# = + @ * % !) or spaces.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Use no more than 50 characters.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx455 \b Notes
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab To use browse sequences, you must also activate the browse buttons in the project file.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab WinHelp creates an auto-browse sequence for topics to which you have added a browse footnote (+) but for which you have specified no browse code.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \b Tips
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab  When using numbers in browse codes, include placeholding zeros (001, 002, 003, and so on).
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab To make it easier to add topics later, use the same name, but no numbers for each browse footnote in a sequence. Help Workshop will arrange your browse sequence in which the order that the topics appear. To change the browse sequence, simply change the order in which topics appear in your .rtf file.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab If your Help file has only one browse sequence, use "auto" as the browse code. Help Workshop automatically creates a browse sequence based on the order in which topics appear in your topic files.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \{button ,AL(`PRO_ADD_BROWSE_BUTTONS;BrowseButtons;BAS_ADDING_BROWSE_CODE;browse_seq')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`PRO_ADD_BROWSE_BUTTONS;BrowseButtons;BAS_ADDING_BROWSE_CODE;browse_seq')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:009a}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} To mark a topic so you can exclude or include it in a Help file}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} PRO_INSERT_BUILD_TAG}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} PRO_INSERT_BUILD_TAG;PRO_TOPIC}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} * (asterisk) footnotes;adding;adding, footnotes to topics;asterisk (*) footnote;build tags;build tags, adding to topics;footnotes;footnotes, adding to topics;footnotes, asterisk (*);footnotes, build tag footnote;topics,;topics, adding footnotes to;topics, marking to exclude or include}
\b To mark a topic so you can exclude or include it in a Help file
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 1\tab Place the insertion point at the beginning of the topic, ahead of any other footnote marks.
\par 2\tab Insert an asterisk (*) as a footnote mark.
\par 3\tab Type one or more \ul build tags\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 12MF62E} as the corresponding footnote text. Separate build tags with a semicolon.
\par 4\tab In your project (.hpj) file, make sure you have specified which topics to include in a build. For more information, click Related Topics.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \b Notes
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab Build tags are not case sensitive.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Topics without build tags are always included in a build, as are all topics that are not expressly excluded from a build in your project file.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \{button ,AL(`PRO_HPJ_BUILD_TAGS;BAS_SPECIFY_BUILD;BUILD;BUILDTAGS')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`PRO_HPJ_BUILD_TAGS;BAS_SPECIFY_BUILD;BUILD;BUILDTAGS')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:009b}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} To specify the type of window to display a topic in}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} PRO_ADD_WINDOW_TYPE}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} PRO_ADD_WINDOW_TYPE}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} > (greater-than sign);> (greater-than sign), footnote;adding;adding, footnotes to topics;footnotes;footnotes, adding to topics;footnotes, greater-than sign (>);footnotes, window type footnote;greater-than sign (>);greater-than sign (>), footnote;topics,;topics, adding footnotes to;topics, specifying window type for;window types;windows,;windows, specifying type}
\b To specify the type of window to display a topic in
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 1\tab Place the insertion point at the beginning of the topic.
\par 2\tab Insert a greater-than sign (>) as a footnote mark.
\par 3\tab Type the name of the window type, as defined in your project (.hpj) file.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \b Notes
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab This footnote specifies the window type a topic will appear in when the topic is opened from the Index or Find tab, or from an \ul ALink\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 7V8V.U} or \ul KLink\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 1R9H33X} macro.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Window types must be defined in your project file. For more information, click Related Topics.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \{button ,AL(`BAS_ADD_WINDOW_TYPE;BAS_HPJ_CREATE_WINDOW;PRO_HPJ_CREATE_WINDOW;PRO_HPJ_CUSTOMIZE_WINDOW')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`BAS_ADD_WINDOW_TYPE;BAS_HPJ_CREATE_WINDOW;PRO_HPJ_CREATE_WINDOW;PRO_HPJ_CUSTOMIZE_WINDOW')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:009c}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} To specify a macro to run when a topic is opened}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} PRO_ADD_MACRO_COMMAND}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} PRO_ADD_MACRO_COMMAND;PRO_TOPIC}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} ! (exclamation point);! (exclamation point), footnote;adding;adding, footnotes to topics;entry macros;exclamation point (!);exclamation point (!), footnote;footnotes;footnotes, adding to topics;footnotes, entry macro footnote;footnotes, exclamation point (!);macros,;macros, entry macros;macros, running when a topic is opened;running macros;topics,;topics, adding footnotes to;topics, specifying entry macros for}
\b To specify a macro to run when a topic is opened
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 1\tab Place the insertion point at the beginning of the topic in which you want the \ul entry macro\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 2BTJW15} to run. 
\par 2\tab Insert an exclamation point (!) as a footnote mark. 
\par 3\tab Type the entry macro commands as the corresponding footnote text. Observe the following restrictions:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li455\ri125\fi-155\tx455 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Separate macros with a semicolon
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Do not use carriage returns
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \{button ,AL(`MACRO_REF_OVR')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`MACRO_REF_OVR')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:009d}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} To add a nonscrolling region to a topic}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} PRO_NONSCROLL}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} PRO_NONSCROLL;PRO_TOPIC}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} adding;adding, nonscrolling regions to topics;Help topics,;Help topics, nonscrolling regions in;nonscrolling regions;pop-up windows;pop-up windows, avoiding nonscrolling regions in;topics,;topics, adding nonscrolling regions to}
\b To add a nonscrolling region to a topic
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 1\tab Make sure that the paragraph or paragraphs you want to be in the \ul nonscrolling region\plain\f1\fs16 {\v _B12QW} are at the top of the topic. 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 2\tab Apply the Keep With Next paragraph style (or equivalent) to the paragraphs.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \b Notes
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab Users can select (for copying or printing purposes) either the scrolling region or the nonscrolling region of a topic, but not both. However, both scrolling and nonscrolling regions are copied when users click a topic using their right mouse button, and then click Copy.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Do not add nonscrolling regions to topics that will be displayed in pop-up windows.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab You can specify different background colors for nonscrolling and scrolling regions by opening your project (.hpj) file in Help Workshop, clicking the Windows button, and then clicking the Color tab.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab If you use a transparent bitmap in both the scrolling region and the non-scrolling region of the same topic, the transparent area of both bitmaps is displayed using the background color of the scrolling region.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:009e}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} To prevent a line of text from wrapping}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} PRO_NON_WRAP}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} PRO_NON_WRAP;PRO_TOPIC}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} line wrap, preventing;text,;text, preventing word wrap;word wrap, preventing;wrapping text, preventing}
\b To prevent a line of text from wrapping
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 1\tab Place the insertion point anywhere in the line that you do not want to wrap.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 2\tab Apply the Keep Lines Together paragraph style (or equivalent). 
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \b Note
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab If the text of the paragraph is too wide for the window, WinHelp adds a horizontal scroll bar.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} ALPG0Y}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 The title footnote specifies the title of the topic as it appears in the Topics Found dialog box, the Bookmark dialog box, the History window, and the Find tab.
\par \page
