{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0034}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} InsertItem macro}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} InsertItem}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} InsertItem;MACROS_MENU}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} InsertItem macro;macros,;macros, InsertItem;menu items;menu items, inserting at given position}
\b\fs24 InsertItem macro
\par \pard\keepn\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \fs16 InsertItem(\plain\f1\fs16 menu-ID\b ,\plain\f1\fs16 \'a0item-ID\b ,\plain\f1\fs16 \'a0item-name\b ,\plain\f1\fs16 \'a0macro\b ,\plain\f1\fs16 \'a0position\b )\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Inserts a menu item at a given position on an existing menu. The menu can either be one you create by using the InsertMenu macro or a standard WinHelp menu.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1575\ri125\fi-1455\brdrb\brdrs\tx1575 \b Parameter\tab Description\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1575\ri125\fi-1455\tx1575 menu-ID\tab Identifies either a standard WinHelp menu or a menu previously created by the ExtInsertMenu or InsertMenu macro.
\par item-ID\tab Specifies the name that WinHelp uses internally to identify the menu item.
\par item-name\tab Specifies the name that WinHelp displays on the menu for the item. This name is case-sensitive. An ampersand (&) before a character in the name identifies it as the item's accelerator.
\par macro\tab Specifies a macro or macro string to run when a user clicks the menu item. The macro must be enclosed in quotation marks. If multiple macros are specified in the project file, separate the macros by using semicolons or colons.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1575\ri125\fi-1455\tx1575 position\tab Specifies the integer position of the menu item in the menu. Position 0 is the first or topmost position on the menu.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1575 \b Comments
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1575 \plain\f1\fs16 The item ID parameter can be used in a subsequent EnableItem, ExtAbleItem, DisableItem or DeleteItem macro to remove or disable the item or to change the operations that the item performs in certain topics.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1575 WinHelp ignores this macro if it is run in a secondary window.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1575 The specified accelerator keys must be unique. If a key conflicts with other accelerator keys, WinHelp displays the error message "Unable to add item" and ignores the macro.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1575 \b Example
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1575 \plain\f1\fs16 The following macro inserts a menu item labeled \plain\f0\fs16 \'93\f1 Tools\plain\f0\fs16 \'94\f1  as the third item on a menu whose identifier is \plain\f0\fs16 \'93\f1 MNU_BKS\plain\f0\fs16 \'94\f1 . Selecting the menu item causes a jump to a topic located in the Tls.hlp file whose topic ID is "tls1":
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab InsertItem(mnu_bks, m_tls, &Tools, JI(`tls.hlp', `tls1'), 3)
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \{button ,AL("MACRO_REF_MENU;macro_all;AppendItem;ChangeItemBinding;DeleteItem;DisableItem;EnableItem;ExtAbleItem;ExtInsertItem;InsertMenu;ResetMenu;REF_STD_MENU;CONFIG")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("MACRO_REF_MENU;macro_all;InsertMenu;AppendItem;ChangeItemBinding;DeleteItem;DisableItem;EnableItem;ExtAbleItem;ExtInsertItem;ResetMenu;REF_STD_MENU;CONFIG")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0035}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} InsertMenu macro}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} InsertMenu}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} InsertMenu;MACROS_MENU}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} InsertMenu macro;macros,;macros, InsertMenu;menus;menus, inserting in WinHelp menu bar}
\b\fs24 InsertMenu macro
\par \pard\keepn\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \fs16 InsertMenu(\plain\f1\fs16 menu-ID\b ,\plain\f1\fs16 \'a0menu-name\b ,\plain\f1\fs16 \'a0menu-position\b )\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Inserts a new menu in the WinHelp menu bar.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1725\ri125\fi-1605\brdrb\brdrs\tx1725 \b Parameter\tab Description\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1725\ri125\fi-1605\tx1725 menu-ID\tab Specifies the name that WinHelp uses internally to identify the menu. This identifier can be used by the AppendItem, ExtInsertItem, and ExtInsertMenu macros to add macros to the menu.
\par menu-name\tab Specifies the name that WinHelp displays on the menu bar. An ampersand (&) before a character in the name identifies it as the menu's accelerator.
\par menu-position\tab Specifies the position on the menu bar of the new menu name. This parameter must be an integer. Positions are numbered from left to right, with position 0 being the left-most menu.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1725 \b Comments
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1725 \plain\f1\fs16 The specified accelerator keys must be unique. If a key conflicts with other accelerator keys, WinHelp displays the error message "Unable to add menu" and ignores the macro.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1725 WinHelp ignores this macro if it is run in a secondary window.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1725 \b Example
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1725 \plain\f1\fs16 The following macro adds a menu named \plain\f0\fs16 \'93\f1 Utilities\plain\f0\fs16 \'94\f1  to the WinHelp program. The label \plain\f0\fs16 \'93\f1 Utilities\plain\f0\fs16 \'94\f1  appears as the fourth item on the WinHelp menu bar. The user can press ALT+U to open the menu.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab InsertMenu(IDM_UTIL, &Utilities, 3)
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \{button ,AL("MACRO_REF_MENU;macro_all;AppendItem;ExtInsertItem;ExtInsertMenu;ResetMenu")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("MACRO_REF_MENU;macro_all;AppendItem;ExtInsertItem;ExtInsertMenu;ResetMenu")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0036}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} IsBook macro}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} IsBook}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} IsBook;new_macro}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} IsBook macro;macros,;macros, IsBook;WinHelp,;WinHelp, determining how WinHelp is running}
\b\fs24 IsBook macro
\par \pard\keepn\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \fs16 IsBook()\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Determines whether WinHelp is running as a standalone system (a double-clicked book icon), or if it is being run from a program. This macro can be used as the first parameter of a IfThen or IfThenElse macro to take specific action depending on whether the current Help file is being run as a double-clicked book icon.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Parameters\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 This macro does not take any parameters.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Comments
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The IsBook macro returns a value of TRUE if WinHelp is being run as a book; otherwise, the macro returns FALSE.
\par The IsBook macro is new for WinHelp version 4.0.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb25\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \{button ,AL("macro_all;IfThen;IfThenElse ")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("macro_all;IfThen;IfThenElse ")}
\par \page
