{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0055}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} ShellExecute macro}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} ShellExecute}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} new_macro;ShellExecute}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} macros,;macros, ShellExecute;opening files;printing;SE macro;ShellExecute macro}
\b\fs24 ShellExecute macro
\par \pard\keepn\keep\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \fs16 ShellExecute(\plain\f1\fs16 filename\b ,\plain\f1\fs16 \'a0[options[\b ,\plain\f1\fs16 \'a0show-flag[\b ,\plain\f1\fs16 \'a0operation[\b ,\plain\f1\fs16 \'a0path[\b ,\'a0\plain\f1\fs16 topic-id]]]]]\b )\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Opens or prints the specified file.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1575\ri125\fi-1455\brdrb\brdrs\tx1575 \b Parameter\tab Description\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1575\ri125\fi-1455\tx1575 filename\tab Specifies the name of the file to open.
\par options\tab Specifies parameters passed to the program when the filename parameter specifies an executable (.exe) file. If the filename parameter specifies a document file, this parameter is empty.
\par show-flag\tab Specifies how the program is shown when it is opened. If the filename parameter specifies a document file, this parameter should be zero.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li3715\ri125\fi-2155\brdrb\brdrs\tx3595 \b Value\tab Meaning
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li3825\ri125\fi-2275\tx3595 \plain\f1\fs16 HIDE (0)\tab Hides the window.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li3595\ri125\fi-2045\tx3595 MAXIMIZE (3)\tab Activates the window and maximizes it.
\par MINIMIZE_ACTIVATE (6)\tab Activates the window and minimizes it.
\par MINIMIZE_NOACTIVE (7)\tab Minimizes the window, but WinHelp keeps the focus.
\par NOACTIVATE (4)\tab Displays a window in its current state, but WinHelp keeps the focus. (If the window was minimized before this call, it stays minimized.)
\par NORMAL (5)\tab Activates the window and displays it in its current size and position.
\par RESTORE (9)\tab Restores the window to its original size and position if the window is minimized or maximized.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1575\ri125\fi-1455\tx1575 
\par operation\tab Specifies the operation to perform. This parameter can be "open" or "opencpl" or "print". If this parameter is not specified, "open" is the default value.
\par path\tab Specifies the default folder. Use \plain\f0\fs16 \'93\'94\f1  if you do not need to specify a default folder.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1575\ri125\fi-1445\tx1575 topic-id\tab Specifies the ID of the topic to display if this macro fails.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1575 \b Comments
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1575 \plain\f1\fs16 The filename can be a document file or an executable file. If it is a document file, this function opens or prints it, depending on the value of the operation parameter. If it is an executable file, this function opens it, even if the operation parameter specifies print.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1575 If no path is specified with the filename, WinHelp searches the following locations in the order listed:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The folder in which the Winhelp.exe program is located
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The folder that contains the current Help file
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The System subfolder in the Windows folder
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The Windows folder
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The PATH environment
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The registry
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 The ShellExecute macro calls the Windows ShellExecute function.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 Help Workshop automatically converts the ShellExecute macro to SE, which is the only form of this macro that WinHelp can use.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 The ShellExecute macro is new for WinHelp version 4.0.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,KL("ExecFile macro;ControlPanel macro;macros, syntax;ShellExecute")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!KL("ExecFile macro;ControlPanel macro;macros, syntax;ShellExecute")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0056}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} ShortCut macro}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} ShortCut}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} new_macro;ShortCut}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} macros,;macros, ShortCut;ShortCut macro}
\b\fs24 ShortCut macro
\par \pard\keepn\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \fs16 ShortCut(\plain\f1\fs16 window-class\b ,\plain\f1\fs16 \'a0program[\b ,\plain\f1\fs16 \'a0wParam[\b ,\plain\f1\fs16 \'a0lParam[\b ,\plain\f1\fs16 \'a0topic-ID]]]\b )\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Runs the specified program if it is not already running. If the specified program is running, WinHelp activates it. If the wParam parameter is specified, a WM_COMMAND message with the specified wParam and lParam values are sent to the program.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1575\ri125\fi-1455\brdrb\brdrs\tx1575 \b Parameter\tab Description\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1575\ri125\fi-1455\tx1575 window-class\tab Specifies the class name of a top level window of the program. WinHelp uses this class name to determine if the program is already running.
\par program\tab Specifies the executable name of the program. This is the name of the program that runs if the window class name cannot be found. The .exe extension does not need to be included.
\par wParam\tab Specifies the first argument to the WM_COMMAND message that is sent to the program. If this value is not specified, the program is started, but no message is sent and the program is not activated.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1575\ri125\fi-1455\tx1575 lParam\tab Specifies the second argument to the WM_COMMAND message.
\par topic-ID\tab Specifies the topic ID of the topic to jump to if the program cannot be found. If this parameter is not specified, WinHelp displays a message box indicating that the program could not be found. If it is specified and no filename is included, the filename specified by the :Base command in the contents (.cnt) file is used. If there is no associated contents file, the current Help file is used. To specify a specific filename, the topic ID should end with an '@' character and the name of the Help file.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1575 \b Comments
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1575 \plain\f1\fs16 If you need to include a topic ID, but do not want to send the program any messages, you can either use -1 for the wParam argument and 0 for the lParam argument, or you can simply include the commas without specifying the values for the arguments as follows:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab ShortCut(class_name, myapp, , , topic-ID)
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 Some programs, such as the Microsoft Visual C++ compiler (MSVC), cannot receive a message in the same call that runs them. In this case, you must first call the ShortCut macro without specifying wParam or lParam. You can then call this macro again and send the wParam and lParam messages. Note that the second time you call this macro, you can use an empty string ("") for the program name.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 Help Workshop automatically converts the ShortCut macro to SH, which is the only form of this macro that WinHelp can use.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 The ShortCut macro is new for WinHelp version 4.0.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \b Example
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 The following example copies the current topic to the Clipboard, runs or activates Notepad, and pastes the text from the Clipboard into Notepad:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab CopyTopic():ShortCut(notepad, notepad, 0x0302)
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
