{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0103}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} [MACROS] section}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 17TGWCQ}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} HPJ_REF;MACROS;new_hpj}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} MACROS section of project files;project files;project files, [MACROS] section}
\b\fs24 [MACROS] section
\par \pard\keepn\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \fs16 [MACROS]\line
\plain\f1\fs16 keyword[;keyword1]\line
macro[;macro1]\line
title
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 The\b  \plain\f1\fs16 [MACROS] section associates macros with keywords. These macros run when a user selects the specified keyword in the index.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1625\ri125\fi-1495\brdrb\brdrs\tx1615 \b Parameter\tab Description\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1625\ri125\fi-1495\tx1615 keyword\tab Specifies the keyword or keywords to associate with the macro(s) on the following line. Use semicolons to separate keywords.
\par macro\tab Specifies which macro to run when a keyword from the preceding line is selected in the index. Separate multiple macros using colons.
\par title\tab Specifies the title to display in the Topics Found dialog box when the selected keyword is linked to two or more Help topics. If no title is to display, leave this line blank. Title text is limited to 255 characters.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 \b Comments
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 \plain\f1\fs16 Help Workshop uses semicolons as keyword and macro delimiters in the [MACROS] section, so you cannot use comments in this section.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 There is no limit to the number of three-line keyword macro definitions you can specify in this section, however you cannot use the same keyword more than once.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 You cannot include a file in the [MACROS] section. If you want to include a list of keyword macro definitions, you must include a file (at the end of the [OPTIONS] section) that also contains the [MACROS] section heading.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 It is strongly recommended that you use only Help Workshop to create or modify the [MACROS] section.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 The [MACROS] section is new.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0104}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} [MAP] section}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} RB_JT}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} HPJ_REF;MAP}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} MAP section of project files;project files;project files, [MAP] section}
\b\fs24 [MAP] section
\par \pard\keepn\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \fs16 [MAP]\line
\plain\f1\fs16 topic-id          numeric value
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 The [MAP] section associates topic IDs (or aliases) with context numbers for context-sensitive Help. The context number corresponds to a value the parent program passes to WinHelp to display a particular topic.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1625\ri125\fi-1495\brdrb\brdrs\tx1615 \b Parameter\tab Description\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1625\ri125\fi-1495\tx1615 topic-id\tab Specifies the topic ID of a topic in the Help file. The ID can be any combination of characters, except spaces, and must also be specified in a topic ID footnote (#) in some topic in the Help file.
\par numeric value\tab Specifies the context number to associate with the topic ID. If the number begins with a digit other than zero (0), Help Workshop interprets it as decimal. If it begins with a zero (0) followed by the letter X, it is interpreted as hexadecimal. If it begins with a zero (0) followed by a digit, it is interpreted as octal.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 \b Comments
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 \plain\f1\fs16 You must use at least one space or tab between the context number and the topic ID. You can precede the topic ID with #define as in:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab #define IDH_MYHELP\tab 12
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 You can include C header files in the [MAP] section using the #include statement as in:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab #include myhelp.h
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 When you include a C header file, observe the following:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab You can use C-style comments (/* and */). The comments can occur anywhere in the line as in:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab #define topic-id    context-number     /* comment */
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab You can use C++-style comments (//) with the #define statement. Everything from // to the end of the line will be ignored.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Help Workshop supports 32-bit constants in #define statements. It also accepts (as 32-bit constants) numbers that end with L and are accepted by the C compiler for a long constant:
\par \tab #define vscroll      1234000L
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Help Workshop does not perform arithmetic on the object of the #define statement. It does not support the following forms of #define:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab #define A  1\line
#define B  (A+1)\line
#define C  (A+2)
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Help Workshop accepts only #define statements; it does not support other forms such as #ifdef and #endif.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES;HPJ_SECTIONS;ALIAS')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES;HPJ_SECTIONS;ALIAS')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0105}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} MAPFONTSIZE}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 12DOBQV}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} HPJ_REF;MAPFONTSIZE}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} fonts,;fonts, mapping;MAPFONTSIZE option of project files;project files;project files, MAPFONTSIZE option}
\b\fs24 MAPFONTSIZE
\par \pard\keepn\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \fs16 MAPFONTSIZE=\plain\f1\fs16 m[-n]:p
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 You specify the MAPFONTSIZE option in the [OPTIONS] section of the project (.hpj) file. MAPFONTSIZE maps the font sizes specified in topic (.rtf) files to different sizes when they are displayed in the Help window. You can use one font size in your topic files and have Help Workshop change the font so that it is a different size when the Help topic is displayed. 
\par This option is especially useful if there is a significant size difference between the authoring display and the intended user display.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1625\ri125\fi-1495\brdrb\brdrs\tx1615 \b Parameter\tab Description\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1625\ri125\fi-1495\tx1615 m[-n]\tab Specifies the size of the source font. This parameter is either a single point size or a range of point sizes, as indicated by the optional parameter n, which specifies a font range to be mapped. A range of point sizes consists of the low and high point sizes separated by a hyphen (-). If a range is specified, all fonts in the range are changed to the size specified by the p parameter.
\par p\tab Specifies the size of the desired font for the Help file.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 \b Comment
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 \plain\f1\fs16 Although you can specify as many as five font ranges in the\b  \plain\f1\fs16 [OPTIONS] section of the project file, you can map only one font size or range with each MAPFONTSIZE statement. If you include more than one MAPFONTSIZE statement, the source font size or range that is specified in subsequent statements cannot overlap previous mappings.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 \b Examples
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 \plain\f1\fs16 The following example illustrates a correct use of the MAPFONTSIZE option, using two statements, in a project file:
\par \pard\keep\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab [OPTIONS]\line
MAPFONTSIZE=8:12            ; display all 8 pt. fonts as 12 pt.\line
MAPFONTSIZE=12-24:16     ; display fonts from 12 to 24 pts. as 16 pt.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 The following two statements show an incorrect use of the MAPFONTSIZE option because the second statement contains a point size already mapped in the preceding statement (14 falls in the 12-24 range):
\par \pard\keep\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab [OPTIONS]\line
MAPFONTSIZE=12-24:16\line
MAPFONTSIZE=14:20
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES;HPJ_SECTIONS;FORCEFONT')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES;HPJ_SECTIONS;FORCEFONT')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0106}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} MULTIKEY}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} K.Z2KQ}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} HPJ_REF;MULTIKEY}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} alternate index;footnotes;footnotes, specifying alternate character for keyword footnotes;index,;index, alternate;keyword table, alternate;MULTIKEY option in OPTIONS section;project files;project files, MULTIKEY option}
\b\fs24 MULTIKEY
\par \pard\keepn\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \fs16 MULTIKEY=\plain\f1\fs16 footnote-character
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 You specify the MULTIKEY option in the [OPTIONS] section of the project file. MULTIKEY specifies the footnote character to use for an alternate keyword table in the index. An alternate index can be accessed only when a program calls the WinHelp API using the HELP_MULTIKEY command.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1885\ri125\fi-1755\brdrb\brdrs\tx1885 \b Parameter\tab Description\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1885\ri125\fi-1755\tx1885 footnote-character\tab Specifies the case-sensitive letter to be used for the keyword footnote.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1885 \b Comment
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1885 \plain\f1\fs16 You can use any alphanumeric character for a keyword table except K, k, A, or a; these are reserved for Help's standard and ALink keyword tables. There is an absolute limit of five keyword tables, including the standard K-keyword table and the A-keyword table.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1885 \b Example
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1885 \plain\f1\fs16 The following example illustrates how to enable the letter L for a keyword-table footnote:
\par \pard\keep\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab MULTIKEY=L
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES;HPJ_SECTIONS;ALink;KLink')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES;HPJ_SECTIONS;ALink;KLink')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0107}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} NOTES}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 15Q.CUI}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} HPJ_REF;new_hpj;NOTES}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} NOTES option in OPTIONS section;project files;project files, NOTES option}
\b\fs24 NOTES
\par \pard\keepn\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \fs16 NOTES=\plain\f1\fs16 [\b 0\plain\f1\fs16  | \b 1\plain\f1\fs16  | \b yes\plain\f1\fs16  | \b no\plain\f1\fs16 ]
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 You specify the NOTES option in the [OPTIONS] section of the project (.hpj) file. NOTES specifies whether Help Workshop should display notes while compiling the Help file. Notes are messages Help Workshop displays when it encounters problems that may or may not adversely affect your Help file.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Comment
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The NOTES option is new.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES;HPJ_SECTIONS;REPORT;ERRORLOG')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES;HPJ_SECTIONS;REPORT;ERRORLOG')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0108}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} OLDKEYPHRASE}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 4_QY9B}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} HPJ_REF;OLDKEYPHRASE}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} OLDKEYPHRASE option in OPTIONS section;project files;project files, OLDKEYPHRASE option}
\b\fs24 OLDKEYPHRASE
\par \pard\keepn\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \fs16 OLDKEYPHRASE=\plain\f1\fs16 value
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 You specify the OLDKEYPHRASE option in the [OPTIONS] section of the project (.hpj) file. OLDKEYPHRASE specifies whether an existing key-phrase file should be used when compressing a Help file with phrase compression.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1625\ri125\fi-1495\brdrb\brdrs\tx1615 \b Parameter\tab Description\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1625\ri125\fi-1495\tx1615 value\tab If this value is YES, the existing phrase (.ph) file is used for phrase compression. If this value is NO, a new .ph file is created during the build. The default value is NO.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 \b Comment
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 \plain\f1\fs16 If you specify phrase compression, Help Workshop creates a phrase-table file that has a .ph filename extension. If Help Workshop finds an existing phrase file, it deletes the file, and then creates a new one \'97 unless OLDKEYPHRASE=YES is specified in your project file. If it is, Help Workshop uses your existing phrase file. Using an existing phrase file reduces compile time, but compression is less effective.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES;HPJ_SECTIONS;COMPRESS;BAS_COMPRESSION')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES;HPJ_SECTIONS;COMPRESS;BAS_COMPRESSION')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0109}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} [OPTIONS] section}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 20PR0VW}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} HPJ_REF;new_hpj;OPTIONS}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} OPTIONS section of project files;project files;project files, [OPTIONS] section}
\b\fs24 [OPTIONS] section
\par \pard\keepn\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \fs16 [OPTIONS]\line
\plain\f1\fs16 option
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 The [OPTIONS] section includes options that control how a Help file is compiled and what feedback the compilation process displays. This section, along with the [FILES] section, is required in all project (.hpj) files. This section should be placed first in the project file so that the options apply during the entire compilation process.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1625\ri125\fi-1495\brdrb\brdrs\tx1615 \b Parameter\tab Description\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1625\ri125\fi-1495\tx1615 option\tab Specifies one or more of the following project-file options.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li3595\ri125\fi-1965\brdrb\brdrs\tx3595 \b Option\tab Description\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li3595\ri125\fi-1965\tx3595 \uldb BMROOT\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 0WJTWB}\tab Specifies the folder that contains the bitmap files named in \{\-bmc\'7d, \{\-bml\'7d, and \{\-bmr\'7d references in the topic (.rtf) files.
\par \uldb BUILD\plain\f1\fs16 {\v C.69DU}\tab Determines which topics to include in the build.
\par \uldb CHARSET\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 0H87TF}\tab Specifies the default character set.
\par \uldb CITATION\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 2DQ_3RE}\tab Adds a citation to the end of any text copied or printed from the Help file.
\par \uldb COMPRESS\plain\f1\fs16 {\v TP84WF}\tab Specifies how the Help file should be compressed.
\par \uldb CONTENTS\plain\f1\fs16 {\v USV_XF}\tab Specifies the default topic ID.
\par \uldb CNT\plain\f1\fs16 {\v RB3WX}\tab Specifies the name of the Help file's contents (.cnt) file.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li3595\ri125\fi-1965\tx3595 \uldb COPYRIGHT\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 19V_0.K}\tab Adds a unique copyright message for the Help file to WinHelp's Version dialog box.
\par \uldb DBCS\plain\f1\fs16 {\v RB4KGS}\tab Specifies whether topic files use a double-byte character set.
\par \uldb DEFFONT\plain\f1\fs16 {\v ECK4F6}\tab Specifies the default font used in WinHelp text boxes.
\par \uldb ERRORLOG\plain\f1\fs16 {\v YCLLJE}\tab Saves compilation messages in a file during the build.
\par \uldb FORCEFONT\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 24ML4CE}\tab Forces all authored fonts in topic files to appear in a different font when displayed in the Help file.
\par \uldb FTS\plain\f1\fs16 {\v RB72W}\tab Specifies what level of information to include (if any) in the index file for full-text searching.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li3595\ri125\fi-1965\tx3595 \uldb HCW\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 2OLG6TE}\tab Reserved for use by Help Workshop.
\par \uldb HLP\plain\f1\fs16 {\v RB8UT}\tab Specifies the name of the Help (.hlp) file to create.
\par \uldb INDEX_SEPARATORS\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 2A9VNJZ}\tab Specifies the characters WinHelp uses to identify first- and second-level index entries.
\par \uldb LCID\plain\f1\fs16 {\v RB.LMD}\tab Specifies the language of the Help file.
\par \uldb MAPFONTSIZE\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 12DOBQV}\tab Maps a font size in the topic file to a different font size in the compiled Help file.
\par \uldb MULTIKEY\plain\f1\fs16 {\v K.Z2KQ}\tab Specifies an alternate keyword table to use for mapping topics.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li3595\ri125\fi-1965\tx3595 \uldb NOTES\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 15Q.CUI}\tab Specifies whether Help Workshop should display notes. 
\par \uldb OLDKEYPHRASE\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 4_QY9B}\tab Specifies whether Help Workshop should use the existing key phrase table or create a new one during compilation.
\par \uldb REPLACE\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 06VZSZ}\tab Specifies a path prefix to replace and its replacement.
\par \uldb REPORT\plain\f1\fs16 {\v JOHTZB}\tab Controls the display of messages during the build process.
\par \uldb ROOT\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 596Y.D}\tab Specifies the folders that contain the topic files listed in the [FILES] section.
\par \uldb TMPDIR\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 2NHAHAE}\tab Specifies the folder in which to place the temporary files that are created while compiling the Help file.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li3595\ri125\fi-1965\tx3595 \uldb TITLE\plain\f1\fs16 {\v CMUDDV}\tab Specifies the text that appears in the title bar of the Help window when the file is open.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx3595 \b Comment
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx3595 \plain\f1\fs16 Most of these options can appear in any order within the [OPTIONS] section. If used, the REPLACE option must come before the ROOT or BMROOT options.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES;HPJ_SECTIONS;BMROOT;BUILD;CHARSET;CITATION;COMPRESS;CONTENTS_hpj;CNT;COPYRIGHT;DBCS;DEFFONT;ERRORLOG;FORCEFONT;FTS;HCW;HLP;ICON;INDEX_SEPARATORS;LANGUAGE;LCID;MAPFONTSIZE;MULTIKEY;NOTES;OLDKEYPHRASE;OPTCDROM;REPLACE;REPORT;ROOT;TMPDIR;TITLE;VERSION")\}  \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES;HPJ_SECTIONS;BMROOT;BUILD;CHARSET;CITATION;COMPRESS;CONTENTS_hpj;CNT;COPYRIGHT;DBCS;DEFFONT;ERRORLOG;FORCEFONT;FTS;HCW;HLP;ICON;INDEX_SEPARATORS;LANGUAGE;LCID;MAPFONTSIZE;MULTIKEY;NOTES;OLDKEYPHRASE;OPTCDROM;REPLACE;REPORT;ROOT;TMPDIR;TITLE;VERSION")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:010a}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} REPLACE}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 06VZSZ}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} HPJ_REF;new_hpj;REPLACE}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} project files;project files, REPLACE option;REPLACE option in OPTIONS section}
\b\fs24 REPLACE
\par \pard\keepn\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \fs16 REPLACE=\plain\f1\fs16 old-prefix \b =\plain\f1\fs16  new-prefix
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 You specify the REPLACE option in the [OPTIONS] section of the project (.hpj) file. REPLACE replaces pathname prefixes with a new prefix. If any specified files (for example, topic and bitmap files) move to a different server or folder, you need to update only this parameter. You do not have to edit pathnames in the project file or in included files.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1625\ri125\fi-1495\brdrb\brdrs\tx1615 \b Parameter\tab Description\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1625\ri125\fi-1495\tx1615 old-prefix\tab Specifies the pathname prefix to replace.
\par new-prefix\tab Specifies the new prefix to use in place of the old prefix.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 \b Comments
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 \plain\f1\fs16 This command is not necessary if all files have been specified using path relative to the location of the project file.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 The pathname in either prefix can be a UNC path, a drive letter, or a relative path.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 When used in a project file, the REPLACE option must come before any path specification, such as those specified in a ROOT or BMROOT option.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 The REPLACE option is new.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 \b Example
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 \plain\f1\fs16 The following example replaces the current local path to topic files with a network path.
\par \pard\keep\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab REPLACE=c:\'5cgeorges\'5cproject=\'5c\'5cserver\'5cshare\'5cgeorges\'5cproject
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:010b}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} REPORT}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} JOHTZB}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} HPJ_REF;REPORT}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} project files;project files, REPORT option;REPORT option in OPTIONS section}
\b\fs24 REPORT
\par \pard\keepn\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \fs16 REPORT=\plain\f1\fs16 (\b yes\plain\f1\fs16  | \b no\plain\f1\fs16 )
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 You specify the REPORT option in the [OPTIONS] section of the project (.hpj) file. REPORT causes Help Workshop to display messages while it compiles a Help file. These messages indicate when Help Workshop is performing the different phases of the build, including scanning the file for compression, compiling the file, verifying topic IDs, and resolving jumps, keywords, and browse sequences.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1625\ri125\fi-1495\brdrb\brdrs\tx1615 \b Parameter\tab Description\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1625\ri125\fi-1495\tx1615 value\tab If YES, specifies that Help Workshop display progress messages on the screen during the build. The default value is YES.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 \b Comments
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 \plain\f1\fs16 Displaying the REPORT messages slows down Help Workshop. To speed up the compile process, set the REPORT option to NO.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 If you have specified a log file, Help Workshop writes REPORT messages to it.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`BAS_COMPILE_MSG;HPJ_SECTIONS;ERRORLOG;NOTES')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`BAS_COMPILE_MSG;HPJ_SECTIONS;ERRORLOG;NOTES')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:010c}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} ROOT}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 596Y.D}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} HPJ_REF;ROOT}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} project files, ROOT option;ROOT option in OPTIONS section}
\b\fs24 ROOT
\par \pard\keepn\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \fs16 ROOT=\plain\f1\fs16 pathname
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 You specify the ROOT option in the [OPTIONS] section of the project (.hpj) file. ROOT specifies the folder in which Help Workshop should search for the topic (.rtf) files that make up the contents of the Help file.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Comments
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The ROOT option also specifies paths that Help Workshop should search for files that are included (using an #include statement) in the project file.
\par If the project file does not have a BMROOT option, Help Workshop searches the folders specified in the ROOT option for bitmaps named in \{\-bmc\'7d, \{\-bml\'7d, and \{\-bmr\'7d references in the topic (.rtf) files. If the project file does not have a ROOT option or if none of the ROOT folders contain the bitmaps, the bitmap filenames must be listed in the [BITMAPS] section of the project file.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Example
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The following entry specifies that topic files are located on \'5c\'5cserver\'5cshare\'5crandys\'5cproject:
\par \pard\keep\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab [OPTIONS]\line
ROOT=\'5c\'5cserver\'5cshare\'5crandys\'5cproject
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 Given this ROOT option, topic files can be listed in the [FILES] section without specifying a path.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES;HPJ_SECTIONS;BMROOT;FILES')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES;HPJ_SECTIONS;BMROOT;FILES')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:010d}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} TMPDIR}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 2NHAHAE}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} HPJ_REF;new_hpj;TMPDIR}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} project files;project files, TMPDIR option;TMPDIR option in OPTIONS section}
\b\fs24 TMPDIR
\par \pard\keepn\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \fs16 TMPDIR=\plain\f1\fs16 folder
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 You specify the TMPDIR option in the [OPTIONS] section of the project (.hpj) file. TMPDIR specifies the folder where temporary files that are created while compiling the Help file should be stored. Help Workshop usually does not create temporary files unless your Help file exceeds 8\'a0MB in size.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Comments
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 If the TMPDIR option is not set, Help Workshop uses the folder specified by the TEMP environment variable.
\par The TMPDIR option is new.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:010e}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} TITLE}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} CMUDDV}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} HPJ_REF;TITLE}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} project files;project files, TITLE option;TITLE option in OPTIONS section}
\b\fs24 TITLE
\par \pard\keepn\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \fs16 TITLE=\plain\f1\fs16 titlename
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 You specify the TITLE option in the [OPTIONS] section of the project (.hpj) file. TITLE assigns a title to the Help file. The title can have up to 127 characters (63 for DBCS languages).
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Comments
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 WinHelp displays the text specified in the TITLE command in the:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Title bar of the Help Topics dialog box if a title was not specified in the contents file.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Title bar of the main Help window whenever it displays the Help file if a caption has not already been defined for it and no title was specified in the contents file.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Topics Found dialog box if you have set up your keyword jump to display the title of the Help file with the topic title.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Version dialog box in WinHelp if the COPYRIGHT parameter was not specified in the project file.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES;HPJ_SECTIONS;COPYRIGHT;WINDOWS;title_cnt')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES;HPJ_SECTIONS;COPYRIGHT;WINDOWS;title_cnt')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:010f}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} [WINDOWS] section}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} HIQAEN}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} HPJ_REF;new_hpj;WINDOWS}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} project files;project files, [WINDOWS] section;WINDOWS section of project files}
\b\fs24 [WINDOWS] section
\par \pard\keepn\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \fs16 [WINDOWS]\line
\plain\f1\fs16 window-name\b =\plain\f1\fs16 "caption", (x-coord, y-coord, width, height), state&buttons, (scrolling-RGB), (nonscrolling-RGB), state
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 The [WINDOWS] section defines the size, location, and colors for the primary Help window and any secondary window types used in a Help file.
\par Help Workshop provides a simple interface for creating or editing the [WINDOWS] section. It is recommended that you use Help Workshop, rather than a text editor, to make changes to this section.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1795\ri125\fi-1665\brdrb\brdrs\tx1795 \b Parameter\tab Description\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1795\ri125\fi-1665\tx1795 window-name\tab Specifies the name of the window that uses the defined attributes. For the primary Help window, this parameter is main. For a secondary window, this parameter may be any unique name (other than main) with as many as eight characters. Any jumps that display a topic in a secondary window give this window name as part of the jump.
\par caption\tab Specifies the text that appears in the title bar of the window. The caption can have as many as 50 characters.
\par x-coord\tab Specifies the x-coordinate, in Help units, of the window's upper-left corner. The horizontal position is defined in terms of WinHelp's 0-1023 coordinate system. (Help assumes the screen is 1024 units wide, regardless of resolution. For information about how to determine actual coordinates for different video resolutions, see the Comments section below.) The x-coordinate is relative to the upper-left corner of the screen, which is 0,0.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1795\ri125\fi-1665\tx1795 y-coord\tab Specifies the y-coordinate, in Help units, of the window's upper-left corner. The vertical position is defined in terms of Help's 0-1023 coordinate system. (Help assumes the screen is 1024 units wide, regardless of resolution. For information about how to determine actual coordinates for different video resolutions, see the Comments section below.) The y-coordinate is relative to the upper-left corner of the screen, which is 0,0.
\par width\tab Specifies the window's default width in Help's 0-1023 coordinate system.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1795\ri125\fi-1665\tx1795 height\tab Specifies the window's default height in Help's 0-1023 coordinate system.
\par state&buttons\tab Specifies whether the window is displayed maximized, and defines the buttons to display in the window's button bar, if any. This parameter is a sum of one or more of the following values.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li3065\ri125\fi-1265\brdrb\brdrs\tx3065 \b Hex Value\tab Meaning\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li3065\ri125\fi-1265\tx3065 0x0001\tab Maximize the window, and ignore the x-coord, y-coord, width, height, and state parameters given in the type definition.
\par 0x0004\tab Turn off the default buttons on the button bar (used only for the main Help window).
\par 0x0100\tab Add the Options button to the button bar.
\par 0x0200\tab Add the Browse buttons to the button bar.
\par 0x0400\tab Add the Contents button to the button bar.
\par 0x0800\tab Add the Index button to the button bar.
\par 0x1000\tab Add the Help Topics button to the button bar.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li3065\ri125\fi-1265\tx3065 0x2000\tab Add the Print button to the button bar.
\par 0x4000\tab Add the Back button to the button bar.
\par 0x8000\tab Add the Find button to the button bar.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1795\ri125\fi-1665\tx1795 scrolling-RGB\tab Specifies the background color for the window's scrolling region. Colors are given as standard RGB values, where RRR, GGG, and BBB are three-digit numbers in the range 0 to 255 representing the red, green, and blue components of the color. If this parameter is not given, Help uses the default Windows system color specified by the end-user in Control Panel.
\par nonscrolling-RGB\tab Specifies the background color for the window's nonscrolling region (if any). Colors are given as standard RGB values, where RRR, GGG, and BBB are three-digit numbers in the range 0 to 255 representing the red, green, and blue components of the color. If this parameter is not given, Help uses the default Windows system color specified by the end-user in Control Panel.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1795\ri125\fi-1665\tx1795 state\tab Specifies whether a secondary window type stays on top of other windows. For backwards compatibility, a 1 can be used to indicate that the window is to be displayed on top of other windows. Otherwise, the parameter is the letter 'f' followed by a number representing the sum of one or more of the following values:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li3065\ri125\fi-1265\brdrb\brdrs\tx3065 \b Value\tab Meaning\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li3065\ri125\fi-1265\tx3065 1\tab Display the window on top of other windows.
\par 2\tab Automatically size the window vertically to match the length of the topic (not available for \b main\plain\f1\fs16  Help window).
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx3065 \b Comments
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx3065 \plain\f1\fs16 You can define as many as 255 secondary windows in a project file.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx3065 If no caption is specified, WinHelp displays in the title bar of the Help window the first string it finds:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The text specified in the :Title option in the contents (.cnt) file.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The text specified in the TITLE option in the project file.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab "Windows Help" (in a main Help window) or no text (in a secondary window).
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 Help Workshop automatically combines RGB values to a single number (prefaced by the 'r' character).
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 A single comma may be substituted for an entry or a group of entries enclosed by parentheses. Preceding commas are required if you want to use the default settings. Trailing commas are optional. 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 The Help coordinate system ranges from 0 through 1023 in both directions, so the vertical position plus the height must be less than or equal to 1023. Similarly, the horizontal position plus the width must be less than or equal to 1023. This 1024-by-1024 coordinate system is mapped to the horizontal and vertical resolutions of the video card. To convert from pixels to WinHelp coordinates, you invert the ratio between Help's resolution and the video resolution. Assuming the video card resolution is horizontal by vertical pixels, and the horizontal and vertical locations (or dimensions) you want are in pixels, the x-coordinate (or width), in Help coordinates, is as follows:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab x-coord = pixel location * (1024/horizontal)
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab width = number of pixels * (1024/horizontal)
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 The y-coordinate (or height), in Help coordinates, is:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab y-coord = pixel location* (1024/vertical)
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab height = number of pixels * (1024/horizontal)
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 For example, if you want the window's upper-left corner to appear at horizontal pixel 320 and at vertical pixel 120, and the Help file is being displayed on a standard VGA monitor with 640 by 480 resolution, the x-coord is (320 * (1024/640)) = 512, and y-coord is (120 * (1024/480)) = 256.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES;BAS_HPJ_CREATE_WINDOW;PRO_HPJ_CREATE_WINDOW;PRO_HPJ_CUSTOMIZE_WINDOW;HPJ_SECTIONS;TITLE;title_cnt')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES;BAS_HPJ_CREATE_WINDOW;PRO_HPJ_CREATE_WINDOW;PRO_HPJ_CUSTOMIZE_WINDOW;HPJ_SECTIONS;TITLE;title_cnt')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:012b}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} \{bmc\}, \{bml\}, \{bmr\} statements}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} J8.HV2}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} bmx}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} adding;adding, bitmaps to topics;bitmaps,;bitmaps, adding to topics;bitmaps, statements;bmc statement;bmct statement;bml statement;bmlt statement;bmr statement;bmrt statement;graphics;graphics, adding to topics}
\b\fs24 \{\-bmc\'7d, \{\-bml\'7d, \{\-bmr\'7d statements
\par \pard\keepn\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \fs16 \{\-bm\plain\f1\fs16 x[\b t\plain\f1\fs16 ]\'a0filename1\b \'7d\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 The \{\-bmx\'7d statement inserts a graphic into a topic when the Help file is compiled.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1575\ri125\fi-1455\brdrb\brdrs\tx1575 \b Parameter\tab Description\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1575\ri125\fi-1445\tx1575 x\tab Specifies how the graphic appears in the topic. You can specify the following characters:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1575\ri125\brdrb\brdrs\tx2165 \b Value\tab Description\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li2165\ri125\fi-555\tx2165 c\tab Aligns the bitmap as a text character on the baseline of the type in exactly the same place in the paragraph where the reference occurs. Because the bitmap is treated as text, any paragraph formatting properties assigned to the paragraph also apply to the bitmap.
\par l\tab Aligns the bitmap along the left margin. Text is aligned with the upper right corner of the bitmap and wraps along the right edge of the image.
\par r\tab Aligns the bitmap along the right margin. Text is aligned with the upper left corner of the bitmap and wraps along the left edge of the image.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1575\ri125\fi-1445\tx1575 \b t\plain\f1\fs16 \tab Specifies that the white background of the graphic should be replaced by the background color of a Help topic. This character can be specified in addition to any of the other values. It can be used only with 16-color bitmaps.
\par filename\tab Specifies the name of the graphic file to include. You can include bitmaps, multiple-hotspot bitmaps (.SHG), and multiple-resolution graphic files (.MRB).
\par \tab You can specify multiple files representing different color depths for the same graphic by separating the filenames with a semicolon as in the following example:
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1575\ri125\fi-1445\tx1575 \tab \{\-\'a0bmc dog_16.bmp;dog_256.bmp;dog_mono\'7d
\par \tab When the Help file is run, WinHelp checks the color capability of the user's computer and displays the appropriate graphic file.\plain\f0\fs16  \f1 
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1575 \b Comments
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1575 \plain\f1\fs16 Help Workshop ignores the \b wd\plain\f1\fs16  parameter, which was used by previous versions of the Help compiler.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1575 Do not include the path with the bitmap filename. Instead, use Help Workshop to specify in your project (.hpj) file which folders contain the bitmaps that are referenced in your topic (.rtf) files.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1575 A \ul transparent bitmap,\plain\f1\fs16 {\v L00JF5} specified by a \{\-bmct\'7d, \{\-bmlt\'7d, or \{\-bmrt\'7d command, has its white pixels replaced by the background color of the currently active window the first time the bitmap is displayed. It will not change when the same bitmap is displayed in another window with a different color. If the background color is dithered, WinHelp will pick the solid color closest to that dither for the background of the bitmap.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1575 \b Examples
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1575 \plain\f1\fs16 The following command displays the specified bitmap at the left margin of the topic and causes Help Workshop to replace the white pixels in the graphic image with the background color of the topic:
\par \pard\keep\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab \{\-bmlt\'a0 logo_sh.bmp\'7d
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb25\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \{button ,AL("BAS_ADDING_GRAPHICS;BMROOT;SHED;MRBC")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("BAS_ADDING_GRAPHICS;BMROOT;SHED;MRBC")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:012c}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} \{button\} statement}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} _RDFAW}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} button}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} adding;adding, buttons to Help topics;button statement;buttons,;buttons, adding to Help topics;See Also button, creating}
\b\fs24 \{\-button\'7d statement
\par \pard\keepn\keep\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \fs16 \{\-button\plain\f1\fs16 \'a0[label]\b ,\'a0\plain\f1\fs16 macro1[\b :\'a0\plain\f1\fs16 macro2\b :\'a0\plain\f1\fs16 ... \b :\'a0\plain\f1\fs16 macroN]\b \'7d\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 The \{\-button\'7d reference inserts a button into the Help file and runs the specified macros when a user clicks the button.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1575\ri125\fi-1455\brdrb\brdrs\tx1575 \b Parameter\tab Description\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1575\ri125\fi-1445\tx1575 label\tab Specifies the label, if any, that appears on the button. You cannot define an \ul accelerator key.\plain\f1\fs16 {\v ABYXEJ}
\par macro\tab Specifies one or more macros to run when a user clicks the button.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1575 \b Example
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1575 \plain\f1\fs16 The following command creates a See Also button that runs a KLink macro when the user clicks it.
\par \pard\keep\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab \{\-button See Also, KLink(networks)\'7d
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("BAS_AUTH_BTN;CreateButton")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("BAS_AUTH_BTN;CreateButton")}
