{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0131}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} MRBC command}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} IDVL.A}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} MRBC}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} bitmaps,;bitmaps, multi-resolution;command-line switches;graphics;graphics, multi-resolution;metafiles;MRBC command;Mrbc.exe;multi-resolution graphics;multi-resolution graphics, compiler (mrbc.exe)}
\b\fs24 MRBC command
\par \pard\keepn\keep\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \fs16 MRBC\'a0\plain\f1\fs16 [\b /S\plain\f1\fs16 ]\'a0name.vga\'a0[name.ega,\'a0name.cga,\'a0name.851]
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 The Mrbc.exe program takes your bitmaps or metafiles with different resolutions (CGA, EGA, VGA, or 8514) and combines them into a single graphic that can be compiled into a Help file.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1435\ri125\fi-1305\brdrb\brdrs\tx1435 \b Parameter\tab Description
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1435\ri125\fi-1305\tx1435 /S\plain\f1\fs16 \tab Specifies silent mode. If you use the /S switch, the Mrbc.exe program determines the resolution of each bitmap, based on the first character of the bitmap extension. If you do not use the /S switch, the Mrbc.exe program prompts you for the resolution of each bitmap.
\par name\tab Specifies the names of the bitmaps to include in the .mrb file. Bitmap paths can be relative or absolute. Relative paths are relative to the user\plain\f0\fs16 \'92\f1 s current folder. The Mrbc.exe program accepts * and ? as wildcards for the filenames. Note that you can specify a Windows bitmap or a SHED hypergraphic file.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1435 The Mrbc.exe program creates an output file that has the same filename as the first bitmap on the command line but with the .mrb extension. Output files are saved in the current folder.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1435 \b Comments
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1435 \plain\f1\fs16 Files created by the Mrbc.exe program may not compress as well as .bmp files. If you want to combine bitmaps only to provide different color depth, used the \{\-bmx \'7d command in your .rtf file instead.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1435 Help Workshop removes the aspect ratio from .bmp files so that WinHelp will not stretch or shrink them. Because of this, it is rarely necessary to use the Mrbc.exe program.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1435 If you use the /S switch, the Mrbc.exe program prompts you for the monitor type of each bitmap. You supply the appropriate response, and then the Mrbc.exe program creates the output file and saves it to the current folder. The valid case-insensitive responses to the request for monitor type are CGA, EGA, VGA, and 8514.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1435 If you use the /S switch, MRBC uses the first character of the input file extension to determine the bitmap resolution. The following table shows how the Mrbc.exe program maps the file extensions:
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li115\ri125\brdrb\brdrs\tx1435 \b First character\tab MRBC interpretation
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1435 \plain\f1\fs16 C\tab CGA bitmap
\par E\tab EGA bitmap
\par V\tab VGA bitmap
\par 8\tab 8514 bitmap
\par other\tab VGA bitmap
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1435 You can specify an unlimited number of bitmaps on the command line, but the Mrbc.exe program supports only the four monitor types listed above.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1435 In addition to resolution, WinHelp uses color as a selection criterion. Include a color version and a monochrome version of each bitmap in the same .mrb file to ensure compatibility with both monitor types.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1435 The Mrbc.exe program does not check for valid matches between bitmap resolution and the specified option. Check .mrb bitmaps on the target monitors to ensure that they display correctly.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1435 In some cases, the drawing tool that creates bitmaps stores the resolution in the bitmap file itself. The Mrbc.exe program checks all bitmap files to determine whether the resolution is specified. If the Mrbc.exe program finds the resolution specified in the bitmap files, it uses the stored ratio instead of the one you specified and displays an informative warning message.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1435 The .mrb output file cannot be viewed or edited using any other graphics program.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1435 WinHelp considers an 8514 display to be any monitor that has 120 pixels per inch. Because some high-resolution monitors deliver 96 pixels per inch to display more inches on the screen, WinHelp uses the VGA bitmap on these devices.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1435 Bitmap files for high color depths may be too large to be practical. Where high color depth is important, use the \{\-bmx\'7d command or a metafile rather than a .mrb file.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1435 \b Example
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1435 \plain\f1\fs16 The following example creates a multi-resolution bitmap that accommodates each monitor type:
\par \pard\keep\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab MRBC\'a0/S\'a0HOUSE.VGA\'a0HOUSE.EGA\'a0HOUSE.CGA\'a0HOUSE.8XX
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 MRBC creates a House.mrb file that consists of VGA, EGA, CGA, and 8514 bitmaps.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("BAS_MULT_RESOLUTION;BAS_MULT_COLOR_GRAPHICS")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("BAS_MULT_RESOLUTION;BAS_MULT_COLOR_GRAPHICS")}
\par \page
