\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} cs_dev}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} context-sensitive Help;context-sensitive Help, designing;development strategies for Help files;Help files;Help files, development strategies;Help menu;Help system;Help system, development strategies;Help Topics command;uninstall option for programs}
\b\fs24 Development strategies for Help files
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 If you are a software developer, consider the following when implementing Help as part of your programs.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Help menu
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Provide a Help menu that contains a single command named Help Topics. The Help Topics command should provide access to the program's Help file(s). The API call should use the following syntax:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab WinHelp(hwnd, "helpfile.hlp", HELP_FINDER, 0)
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \b Context-sensitive Help
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 Assign context-sensitive help to each element in every dialog box in your program.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab For topics that will be called from the program, use the IDH_ prefix in the topic ID.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Use a separate header (.h) file to map topic IDs and include it in the [MAP] section of the project (.hpj) file.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \b Uninstall option
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 When providing an Uninstall option for a program, consider the following Help-related files that might exist on a user's system:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab .hlp (Help file)
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab .cnt (Help contents file)
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab .gid (hidden configuration file)
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab .fts (full-text search index file)
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab .ftg (full-text search group list)
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,KL("MAP section;WinHelp")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!KL("MAP section;winhelp_api")}
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} How WinHelp finds a file}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 1N8RUU}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} cs_find}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} file locations;files,;files, how WinHelp searches for;Help files;Help files, how WinHelp searches for;Help files, listing in the registry;registry, listing a Help file in;search path;WinHelp,;WinHelp, searching for files}
\b\fs24 How WinHelp finds a file
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 WinHelp searches for Help files, contents files, programs and DLLs in the following locations:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab If a path is specified, WinHelp first searches for the file in the path. If not found, the path is removed and the following locations are searched.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The folder that contains the current Help file.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The current folder.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The System subfolder in the Windows folder.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The Windows folder.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The folders listed in the PATH environment.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The location specified in Winhelp.ini.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The registry.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 The following registry location is used:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\'5cSoftware\'5cMicrosoft\'5cWindows\'5cHelp
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 The value of the Help key is the name of the Help file, and the corresponding data is the folder where the Help file resides. The following example shows how to list a Help file in the registry:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \f4 if (RegCreateKeyEx(HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE,\line
        "Software\'5c\'5cMicrosoft\'5c\'5cWindows\'5c\'5cHelp", 0,\line
        "Folder", REG_OPTION_NON_VOLATILE, KEY_ALL_ACCESS,\line
        NULL, &hkey, &disposition) == ERROR_SUCCESS) \{\-\line
    RegSetValueEx(hkey, "your filename", 0, REG_SZ, "your folder",\line
        strlen("your folder") + 1);\line
    RegCloseKey(hkey);\line
\'7d
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \f1 If WinHelp cannot find a Help file, it displays a dialog box that enables users to specify the location of the file. If users find the file, WinHelp adds the location information to the registry.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:011c}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Providing context-sensitive Help in a dialog box}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} HM.BD8}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} cs_help}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} context-sensitive Help;context-sensitive Help, providing in dialog boxes;context-sensitive Help, turning off for a control;dialog boxes;dialog boxes, modifying common interfaces;dialog boxes, providing context-sensitive Help in;F1 key}
\b\fs24 Providing context-sensitive Help in a dialog box
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 To provide context-sensitive Help in a dialog box, you must create an array consisting of pairs of double word values. The first value in each pair is the identifier of a control in the dialog box, the second is the topic identifier of the Help topic for the control. The array should contain one pair of identifiers for each control in the dialog box.
\par The dialog box procedure must process the WM_HELP and WM_CONTEXTMENU messages. The dialog procedure receives the WM_HELP message when users press the \scaps f1\plain\f1\fs16  key or when users click the \{bmc bm0.bmp\} button in the title bar, and then click an object in the dialog box. The dialog procedure receives the WM_CONTEXTMENU message when users click the right mouse button.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 The lParam parameter of the WM_HELP message is a pointer to a HELPINFO structure. The hItemHandle member of this structure identifies the control for which the user has requested Help. You must pass this handle to the WinHelp function along with the HELP_WM_HELP command, the name of your Help file, and a pointer to the array of identifiers. The WinHelp function searches the array for the control identifier of the specified control, then retrieves the corresponding Help context identifier. Next, the function passes the Help context identifier to WinHelp, which finds the corresponding topic and displays it in a pop-up window. If the control has an identifier of -1, the system searches for the next control that is a tab stop, and uses its identifier to find the Help context identifier. For this reason, it is important that static text be placed before controls in your resource file.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Processing the WM_CONTEXTMENU message is similar to processing WM_HELP, with two exceptions when calling the WinHelp function:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab You pass the wParam parameter from the WM_CONTEXTMENU message, which is the handle of the control that sent the message.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab You specify the HELP_CONTEXTMENU command instead of HELP_WM_HELP.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 The HELP_CONTEXTMENU command causes WinHelp to display a menu, which is system defined. The menu contains a What's This command and allows users to display Help for the control. In Windows\'a095, a What's This command does not appear when users click an edit field using their right mouse button.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \b Modifying common dialog boxes
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 If you modify a common dialog box and want to hook your context-sensitive Help topics to the new controls, you must install a hook procedure that determines if the WM_HELP or WM_CONTEXTMENU message is for your controls. If so, call WinHelp using your Help file. If not, send the message through to the common dialog box.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \b Turning off context-sensitive Help for a control
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 If you need to turn off the context-sensitive Help for a control, such as a group, you can map the Help ID for that control to -1, as shown in the following example:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab ID_GROUP_BOX, ((DWORD) -1)
\par \pard\sb45\sl-115\li295\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \{button ,AL(`cs_ex;PRO_HPJ_ADD_MAP')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`cs_ex;PRO_HPJ_ADD_MAP')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:011d}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Example code (context-sensitive Help)}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 17EVVJN}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} cs_ex}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} context-sensitive Help;context-sensitive Help, example code;context-sensitive Help, providing in dialog boxes;dialog boxes;dialog boxes, providing context-sensitive Help in;example code for context-sensitive Help;sample code for context-sensitive Help}
\b\fs24 Example code (context-sensitive Help)
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx355 \plain\f1\fs16 The following example shows how to implement context-sensitive Help in a dialog box:
\par LRESULT CALLBACK EditDlgProc(HWND hwndDlg, UINT uMsg, WPARAM wParam,  LPARAM lParam) \line
\{\- \line
\line
\tab // Create an array of control identifiers and context identifiers. \line
\line
\tab static DWORD aIds[] = \{\-\line
\tab     ID_SAVE,   IDH_SAVE,\line
\tab     ID_DELETE, IDH_DELETE,\line
\tab     ID_COPY,   IDH_COPY,\line
\tab     ID_PASTE,  IDH_PASTE,\line
\tab     0,0\line
\tab \'7d;\line
\line
\tab switch (uMsg) \{\-\line
\tab     case WM_HELP:\line
\tab         WinHelp(((LPHELPINFO) lParam)->hItemHandle, "helpfile.hlp",\line
\tab             HELP_WM_HELP, (DWORD) (LPVOID) aIds);\line
\tab         break;\line
\line
\tab     case WM_CONTEXTMENU:\line
\tab         WinHelp((HWND) wParam, "helpfile.hlp", HELP_CONTEXTMENU,\line
\tab             (DWORD) (LPVOID) aIds);\line
\tab         break;\line
\tab     .\line
\tab     . // process other messages here\line
\tab     .\line
\tab \'7d\line
\line
\tab return FALSE;\line
\'7d
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,KL("context-sensitive Help;WM_HELP;WM_CONTEXTMENU")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!KL("context-sensitive Help;WM_HELP;WM_CONTEXTMENU")}
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Adding a tab to the Help Topics dialog box}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 130K0._}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} new_tab}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} adding;adding, tabs to the Help Topics dialog box;customizing;customizing, Help Topics dialog box;dialog boxes;dialog boxes, Help Topics dialog box;Help Topics dialog box;Help Topics dialog box, adding tabs to;OpenTabDialog function;tabs;tabs, adding to the Help Topics dialog box}
\b\fs24 Adding a tab to the Help Topics dialog box
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 To add a custom tab to the WinHelp Help Topics dialog box, you must write your own DLL. Your DLL must supply the following function:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab HWND WINAPI \b OpenTabDialog(\plain\f1\fs16 HWND, DWORD, DWORD\b )\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 This function will be called when you are to create your dialog. The first parameter will be the parent's window handle. The second and third parameters are reserved (for future use). Your DLL must then call the CreateDialog function to create your dialog and return the dialog's window handle.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 The dialog template should be for a dialog without a border and non-visible, and it should use the DS_CONTROL style so that the dialog will get the focus when the tab is activated. WinHelp will resize the Help Topics dialog box as necessary to accommodate your dialog.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 Use the MSG_TAB_CONTEXT and MSG_TAB_MACRO messages in your DLL to communicate with WinHelp.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 Add the tab name and DLL name to the contents (.cnt) file by opening the contents file in Help Workshop, and then clicking the Tabs button.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 The following is an example of the style flags to use for the dialog:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab STYLE WS_CHILD | DS_3DLOOK | DS_CONTROL | WS_TABSTOP
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,KL("DLLs, writing for WinHelp;adding, tabs to Help Topics dialog box;OpenTabDialog;CreateDialog;DS_CONTROL;MSG_TAB_CONTEXT;MSG_TAB_MACRO;DLGTEMPLATE")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!KL("DLLs, writing for WinHelp;adding, tabs to Help Topics dialog box;OpenTabDialog;CreateDialog;DS_CONTROL;MSG_TAB_CONTEXT;MSG_TAB_MACRO;DLGTEMPLATE")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:011e}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Windows Help settings in the Win.ini file}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} C98ZPE}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} colors;colors, initialization settings in Win.ini;hotspots;hotspots, changing default colors;initialization settings in the Win.ini file;Win.ini file;WinHelp,;WinHelp, initialization settings}
\b\fs24 Windows Help settings in the Win.ini file
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The Win.ini file, which is located in the Windows folder, contains initialization information about WinHelp in the [Windows Help] section. The [Windows Help] section can contain the following entries:
\par \uldb Backtrack=num\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 8WUIJM}\line
\uldb Help Author=1\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 21N6.UM}\line
\uldb JumpColor=(r,g,b)\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 4SNKWF}\line
\uldb IFJumpColor=(r,g,b)\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 4SNKWF}\line
\uldb PopupColor=(r,g,b)\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 4SNKWF}\line
\uldb IFPopupColor=(r,g,b)\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 4SNKWF}\line
\uldb MacroColor=(r,g,b)\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 4SNKWF}\b 
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("WININI_SETTINGS")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("WININI_SETTINGS")}
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Backtrack (in Win.ini)}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 8WUIJM}
\pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} BACKTRACK;WININI_SETTINGS}
\b Backtrack=num
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 This line enables users to set the number of topics WinHelp saves in the History list. You can specify any positive integer between 1 and 500, for example:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab Backtrack=25
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Help Author (in Win.ini)}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 21N6.UM}
\pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} WININI_SETTINGS}
\b Help Author=1
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 This setting is automatically set or cleared when you check or clear the Help Author command on the File menu in Help Workshop. For information about Help Author mode, click Related topics.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("BAS_HELP_AUTHOR_MODE")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("BAS_HELP_AUTHOR_MODE")}
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} JumpColor and MacroColor (in Win.ini)}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 4SNKWF}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} WININI_SETTINGS}
\b JumpColor=(r,g,b), IFJumpColor=(r,g,b), PopupColor=(r,g,b), IFPopupColor=(r,g,b), and MacroColor=(r,g,b)
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 You can use any of the following statements in the [WINDOWS HELP] section of your Win.ini file to change hotspot colors from the default green.
\par JumpColor=(r,g,b)\line
IFJumpColor=(r,g,b)\line
PopupColor=(r,g,b)\line
IFPopupColor=(r,g,b)\line
and MacroColor=(r,g,b)
\par The r, g, and b values represent the red, green, and blue (RGB) components of the hotspot color. These color values can be a number from 0 to 255. The meaning of each statement is explained in the following table.
\par \trowd\trgaph105\trleft4 \cellx1265\cellx3415\cellx5175\pard\intbl\sb75\sl-235 \b Command\cell\pard \pard\intbl\sb75\sl-235 Defines the color for\cell\pard \pard\intbl\sb75\sl-235 Default Color\cell\intbl\row
\trowd\trgaph105\trleft4 \cellx1265\cellx3415\cellx5175\pard\intbl\sb75\sl-235 \plain\f1\fs16 JumpColor\cell\pard \pard\intbl\sb75\sl-235 Jump hotspots\cell\pard \pard\intbl\sb75\sl-235 Green\cell\intbl\row
\trowd\trgaph105\trleft4 \cellx1265\cellx3415\cellx5175\pard\intbl\sb75\sl-235 IFJumpColor\cell\pard \pard\intbl\sb75\sl-235 Interfile jump hotspots\cell\pard \pard\intbl\sb75\sl-235 Same as JumpColor\cell\intbl\row
\trowd\trgaph105\trleft4 \cellx1265\cellx3415\cellx5175\pard\intbl\sb75\sl-235 PopUpColor\cell\pard \pard\intbl\sb75\sl-235 Pop-up hotspots\cell\pard \pard\intbl\sb75\sl-235 Same as JumpColor\cell\intbl\row
\trowd\trgaph105\trleft4 \cellx1265\cellx3415\cellx5175\pard\intbl\sb75\sl-235 IFPopupColor\cell\pard \pard\intbl\sb75\sl-235 Interfile pop-up hotspots\cell\pard \pard\intbl\sb75\sl-235 Same as JumpColor\cell\intbl\row
\trowd\trgaph105\trleft4 \cellx1265\cellx3415\cellx5175\pard\intbl\sb75\sl-235 MacroColor\cell\pard \pard\intbl\sb75\sl-235 Macro hotspots\cell\pard \pard\intbl\sb75\sl-235 Same as JumpColor\cell\intbl\row
\pard \fs24 \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:011f}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Creating a Winhelp.ini file for search paths}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 144KIW8}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} Help files;Help files, search path for;search path;Win.ini file}
\b Creating a Winhelp.ini file for search paths
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 If you are distributing your program and Help files on removable media such as a CD-ROM, you can have your setup program define the drives and directories where WinHelp should search for Help files. The paths you define will be added to Help\plain\f0\fs16 \'92\f1 s regular search paths for interfile jumps.
\par The syntax for the Winhelp.ini entry is:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab [FILES]\line
HLP-filename=path, message
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1625\ri125\fi-1495\brdrb\brdrs\tx1615 \b Parameter\tab Description\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1625\ri125\fi-1495\tx1615 HLP-filename\tab Specifies the name of the Help or contents file for which you want to define a search path.
\par path\tab Specifies the fully qualified path to the folder where the file is located.
\par message\tab The message that WinHelp should display in a message box if the path cannot be found. This parameter is optional.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 \b Comments
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 \plain\f1\fs16 On Windows\'a0NT, you must use the Winhlp32.ini file instead of the Winhelp.ini file.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 When creating entries in the Winhelp.ini file, make sure that the first program to create the Winhelp.ini file also creates the [FILES] section heading. You can use the Windows WritePrivateProfileString function to create entries in the Winhelp.ini file.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 \b Example
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1615 \plain\f1\fs16 The following entry instructs Help to look in the \'5cProduct\'5cFiles folder on drive P for the Notepad Help file. If necessary, Help will prompt the user to insert a CD into the drive:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \tab [FILES]\line
Notepad.hlp=P:\'5cProduct\'5cFiles, Please insert your Windows\'a095 CD into drive P.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,KL("WritePrivateProfileString;cs_find")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!KL("WritePrivateProfileString;cs_find")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0133}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} About full-text search}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} FTS_About}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} FTS_About}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} full-text search;full-text search, engine overview;reference;reference, full-text search}
\b\fs24 About Full-Text Search
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The full-text-search (FTS) engine gives programs the same full-text search capabilities as available with Windows Help. The engine provides a set of functions that you use to create full-text-search indexes and use existing indexes to search for words and phrases in your source documents. The engine also provides functions for compressing text and highlighting search hits in your source text.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Sources, Topics, Words, and Phrases
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The full-text-search engine works in conjunction with source documents (source files) that contain text organized in words and phrases, separated by wordbreak and other formatting characters. To use the engine, you must also organize the source into topics, where a topic typically corresponds a section in a book or information in a help file that is to be display as a unit. You must assign a unique value or handle to each topic; the engine uses that handle value to identify the topic during searches. Although not required, it is recommended that you assign a title to each topic.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Once you have identified the topics, you construct the index. The index contains the word and phrases from the source document (in compressed format) and data that identifies which words and phrases belong in which topics. Once you have an index, you use the built-in search dialog box provided by the engine to let the user search for words and phrases in the source documents.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0134}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Index construction}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 1NDWCPQ}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} full-text search;full-text search, constructing an index;index,;index, constructing full-text search}
\b\fs24 Index Construction
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 You create an full-text-search index by using the \b NewIndex\plain\f1\fs16  function. You specify the name of the source for the index, the character set and locale for which the index is created, the type of searching methods the index must support, and the kinds of handle values you\plain\f0\fs16 \'92\f1 ll used to identify topics. If successful, the function initializes the index and returns an index handle (a value having HINDEX type) identifying it. You use the index handle in subsequent function calls to add entries to the index.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 When you create an index you can specify a combination of search types. If no other type is given, you must specify TOPIC_SEARCH. This ensures that the index supports searches for topics that contain a given word or collection of words. You can use the PHRASE_SEARCH value to create an index that supports searches for topics that contain a given phrase, that is, a specific sequence of words. Use the PHRASE_FEEDBACK value for an index that supports validation of phrases, that is, provides feedback about the set of valid words that can appear next in a given phrase. Use the VECTOR_SEARCH for an index that supports similarity searches, that is, searches that present topics that are statistically similar in terms of type and frequency of words used.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 The search types are cumulative capabilities. That is, you can\plain\f0\fs16 \'92\f1 t ask for PHRASE_FEEDBACK without PHRASE_SEARCH, and you can\plain\f0\fs16 \'92\f1 t ask for VECTOR_SEARCH without PHRASE_FEEDBACK.
\par You add topics to the index by using first calling the \b ScanTopicTitle\plain\f1\fs16  function to define a title and a handle value for the topic. The handle value may be either a 32-bit value or a 64-bit value. Then you supply the text for the topic by one or more calls to the \b ScanTopicText\plain\f1\fs16  function. You repeat this procedure, calling \b ScanTopicTitle\plain\f1\fs16  followed by calls to \b ScanTopicText\plain\f1\fs16 , until you have indexed all topics.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Once you have added entries to the index, you can save the index to disk by using the \b SaveIndex\plain\f1\fs16  function. The index remains in memory, even if you have saved it to disk. You must use the \b DeleteIndex\plain\f1\fs16  function to finally remove the index.
\par Because indexing large sources may be a lengthy operation, you should give users some indication that progress is being made. To ensure that you can indicate progress while entries are being added to an index, you use the \b RegisterAnimator\plain\f1\fs16  function to register an \b AnimatorProc\plain\f1\fs16  callback function. That function will be called frequently during the indexing operation. When your \b AnimatorProc\plain\f1\fs16  is called you may take appropriate graphical actions to show that your program is \plain\f0\fs16 \'93\f1 alive\plain\f0\fs16 \'94\f1  and is making progress.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 You should be careful that your \b AnimatorProc\plain\f1\fs16  doesn\plain\f0\fs16 \'92\f1 t take so much processor time that it slows down the indexing process. One good way to keep your processing under control is to call \b GetTickCount\plain\f1\fs16  at the start of your \b AnimatorProc\plain\f1\fs16  and use a global variable to keep track of how recently you updated your progress animation or your progress indicator.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("FTS_Index_Construct")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("FTS_Index_Construct")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0135}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Where files are placed}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} .4BU_Z}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} full-text search;full-text search, where index files are placed;index,;index, constructing full-text search}
\b\fs24 Where Files are Placed
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 When the indexer constructs an index file, it first attempts to create the index in the directory defined by the \b SaveIndex\plain\f1\fs16  function. If that is not possible, it tries to create the index file in the \'5cWindows\'5cHELP folder. If that attempt also fails, it makes one last attempt to create the file in the Windows folder before giving up.
\par When temporary files are necessary, the indexer first interprets the pbSourceName value passed to \b NewIndex\plain\f1\fs16  as an initial location and attempts to create the temporary file there. If that fails, it tries the \'5cWindows\'5cHELP folder and finally the \'5cWindows folder before giving up.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("NewIndex;SaveIndex")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("NewIndex;SaveIndex")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0136}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Searcher (full-text)}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 1H.SZNG}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} full-text search;full-text search, using a searcher}
\b\fs24 Searcher
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 You use the searcher to carry out a search for the topic or topics in a given collection that contain a particular set of words or phrases. You create a searcher by using the \b NewSearcher\plain\f1\fs16  function. If successful, the function returns a searcher handle (a value having HSEARCHER type) identifying the searcher. You use the handle in subsequent function calls to open an index and search for words and phrases.
\par Before you can search for words, you must open an index file and associate it with the searcher. You do this by using the \b OpenIndex\plain\f1\fs16  function. If the function is successful, it returns an integer value that identifies the index. You can use the index identifier with the \b QueryOptions\plain\f1\fs16  function to determine what type of searches the index supports. You can also check which type of searches are valid for an index before opening the index by using the \b IsValidIndex\plain\f1\fs16  function. The index identifier will also be used later when a topic must be displayed from that index.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 When you call \b OpenIndex\plain\f1\fs16 , it will return to you the source name and time stamp values that were originally passed when it was created with the \b NewIndex\plain\f1\fs16  function. If those don\plain\f0\fs16 \'92\f1 t match what you\plain\f0\fs16 \'92\f1 re expecting, you can call \b DiscardIndex\plain\f1\fs16  to remove it from the search set. Alternatively you can supply the source name and time stamp values to OpenIndex and have it do the comparisons for you.
\par You can associate more than one index with a searcher by using the \b OpenIndex\plain\f1\fs16  function multiple times. If you do associate a group of indexes with a searcher, you can save information about that group to a file on disk by using the \b SaveGroup\plain\f1\fs16  function. If you save the group in this way, at a later time you can quickly open and associate the group of index files with a new searcher by using the \b LoadGroup\plain\f1\fs16  function. That is, you don\plain\f0\fs16 \'92\f1 t have to explicitly call the \b OpenIndex\plain\f1\fs16  function for each index in the group.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Once you have an index or indexes associated with the searcher, you can create a search dialog by calling the \b OpenDialog\plain\f1\fs16  function. That function returns the window handle for the dialog box, so you can access and manage the dialog box just as you would any other window. Because the dialog box is created invisible and disabled, you must explicitly enable and show it before the user can use it. In general, you should move the dialog box to the location in its parent window, then show it and enable it.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Later when the user double-clicks one of the topic titles, the dialog will send a message to its parent window. That message will tell you the topic handle and index identifier for that title. Then your program must display the corresponding topic text. Usually that message will be MSG_FTS_JUMP_HASH, but it may also be MSG_FTS_JUMP_VA or MSG_FTS_JUMP_QWORD, depending on indexing options which were given when the index was created. In all cases the topic handle will be exactly the value you passed to the \b ScanTopicTitle\plain\f1\fs16  function when you indexed that topic.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 You can supply a \plain\f0\fs16 \'93\f1 Display\plain\f0\fs16 \'94\f1  button in the parent window and get a topic displayed by sending a WM_COMMAND message of type ID_OK to the dialog box. It will then send back a message with the handle and index identifier for the topic whose title is highlighted.
\par The dialog box has several other message it may send to its parent window. You\plain\f0\fs16 \'92\f1 ll get a MSG_FTS_GET_TITLE message when the dialog needs to show the name you\plain\f0\fs16 \'92\f1 ve given to the text set that goes with a particular index. You\plain\f0\fs16 \'92\f1 ll be given the identifying number for the index, and you\plain\f0\fs16 \'92\f1 ll supply a null-terminated string.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 When you call the \b LoadGroup\plain\f1\fs16  function, it may send you one or more MSG_FTS_WHERE_IS_IT messages if the FTG file or one of the files in the group doesn\plain\f0\fs16 \'92\f1 t exist or isn\plain\f0\fs16 \'92\f1 t valid. That message will point to the file name that can\plain\f0\fs16 \'92\f1 t be found, and you can change the file name string to point to an alternate directory. If you want to support this message, you must call \b SetDirectoryLocator\plain\f1\fs16  to identify the window which will process the MSG_FTS_WHERE_IS_IT message.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Finally you may receive a MSG_REINDEX_REQUEST message if the user clicks on the \plain\f0\fs16 \'93\f1 Rebuild\plain\f0\fs16 \'94\f1  button. That\plain\f0\fs16 \'92\f1 s your signal to rebuild the index (or indices) perhaps with new indexing options.
\par If you\plain\f0\fs16 \'92\f1 d like to temporarily hide the search dialog, simply send it a WM_CLOSE message. The dialog will make itself invisible and will set the desktop to be its parent. Later when you want to make the search dialog visible again, simply send a UM_CONNECT message to it. If you really want to destroy the search dialog, send it a UM_CLOSE message. Alternatively you can just call \b DeleteSearcher\plain\f1\fs16 .
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("FTS_Search")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("FTS_Search")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0137}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Highlighting search targets}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 13JL3TS}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} full-text search;full-text search, highlighting}
\b\fs24 Highlighting Search Hits
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 When you\plain\f0\fs16 \'92\f1 re displaying a topic you\plain\f0\fs16 \'92\f1 ve found with a searcher you can highlight the target words and phrases using the Hiliting interfaces. After you\plain\f0\fs16 \'92\f1 ve opened a Searcher (with \b NewSearcher\plain\f1\fs16 ) you can attach a hiliter to it (with \b NewHiliter\plain\f1\fs16 ). You only need to create one Hiliter for a sequence of search operations. 
\par When you want to get highlighting information for a search topic you must first extract the text to be examined and pass it to the hiliter (using \b ScanDisplayText\plain\f1\fs16 ). This may be done in sections, either for convenience, or because different sections of the text have different Charset and Locale designations. If you later want to begin fresh on a new topic, you must first call \b ClearDisplayText\plain\f1\fs16  to discard the old display text.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Once all the text has been scanned, you retrieve the hilite count (using \b CountHilites\plain\f1\fs16 ) for all part of the text to determine how much hilite storage space is required.  Then you use \b QueryHilites\plain\f1\fs16  to get the hilites themselves as offsets into the text you passed to ScanDisplayText. 
\par The final stage is to apply the hilite offsets to your original text -- which is something you do entirely in your own code. 
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("FTS_topic_hiliting")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("FTS_topic_hiliting")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0138}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Phrase compression}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} FJHF3S}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} full-text search;full-text search, phrase compression}
\b\fs24 Phrase Compression
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 You can take advantage of the built-in compression capabilities to compress your own text. You can create a compressor by using the \b NewCompressor\plain\f1\fs16  function. If successful, the function returns a compressor handle (a value having HCOMPRESSOR type which identifies the compressor). You use that handle in subsequent function calls to create a phrase table, and compress or decompress text. When you no longer need the compressor, you can delete it by using the \b DeleteCompressor\plain\f1\fs16  function.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 You carry out the compression in two steps. First, you use the \b ScanText\plain\f1\fs16  function to let the compressor develop compression statistics (a phrase table) for the text you want to compress. Then you use the \b CompressText\plain\f1\fs16  function to carry out the actual compression. The function returns the compressed text in a buffer and specifies the size in bytes of that text.
\par Typically, a program saves the compressed text so that it can be expanded later. To expand to the compressed text later, you must always save the compression statistics, called the phrase table, with the compressed text. You can retrieve the phrase table data by using the \b GetPhraseTable\plain\f1\fs16  function. You can call \b GetPhraseTable\plain\f1\fs16  after finished scanning all the text in the first pass.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 To expand (decompress) the compressed text, you use the \b DecompressText\plain\f1\fs16  function. Before expanding, however, you must set the phrase table for the text by using the \b SetPhraseTable\plain\f1\fs16  function.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("FTS_phrase_compress")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("FTS_phrase_compress")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0139}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Language support}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 1B6J9DF}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} full-text search;full-text search, language support}
\b\fs24 Language Support
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 In most cases the full-text engine automatically adjusts to accommodate the active language based on information from the National Language Support (NLS) APIs. For the cases where that support is not sufficient there are two types of external DLL interfaces \plain\f0\fs16 \'97\f1  a Stemmer interface and a Word Breaker interface.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("FTS_NLS")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("FTS_NLS")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:013a}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} The stemmer interface}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 1_PK1FQ}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} FTS_NLS}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} full-text search;full-text search, stemmer;stemmer}
\b\fs24 The Stemmer Interface
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 A stemmer is a language dependent piece of code that reduces related words to a common form. For example an English stemmer might map \plain\f0\fs16 \'93\f1 publish\plain\f0\fs16 \'94\f1 , \plain\f0\fs16 \'93\f1 published\plain\f0\fs16 \'94\f1 , \plain\f0\fs16 \'93\f1 publishes\plain\f0\fs16 \'94\f1 , and \plain\f0\fs16 \'93\f1 publishing\plain\f0\fs16 \'94\f1  to the form \plain\f0\fs16 \'93\f1 publish\plain\f0\fs16 \'94\f1 . The key idea is that words which denote a common idea map to the same stem.
\par The full-text engine automatically uses language specific stemmers to build index data to support similarity searches between topics. Similarity search information can still be built when no stemmer is available, but it is more accurate when a stemmer is present. Windows\'a095 includes a stemmer specific to U. S. English (STEM0409.DLL).
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 If you want to construct a stemmer for some other language, you must construct a DLL whose name follows the pattern STEMxxxx.DLL, where xxxx is the hexadecimal representation of the local identifier (lcid) for the language. Within that DLL you must export a function named Stemmer.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("Stemmer")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("Stemmer")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:013b}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} The word breaker interface}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} BQRI8O}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} FTS_NLS}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} full-text search;full-text search, word-breaker interface;word-breaker interface}
\b\fs24 The Word Breaker Interface
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 A word breaker scans a sequence of characters and divides it into words and punctuation. This is a fundamental operation during index construction.
\par For most languages word breaking can be done automatically building a table that defines whether a character is a word character or a punctuation character. Then contiguous sequences of word characters are presumed to be words.
\par For some languages (Japanese, for example) the rules are considerably more complicated. To address those languages the full-text search engine (FTSRCH.DLL) will look for language-specific word breaker DLLs and use them when they are available.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 When constructing a language-specific word breaker, you must provide a DLL whose name follows the pattern FTLXxxxx.DLL, where xxxx is the four-digit hexadecimal representation of the language identifier. Thus a word breaker DLL for Japanese would be named FTLX0411.DLL.
\par Your DLL must export two interfaces \plain\f0\fs16 \'97\f1  \b FTSWordBreakW\plain\f1\fs16  and \b FTSWordBreakA\plain\f1\fs16 .
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("WordBreaker")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("WordBreaker")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:013c}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} AnimatorProc function}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 21YXJIB}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} AnimatorProc;FTS_Index_Construct}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} AnimatorProc function;full-text search;full-text search, functions}
\b\fs24 AnimatorProc
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 void AnimatorProc(void);
\par Periodically called by the FTS engine while processing requests to add entries to an index. This program-supplied function should carry out an appropriate action to notify the user that the construction of the index is progressing. Uses standard C calling conventions.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Return Value
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 None.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Comments
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 This function should avoid doing a lot of processing during each call. One good approach is to use a variable together with calls to \b GetTickCount\plain\f1\fs16  to keep track of the amount of time that has elapsed since the last animation action.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("RegisterAnimator")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("RegisterAnimator")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:013d}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} ClearDisplayText function}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 2JLR1UT}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} ClearDisplayText;FTS_topic_hiliting}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} ClearDisplayText function;full-text search;full-text search, functions}
\b\fs24 ClearDisplayText
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 ERRORCODE ClearDisplayText(HHILITER hHiliter);
\par Removes any text previously passed to the hiliter.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1435\ri125\fi-1305\brdrb\brdrs\tx1435 \b Parameter\tab Description\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1435\ri125\fi-1305\tx1435 hcmp\tab Handle of the hiliter. Must have been previously created using the \b NewHiliter\plain\f1\fs16  function.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1435 \b Return Value
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1435 \plain\f1\fs16 Returns either zero or a negative error code value.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("ScanDisplayText;CountHilites;QueryHilites;DeleteHiliter;NewHiliter")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("FTS_topic_hiliting;ScanDisplayText;CountHilites;QueryHilites;DeleteHiliter;NewHiliter")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:013e}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} CompressText function}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 6.QF_Y0}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} CompressText;FTS_phrase_compress}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} CompressText function;full-text search;full-text search, functions}
\b\fs24 CompressText
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 INT CompressText(HCOMPRESSOR hcmp, PBYTE pbText, UINT cbText, PBYTE *ppbCompressed, UINT iCharset);
\par Compresses the given text using the phrase table associated with the given compressor.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1435\ri125\fi-1305\brdrb\brdrs\tx1435 \b Parameter\tab Description\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1435\ri125\fi-1305\tx1435 hcmp\tab Handle of the compressor. Must have been previously created using the \b NewCompressor\plain\f1\fs16  function.
\par pbText\tab Address of the buffer containing the text to compress. That text will be overwritten whenever the compressed text is smaller than the uncompressed text.
\par cbText\tab Size of uncompressed text in bytes.
\par ppbCompressed\tab Address of a variable that will receive the address of a malloc buffer containing compressed text. That variable will not be set when the compressed text is smaller than the uncompressed text. This parameter may be NULL.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1435\ri125\fi-1305\tx1435 iCharset\tab Character set of the text to be compressed. If this parameter is USE_DEFAULT, the function uses the default character set specified when the compressor was created.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1435 \b Return Value
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1435 \plain\f1\fs16 Returns either a negative error code value or the size in bytes of the compressed form of the input text.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1435 If this value is positive and less than cbText, the compressed form will be written into the pbText area. Otherwise if the result value is greater than or equal to cbText and ppbCompressed is non-NULL, the compressed form will be stored in a malloc\plain\f0\fs16 \'92\f1 d buffer and the address of that buffer will be stored in *ppbCompressed.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("DecompressText;NewCompressor")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("DecompressText;NewCompressor")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:013f}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} CountHilites function}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 1XG3Z9W}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} CountHilites;FTS_topic_hiliting}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} CountHilites function}
\b\fs24 CountHilites
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 INT CountHilites(HHILITER hHiliter, INT base, INT limit);
