{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0146}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} FTSWordBreakA function}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 3_.B_MY}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} FTSWordBreakA;WordBreaker}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} FTSWordBreakA function}
\b\fs24 FTSWordBreakA
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 int APIENTRY FTSWordBreakA  (CP wCP, LPSTR *ppbText, LPINT pcbText, LPSTR *papbToken, LPSTR *papbTokenEnd, LPBYTE paType, PUINT paHash, int cwTokens, UINT fTokenizeSpaces);
\par Scans a sequence of non-Unicode characters and constructs information about where words and punctuation streams occur. It exactly parallels \b FTSWordBreakW\plain\f1\fs16  except that its input text is composed of 8-bit values with characters being represented by either one or two 8-bit values. This kind of text is called multibyte text.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1435\ri125\fi-1305\brdrb\brdrs\tx1435 \b Parameter\tab Description\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1435\ri125\fi-1305\tx1435 wCP\tab Code page for the text.
\par ppbText\tab Address of a LPWSTR variable which in turn points to the multibyte text which is to be scanned. On exit that variable will be adjusted to point just beyond the text for which token information has been constructed.
\par pcbText\tab Address of a variable which defines the number characters remaining in the multibyte text. On exit that variable will be adjusted to count the number of characters not yet processed.
\par papbToken\tab Address of an array of LPWSTR items. That array contains slots for cwTokens items. On exit it will contain pointers to the character positions in which tokens start. This pointer may be NULL.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1435\ri125\fi-1305\tx1435 papbTokenEnd\tab Address of an array of LPWSTR items. That array contains slots for cwTokens items. On exit it will contain pointers to the character positions just beyond the ends of tokens. This pointer may be NULL.
\par paType\tab Address of an array of BYTE items. That array contains slots for cwTokens items. On exit each byte value will indicate whether the corresponding token is a word, a number, or punctuation. A zero value denotes punctuation while words and numbers are denoted by 0x02 and 0x01 respectively. This pointer may be NULL.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1435\ri125\fi-1305\tx1435 paHash\tab Address of an array of UINT items. That array contains slots for cwTokens items. On exit each element will contain a hash value for the corresponding token. This pointer may be NULL.
\par \tab Hash values are to be constructed as follows:
\par \tab for (pw= pwToken, cw= cwToken, uHash= 0; cw--; ++pw) \line
    uHash = _rotl(uHash, 5) - *pw;
\par cwTokens\tab Defines the number of array slots in papwToken, papwTokenEnd, paType, and paHash.
\par fTokenizeSpaces\tab Set of bit flags which determine how tokens are constructed. Can be a combination of these values:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li4145\ri125\fi-2705\brdrb\brdrs\tx4145 \b Value\tab Meaning\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li4145\ri125\fi-2705\tx4145 TOKENIZE_SPACES (0x01)\tab When this bit flag is on, a single space character imbedded between two words will be shown as a token. When the flag is off, it will be ignored.
\par REMOVE_SPACE_CHARS (0x02)\tab When this bit flag is on, all white space characters will be discarded when punctuation tokens are constructed. This means that the *ppwText buffer will be altered. If a punctuation sequence consists of nothing but white space characters, no token will be constructed.
\par STARTING_IMBEDS (0x04)\tab When this flag is on, a punctuation character which may be imbedded in a word is allowed to start a word or a number. An example of such a character is the English decimal point (\plain\f0\fs16 \'93\f1 .\plain\f0\fs16 \'94\f1 ).
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx4145 \b Return Value
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx4145 \plain\f1\fs16 Returns the number of tokens for which information has been constructed.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("FTSWordBreakW")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("FTSWordBreakW")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0147}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} FTSWordBreakW function}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 3_.B_ND}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} FTSWordBreakW;WordBreaker}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} FTSWordBreakW function}
\b\fs24 FTSWordBreakW
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 int APIENTRY FTSWordBreakW  (LPWSTR *ppwText, LPINT pcwText, LPWSTR *papwToken, LPWSTR *papwTokenEnd, LPBYTE paType, PUINT paHash, int cTokens, UINT fTokenizeSpaces);
\par This function scans a sequence of Unicode characters and constructs information about where words and punctuation tokens occur. That information will be copied into a collection of arrays passed to \b FTWWordBreakW\plain\f1\fs16 .
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1435\ri125\fi-1305\brdrb\brdrs\tx1435 \b Parameter\tab Description\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1435\ri125\fi-1305\tx1435 ppwText\tab Address of a LPWSTR variable which in turn points to the Unicode text which is to be scanned. On exit that variable will be adjusted to point just beyond the text for which token information has been constructed.
\par pcwText\tab Address of a variable which defines the number characters remaining in the Unicode text. On exit that variable will be adjusted to count the number of characters not yet processed.
\par papwToken\tab Address of an array of LPWSTR items. That array contains slots for cwTokens items. On exit it will contain pointers to the character positions in which tokens start. This pointer may be NULL.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1435\ri125\fi-1305\tx1435 papwTokenEnd\tab Address of an array of LPWSTR items. That array contains slots for cwTokens items. On exit it will contain pointers to the character positions just beyond the ends of tokens. This pointer may be NULL.
\par paType\tab Address of an array of BYTE items. That array contains slots for cwTokens items. On exit each byte value will indicate whether the corresponding token is a word, a number, or punctuation. A zero value denotes punctuation while words and numbers are denoted by 0x02 and 0x01 respectively. This pointer may be NULL.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1435\ri125\fi-1305\tx1435 paHash\tab Points to an array of UINT items. That array contains slots for cwTokens items. on exit each element will contain a hash value for the corresponding token. This pointer may be NULL.
\par \tab Hash values are to be constructed as follows:
\par \tab for (pw= pwToken, cw= cwToken, uHash= 0; cw--; ++pw)\line
    uHash = _rotl(uHash, 5) - *pw;
\par cwTokens\tab Defines the number of array slots in papwToken, papwTokenEnd, paType, and paHash.
\par fTokenizeSpaces\tab Set of bit flags which determine how tokens are constructed. Can be a combination of these values:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li4145\ri125\fi-2705\brdrb\brdrs\tx4135 \b Value\tab Meaning\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li4145\ri125\fi-2705\tx4135 TOKENIZE_SPACES (0x01)\tab When this bit flag is on, a single space character imbedded between two words will be shown as a token. When the flag is off, it will be ignored.
\par REMOVE_SPACE_CHARS (0x02)\tab When this bit flag is on, all white space characters will be discarded when punctuation tokens are constructed. This means that the *ppwText buffer will be altered. If a punctuation sequence consists of nothing but white space characters, no token will be constructed.
\par STARTING_IMBEDS (0x04)\tab When this flag is on, a punctuation character which may be imbedded in a word is allowed to start a word or a number. An example of such a character is the English decimal point (\plain\f0\fs16 \'93\f1 .\plain\f0\fs16 \'94\f1 ).
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx4135 \b Return Value
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx4135 \plain\f1\fs16 Returns the number of tokens for which information has been constructed.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("FTSWordBreakA")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("FTSWordBreakA")}
