{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0150}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} OpenIndex function}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 1MJJIW0}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} FTS_Search;OpenIndex}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} OpenIndex function}
\b\fs24 OpenIndex
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 INT OpenIndex(HSEARCHER hsrch, PSZ pszIndexFileName, PBYTE pbSourceName, PUINT pcbSourceNameLimit, PUINT pTime1, PUINT pTime2);
\par Opens the given index file for use by the given searcher. It will optionally verify that the supplied *pbSourceName, *pTime1, and *pTime2 values match those stored in the index file.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1795\ri125\fi-1665\brdrb\brdrs\tx1795 \b Parameter\tab Description\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1795\ri125\fi-1665\tx1795 hsrch\tab Handle of the searcher to associate with the dialog box. Must have been previously created using the \b NewSearcher\plain\f1\fs16  function.
\par pszIndexFileName\tab Address of a null-terminated string that specifies the name of the index file to open. The index file is assumed to have been previously created using the \b SaveIndex\plain\f1\fs16  function.
\par pbSourceName\tab Address of the buffer that receives the name of the source files associated with the index. This is the same as the source name associated with the index when created. If on entry this pointer refers to a non-null string, that string will be compared against the source name stored in the index file. The OpenIndex operation will fail if the strings do not compare equal. The comparison, when performed, will also examine *pcbSourceNameLimit.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1795\ri125\fi-1665\tx1795 pcbSourceNameLimit\tab Address of the variable that receives the size in bytes of the source name. On entry that variable is assumed to contain the size of the pbSourceName buffer. If that size is smaller than the original source name, the value copied to pbSourceName will be truncated accordingly.
\par pTime1\tab Address of the variable that receives the low 32 bits of the 64-bit time value associated with the index. If on entry this points to a non-zero value, that value will be compared against the corresponding value in the index file, and the OpenIndex operation will fail if the two values are unequal.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1795\ri125\fi-1665\tx1795 pTime2\tab Address of the variable that receives the high 32 bits of the 64-bit time value associated with the index. If on entry this points to a non-zero value, that value will be compared against the corresponding value in the index file, and the OpenIndex operation will fail if the two values are unequal.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1795 \b Return Value
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1795 \plain\f1\fs16 Returns a non-negative integer identifying the index file if successful and a negative error value otherwise.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("NewSearcher;SaveIndex;fts_errorcode")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("NewSearcher;SaveIndex;fts_errorcode")}
\par \page
