{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} DLLs;DLLs, embedded window message processing;Windows messages, DLL processing}
\b\fs24 Message Processing for Embedded Windows
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Embedded windows receive most standard Windows messages, including mouse and WM_PAINT messages. Embedded windows should not take the input focus; therefore, they do not need to process keystrokes.
\par Embedded window DLLs must also process the following messages, which are specifically defined for use with embedded windows:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{bmc bm1.bmp\}\tab \uldb EWM_RENDER (0x706A)\plain\f1\ul\fs16 {\v *EWM_RENDER}\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{bmc bm1.bmp\}\tab \uldb EWM_QUERYSIZE (0x706B)\plain\f1\ul\fs16 {\v *EWM_QUERYSIZE}\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \{bmc bm1.bmp\}\tab \uldb EWM_ASKPALETTE (0x706C)\plain\f1\ul\fs16 {\v *EWM_ASKPALETTE}\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \{button ,AL(`DLL_WRITE_OVERVIEW')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`DLL_WRITE_OVERVIEW')}
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} EWM_RENDER message}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} EWM_RENDER}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} EWM_RENDER message;messages;messages, EWM_RENDER}
\b\fs24 EWM_RENDER
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 WinHelp sends the EWM_RENDER message to an embedded window to get information about the image in the window. It uses this information when printing the image or placing it in the Clipboard. The wParam parameter to EWM_RENDER indicates the type of information returned by the message, and the LOWORD of the return value contains a handle to this information. Possible wParam values and return values are shown in the following table.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1595\ri125\fi-1445\brdrb\brdrs\tx1595 \b wParam\tab Return Value
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1595\ri125\fi-1445\tx1595 \plain\f1\fs16 CF_TEXT\tab Sharable global handle to a null-terminated ASCII string. WinHelp frees this handle.
\par CF_BITMAP\tab Handle to a bitmap. WinHelp removes this handle.
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} EWM_QUERYSIZE message}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} EWM_QUERYSIZE}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} EWM_QUERYSIZE message;messages;messages, EWM_QUERYSIZE}
\b EWM_QUERYSIZE
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 WinHelp sends the EWM_QUERYSIZE message to an embedded window to obtain the size of the window. The wParam parameter is a handle to the device context for the window. The lParam parameter points to a POINT structure. The embedded window DLL should fill in the \b x\plain\f1\fs16  field of the structure with the window's height and the \b y\plain\f1\fs16  field of the structure with the window's width. WinHelp uses this information when laying out the topic in the topic window, when printing the topic, or when placing it in the Clipboard.
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} EWM_ASKPALLETE message}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} EWM_ASKPALETTE}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} EWM_ASKPALETTE message;messages;messages, EWM_ASKPALETTE}
\b EWM_ASKPALETTE
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 WinHelp sends the EWM_ASKPALETTE message to all embedded windows displayed within a topic to get information about the palettes used in each window. The wParam and lParam parameters are not used.
\par When an embedded window receives an EWM_ASKPALETTE message, it should return a handle to the palette that it uses. WinHelp then selects the most appropriate palette for use in that topic. Usually, this palette is the one used for the first embedded window in the currently displayed part of the topic.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Before the DLL repaints an embedded window, it should send an EWM_ASKPALETTE message to the parent window to determine which palette to use. The following code fragment illustrates how to do this:
\par hpal = (HPALETTE)SendMessage(GetParent(hwnd), EWM_ASKPALETTE, 0, 0L)
\par 
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0166}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Help RTF tokens}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} RTFHelpRTFStatements}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} RTF_overview;RTFHelpRTFStatements}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} Help RTF tokens;rich-text format;RTF files;RTF files, about RTF tokens;RTF tokens;tokens, RTF}
\b\fs24 Help RTF tokens
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Help RTF tokens are an extended subset of tokens defined by the Microsoft Rich Text Format (RTF) standard. The RTF tokens specify character and paragraph properties, such as font, color, spacing, and alignment, for text and graphics in the Help file. The following topics describe the subset of RTF tokens recognized by Help Workshop. Use this information if you plan to edit RTF files directly or create an RTF reader/writer that converts files to RTF format.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("RTF1")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("RTF1")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0167}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Rich-text format}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 1I0I9F}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} RTF1}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} files,;files, RTF;rich-text format;RTF files;RTF files, about rich-text format;RTF reader;topic files;topic files, about rich-text format}
\b\fs24 Rich-Text Format
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The rich-text format (RTF) standard is a method of encoding formatted text and graphics for easy transfer between different programs and different operations. Generally, it is used by all Microsoft Word programs \plain\f0\fs16 \'97\f1  Word for Windows, Word for the Macintosh, and Word for MS-DOS \plain\f0\fs16 \'97\f1  for moving word-processing documents between different platforms without having to rely on special translation software or conversion utilities. Because the RTF standard provides a format for text and graphics interchange that can be used with different output devices and operating systems, Help Workshop also supports this standard. That means you can use almost any text editor that generates RTF output, including your own custom RTF editor, to create the source files that are built into Help files.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Software that takes a formatted file and turns it into an RTF file is referred to as an RTF "writer." Software that translates an RTF file into a formatted file is referred to as an RTF "reader." An RTF writer separates the program's control information from the actual text and writes a new file containing the text and RTF groups associated with that text. An RTF reader does the converse of this operation.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0168}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Elements of RTF}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} .GABF8}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} RTF1}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} files,;files, about RTF files;files, RTF;Help RTF tokens;Help Workshop;Help Workshop, elements of RTF;rich-text format;RTF files;RTF files, about RTF files;RTF tokens;tokens, RTF;topic files;topic files, elements of}
\b\fs24 Elements of RTF
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Help RTF tokens are presented to Help Workshop in topic files, which are specified in the\b  \plain\f1\fs16 [FILES] section of a Help project (.HPJ) file. To Help Workshop a topic file consists of the following elements:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \f1\fs16 RTF tokens
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \f1\fs16 Control symbols
\par \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \f1\fs16 Groups
\par \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \f1\fs16 Unformatted text
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 RTF tokens, control symbols, and braces constitute control information. Text grouping is used to define the format and placement of text and graphics in the Help file. All other characters in RTF text constitute plain text.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("element1;FILES")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("element1;FILES")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0169}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} RTF token syntax}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 42X9YCM}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} element1;RTF1}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} characters;characters, in RTF tokens;Help RTF tokens;RTF files;RTF files, about RTF tokens;RTF tokens;syntax of RTF tokens;tokens, RTF}
\b\fs24 RTF token Syntax
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 An RTFtoken is a formatted tag that specifies a particular kind of information in the RTF file. An RTF token consists of a backslash (\'5c) followed by an RTF token name and a delimiter:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li715\ri125 \'5cstatement-name<delimiter>
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Statments
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 RTF tokens always begin with a backslash (\b \'5c\plain\f1\fs16 ). The statement-name identifies the RTF token and specifies what it does. No spaces or other characters may separate the backslash and the statement-name.
\par An RTF token may optionally have a number parameter immediately after the name. This number must be in the range of a signed integer (-32767 through 32767). No spaces or other characters may separate the name and the numeric parameter (if any).
\par Certain statements control properties (such as bold and italic) that have only two states. When the RTF token has no parameter or has a non-zero parameter, the statement is used to turn the property on. When the RTF token has a 0 (zero) parameter, the statement is used to turn the property off. For example, \b \'5cb\plain\f1\fs16  turns on bold, whereas \b \'5cb0\plain\f1\fs16  turns off bold.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Delimiters
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Delimiters are mandatory characters that separate the statement text of a parameter from subsequent text. A delimiter can be one of the following:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \f1\fs16 A space. The space is considered part of the statement.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab A digit or a minus sign (-), which indicates that a numeric parameter follows. If a numeric parameter immediately follows the statement name, this parameter becomes part of the statement.
\par \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \f1\fs16 Any character other than a letter or digit. The delimiting character terminates the statement but is not considered part of the statement. A "letter" is an upper- or lowercase ASCII letter.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 When a space is used as a delimiter, Help Workshop discards it. If any other character is used, Help Workshop processes it as text or as the start of another RTF token. For example, if a backslash is used as a delimiter, Help Workshop interprets it as the beginning of the next RTF token.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 For example, the following line demonstrates usage of the \b \'5ctab \plain\f1\fs16 statement and a space delimiter:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx355 \{bmc bm4.bmp\}\tab text in paragraph\'5ctab more text
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:016a}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Control symbols}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 0Z.S6A}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} element1}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} backslash character;characters;characters, in control symbols;control symbols;RTF files;RTF files, about control symbols;symbols, control}
\b\fs24 Control Symbols
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 A control symbol consists of a backslash (\'5c) followed by a single non-letter. Control symbols require no further delimiting. The following control symbols are supported:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1795\ri125\fi-1665\brdrb\brdrs\tx1795 \b Control Symbol\tab Meaning
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1795\ri125\fi-1665\tx1795 \plain\f1\fs16 \'5c|\tab Formula character
\par \'5c~\tab Nonbreaking space
\par \'5c-\tab Optional hyphen
\par \'5c_\tab Nonbreaking hyphen
\par \'5c:\tab Subentry in an index entry
\par \'5c'hh\tab Hexadecimal value of a character in the current character set, where h is a hexadecimal digit in the range 0 through F.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:016b}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Groups (RTF)}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 2SVTHYP}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} element1}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} braces characters;characters;characters, in groups;groups;groups, about groups;RTF files;RTF files, about groups}
\b\fs24 Groups
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 A group consists of Help RTF tokens and text enclosed in braces (\b \{\- \'7d\plain\f1\fs16 ). The opening brace \b \{\-\plain\f1\fs16  indicates the start of the group, and the closing brace \b \'7d\plain\f1\fs16  indicates the end of the group, as shown in this example:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{bmc bm4.bmp\}\tab \{\-       group start, and\line
\'7d       group end.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 Different groups perform different functions in the RTF file. Some groups specify information such as the fonts, styles, colors, summary information, and document-format attributes used in the file. Other groups simply include text and the RTF tokens that define attributes for that text. Still other groups specify picture data, footnotes, bookmarks, annotations, and section- and paragraph-formatting attributes for the file.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 Formatting specified within a group affects only the text within that group. Text within a group inherits any formatting of the text preceding the group.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \b Destinations
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 Some statements, referred to as destinations, mark the beginning of a collection of related text. A destination is marked by a control word that signals the beginning of the group. An example of a destination is the group where the Help-specific text follows the statement. Destination statements and their following text must be enclosed in braces, as in this example:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{bmc bm4.bmp\}\tab \{\-\'5cfootnote main_contents\'7d
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:016c}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Unformatted text (RTF)}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 3O1..6U}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} backslash character;brace characters;characters;characters, in unformatted text;rich-text format;RTF files;RTF files, about unformatted text;text,;text, unformatted;unformatted text}
\b\fs24  {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} element1}
Unformatted Text
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Unformatted text consists of any combination of 7-bit ASCII characters. Although characters whose values are greater than 127 are not permitted in topic files, the \b \'5c'\plain\f1\fs16  statement can be used to insert them in the final Help file. Help Workshop treats spaces as part of the text, but it discards carriage return and linefeed characters.
\par Because the backslash character (\'5c) and braces (\{\- \'7d) have specific meanings in RTF, they must be preceded with a backslash if you want to use them as plain text, as shown by the control symbols \b \'5c\'5c\plain\f1\fs16 , \b \'5c\{\-\plain\f1\fs16 , and \b \'5c\'7d\plain\f1\fs16 .
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:016d}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} RTF semantics}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 1TKNZYJ}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} rich-text format;RTF reader;RTF semantics}
\b\fs24  {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} RTF1}
RTF Semantics
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 When reading a stream of RTF text, an RTF reader must accomplish the following tasks:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 1\tab Separate RTF control information from plain text.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 2\tab Act on control information.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li295\ri125\tx295 This is designed to be a relatively simple process, as described in the next section.
\par Some control information just contributes special characters to the plain text stream. Other information changes the program state, which includes document properties as a whole and a stack of group states that apply to parts of the document. The group state is saved by the opening \b \{\-\plain\f1\fs16  brace and is restored by the closing \b \'7d\plain\f1\fs16  brace.
\par The current group state specifies:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li455\ri125\fi-155\tx455 \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \f1\fs16 The destination or part of the document that the plain text is building up.
\par \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \f1\fs16 The section formatting properties.
\par \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \f1\fs16 The paragraph formatting properties.
\par \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \f1\fs16 The character formatting properties.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 3\tab Collect and properly dispose of any remaining plain text as directed by the current group state.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("semantics")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("semantics")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:016e}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Acting on control information (RTF)}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 13IMJK5}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} semantics}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} characters;characters, actions taken by RTF reader;control information, acting on;RTF reader}
\b\fs24 Acting on Control Information
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 When parsing the RTF stream, the RTF reader follows this process:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 1\tab Reads the next character.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 2\tab If the character is an opening brace ( char == '\{\-' ), stores the current state on the stack. 
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li295\ri125\tx295 Or if the current state does not change, it then continues.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 3\tab If the character is a closing brace ( char == '\'7d' ), retrieves the current state from the stack.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li295\ri125\tx295 Generally, this will change the state.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 4\tab If the character is a backslash ( char == '\'5c' ), collects the RTF token or control symbol and its parameter.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li455\ri125\fi-155\tx455 a.\tab Looks up the statement or symbol in the symbol table (a constant table) and acts according to the description found there. The parameter is left available for use by the action.
\par b.\tab Leaves a read pointer before or after the delimiter, as appropriate.
\par c.\tab After completing the action, continues.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 5\tab If the character is anything other than \b \{\-\plain\f1\fs16 , \b \'7d\plain\f1\fs16 , or \b \'5c\plain\f1\fs16 , writes the plain text character to the current destination using the current formatting properties.
\par 6\tab Reads the next character.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:016f}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Acting on symbol table entries (RTF)}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} CTG.X3}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} semantics}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} RTF reader;symbol table entries}
\b\fs24 Acting on Symbol Table Entries
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 When looking up RTF tokens and symbols in the symbol table, the RTF reader can take any of the following actions:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \f1\fs16 Change the destination to the destination described in the table entry.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li295\ri125\tx295 Most destination changes are legal only immediately after an opening brace. Other restrictions may also apply (for example, footnotes may not be nested).
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \f1\fs16 Change formatting property.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li295\ri125\tx295 The symbol table entry will describe the property and whether the parameter is required.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \f1\fs16 Insert a special character.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li295\ri125\tx295 The symbol table entry will describe the character code.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \f1\fs16 End of paragraph.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li295\ri125\tx295 This can also be viewed as just a special character.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \f1\fs16 End of section.
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li295\ri125\tx295 This can also be viewed as just a special character.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \f1\fs16 Ignore the character.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0170}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} The RTF file}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 4H1Q9D}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} RTF1}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} files,;files, about RTF files;files, RTF;RTF files;RTF files, about RTF files}
\b\fs24 The RTF File
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 This section describes the different groups that make up an RTF file. It first presents a sample RTF file, which is used in examples throughout the section. It then describes the required and optional components of an RTF file.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("groups1")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("groups1")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0171}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Sample RTF file}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} VI9DEQ}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} groups1}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} files,;files, RTF;RTF files;RTF files, sample file;sample RTF file}
\b\fs24 Sample RTF File
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The following is an example of a simple but complete, single-topic RTF file that can be compiled by Help Workshop:
\par \pard\keep\sb75\sl-235\li715\ri125 \{\-\'5crtf1\'5cansi \'5cdeff0\'5cdeflang1024\b \line
\line
\plain\f1\fs16 \{\-\'5cfonttbl\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \{\-\'5cf0\'5cfroman Times New Roman;\'7d\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \{\-\'5cf1\'5cfroman Symbol;\'7d\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \{\-\'5cf2\'5cfswiss Arial;\'7d\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \{\-\'5cf3\'5cfroman MS Serif;\'7d\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \{\-\'5cf4\'5cfswiss MS Sans Serif;\'7d\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \'7d\line
\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \{\-\'5ccolortbl;\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \'5cred0\'5cgreen0\'5cblue0;\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \'5cred0\'5cgreen0\'5cblue255;\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \'5cred0\'5cgreen255\'5cblue0;\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \'5cred255\'5cgreen0\'5cblue0;\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \'5cred255\'5cgreen255\'5cblue255;\b \line
\line
\plain\f1\fs16 #\{\-\'5cfootnote graphics_cont\'7d\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 $\{\-\'5cfootnote Graphics\'7d\line
\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \'5cpard\'5cplain \'5cli120\'5csb340\'5csa120\'5csl-320 \'5cf3\'5cfs28 Graphics\b \line
\line
\plain\f1\fs16 \'5cpar \'5cpard\'5cplain \'5cli120 \'5cf4\'5cfs20 Use graphic images to illustrate concepts and present \b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 information visually. Graphics include line art, icons, screen shots of the interface, \line
and graphics with hotspots ("hypergraphics").\line
\'5cpar\line
\'7d
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 As noted earlier, the entire RTF file is one group, so the file begins and ends with braces (\b \{\-\'7d\plain\f1\fs16 ). Other groups nested within the group containing the file define the header and text information.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0172}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Required entries (RTF)}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} UTJD_M}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} groups1}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} files,;files, RTF;required entries in RTF files;RTF files;RTF files, required entries}
\b\fs24 Required Entries
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The following entries must appear in the order shown immediately after the opening brace of the RTF file:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \f1\fs16 The RTF token \b \'5crtf\plain\f1\fs16 n. This RTF token identifies the version (given by the number n) of the RTF standard used in the file. For Help Workshop, this RTF token must be \b \'5crtf1\plain\f1\fs16 .
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \f1\fs16 An RTF token identifying the character set used in the file. The RTF character set described in this appendix corresponds to the \b \'5cansi\plain\f1\fs16  character set statement.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 System default values, such as font number (\'5c\b deff\plain\f1\fs16 n statement), follow the character set statement. The \b \'5cdeff\plain\f1\fs16 n statement specifies which font defined in the font table (see the next section) is the default font for the file.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 The required entries appear as follows in the sample RTF file:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li715\ri125\tx295 \{\-\'5crtf1\'5cansi\'5cdeff0
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0173}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Font table (RTF)}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} KOO4SQ}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} groups1}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} font tables;groups;groups, font table;RTF files;RTF files, font table}
\b\fs24 Font Table
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The first group listed after the opening statements is the font table group. All the fonts that the RTF file uses must be declared in the font table. These fonts should correspond to the fonts that are present on the user's computer.
\par The font table group has the following form:
\par \pard\keep\sb75\sl-235\li715\ri125 \b \{\-\'5cfonttbl\line
\{\-\'5cf\plain\f1\fs16 font-number\b \'5cf\plain\f1\fs16 font-family\b  \plain\f1\fs16 font-name\b ;\'7d\line
\{\-\'5cf\plain\f1\fs16 font-number\b \'5cf\plain\f1\fs16 font-family\b  \plain\f1\fs16 font-name\b ;\'7d\line
\plain\f1\fs16 .\line
.\line
.\line
\b \'7d
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The actual font table is the group beginning with the RTF token \b \'5cfonttbl\plain\f1\fs16 . Each font is defined as a separate group within the font-table group. Each font definition has three components: the font-number, the font-family, and the font-name.
\par The font-number is an integer that identifies the font.
\par The font-family is one of the following standard font families defined by the Windows operating system:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li3325\ri125\fi-3195\brdrb\brdrs\tx1525\tx3325 \b Control Word\tab Font Family\tab Examples
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li3325\ri125\fi-3195\tx1525\tx3325 fnil\plain\f1\fs16 \tab Default or unknown\tab 
\par \b froman\plain\f1\fs16 \tab Roman\tab MS Serif and Palatino
\par \b fswiss\plain\f1\fs16 \tab Swiss\tab Helvetica, MS Sans Serif
\par \b fmodern\plain\f1\fs16 \tab Modern\tab Courier, Elite, Pica
\par \b fscript\plain\f1\fs16 \tab Script\tab Cursive, Script, Zapf Chancery
\par \b fdecor\plain\f1\fs16 \tab Decorative\tab Old English, Zapf Dingbats
\par \b ftech\plain\f1\fs16 \tab Technical\tab Symbol
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1525\tx3325 Each font definition must end with a semicolon (;) immediately before the closing brace.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1525\tx3325 If the RTF file uses a default font, the RTF token \b \'5cdeff\plain\f1\fs16 font-number appears before the font-table group. The font-number is an integer indicating which font in the table is used for the default.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1525\tx3325 \b Example
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1525\tx3325 \plain\f1\fs16 The following group defines nine fonts:
\par \pard\keep\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{bmc bm4.bmp\}\tab \{\-\'5cfonttbl\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \{\-\'5cf0\'5cfroman Times New Roman;\'7d\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \{\-\'5cf1\'5cfroman Symbol;\'7d\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \{\-\'5cf2\'5cfswiss Arial;\'7d\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \{\-\'5cf3\'5cfroman MS Serif;\'7d\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \{\-\'5cf4\'5cfswiss MS Sans Serif;\'7d\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \{\-\'5cf5\'5cfmodern Courier;\'7d\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \{\-\'5cf6\'5cfdecor Zapf Dingbats;\'7d\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \{\-\'5cf7\'5cfswiss Helvetica Condensed;\'7d\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \{\-\'5cf8\'5cfswiss Helvetica;\'7d\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \'7d
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 This example defines the following fonts:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\brdrb\brdrs\tx985\tx2335 \b Font #\tab Font Family\tab Font
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx985\tx2335 0\plain\f1\fs16 \tab Roman\tab Times New Roman
\par \b 1\plain\f1\fs16 \tab Technical\tab Symbol
\par \b 2\plain\f1\fs16 \tab Swiss\tab Arial
\par \b 3\plain\f1\fs16 \tab Roman\tab MS Serif
\par \b 4\plain\f1\fs16 \tab Swiss\tab MS Sans Serif
\par \b 5\plain\f1\fs16 \tab Modern\tab Courier
\par \b 6\tab \plain\f1\fs16 Decorative\tab Zapf Dingbats
\par \b 7\tab \plain\f1\fs16 Swiss\tab Helvetica Condensed
\par \b 8\plain\f1\fs16 \tab Swiss\tab Helvetica
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0174}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Color table (RTF)}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 2MDTY6C}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} groups1}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} color tables;groups;groups, color-table;RTF files;RTF files, color table}
\b\fs24 Color Table
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 If the Help file uses color, the RTF file must also define a color table group to specify the individual colors. The color table group has the following form:
\par \pard\keep\sb75\sl-235\li715\ri125 \{\-\'5ccolortbl;\line
\'5crednumber\'5cgreennumber\'5cbluenumber;\line
\'5crednumber\'5cgreennumber\'5cbluenumber;\line
.\line
.\line
.\line
\'7d
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Each definition specifies a value in the range 0 through 255 for the red, green, and blue components of the color. Unlike font entries in the font table, color entries in the color table do not specify a color number. Instead, Help Workshop assumes that the first color defined is color zero, the second color is color one, and so on.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Example
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The following example defines the standard 16 colors in the Windows palette:
\par \pard\keep\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{bmc bm4.bmp\}\tab \{\-\'5ccolortbl;\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \'5cred0\'5cgreen0\'5cblue0;\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \'5cred0\'5cgreen0\'5cblue255;\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \'5cred0\'5cgreen255\'5cblue255;\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \'5cred0\'5cgreen255\'5cblue0;\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \'5cred255\'5cgreen0\'5cblue255;\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \'5cred255\'5cgreen0\'5cblue0;\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \'5cred255\'5cgreen255\'5cblue0;\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \'5cred255\'5cgreen255\'5cblue255;\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \'5cred0\'5cgreen0\'5cblue127;\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \'5cred0\'5cgreen127\'5cblue127;\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \'5cred0\'5cgreen127\'5cblue0;\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \'5cred127\'5cgreen0\'5cblue127;\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \'5cred127\'5cgreen0\'5cblue0;\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \'5cred127\'5cgreen127\'5cblue0;\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \'5cred127\'5cgreen127\'5cblue127;\b \line
\plain\f1\fs16 \'5cred192\'5cgreen192\'5cblue192;\line
\'7d
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0175}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Style sheet (RTF)}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 23LQBV4}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} groups1}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} groups;groups, style-sheet;RTF files;RTF files, style sheet;style sheets}
\b\fs24 Style Sheet
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 In the standard RTF specification, the style sheet group defines the different styles defined for a document. In Word for Windows, a style is a named combination of formats (including those for characters, paragraphs, tabs, borders, and frames) that authors can apply to text using a defined sequence of keystrokes. Authors can add styles to a document template.
\par Help Workshop ignores the style sheet group in an RTF file. If you plan to use the RTF file only to create a Help file, you can omit the style sheet group from the file to save space. However, if you also plan to print documents from the RTF file, you can include a style sheet group to define styles for the document. Then, when you open the RTF file in Word for Windows, you can apply the styles that you have defined to text.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 A style sheet group has the following format:
\par \pard\keep\sb75\sl-235\li715\ri125 \b \{\-\'5cstylesheet\line
\{\-\'5cs\plain\f1\fs16 style-num\b \'5c\plain\f1\fs16 style-specs style-name\b ;\'7d\line
\{\-\'5cs\plain\f1\fs16 style-num\b \'5c\plain\f1\fs16 style-specs style-name\b ;\'7d\line
\plain\f1\fs16 .\line
.\line
.\line
\b \'7d
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Each style definition appears in a group within the style sheet group. The style definition is identified by a unique style number.
\par The exact style specifications follow the style number. The style specifications can include RTF tokens for any type of character, text, tab, border, or frame formatting.
\par The last part of the style definition is the style name. This is the name that appears in the Word for Windows drop-down list boxes that list the document's styles. A single space must separate the style specifications from the style name.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Each style definition must end with a semicolon (\b ;\plain\f1\fs16 ) immediately before the closing brace.
\par In Word for Windows, styles may be based on previously defined styles. In this case, the style inherits the attributes of the previously defined style. A style may also define a style to be applied to the next paragraph in the document. The following RTF tokens may appear in the style sheet to activate these features:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li2345\ri125\fi-2215\brdrb\brdrs\tx2335 \b Control Word\tab Meaning
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li2345\ri125\fi-2215\tx2335 \'5csbasedon\plain\f1\fs16 style-num\tab The style defined in this group inherits the attributes of the style with the given style number. If this style does not inherit attributes from any style, style-num is 0.
\par \b \'5csnext\plain\f1\fs16 style-num\tab The style with the given style number is applied to the next paragraph in the document. If no style is to be applied to the next paragraph in the document, style-num is 0.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx2335 \b Example
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx2335 \plain\f1\fs16 Here is a portion of a sample style sheet:
\par \pard\keep\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{bmc bm4.bmp\}\tab \{\-\'5cstylesheet\line
\{\-\'5cs229\'5cli2160\'5cri720\'5ctldot\'5ctx8280\'5ctqr\'5ctx8640 \'5cf5\'5cfs20\'5clang1033 \'5csbasedon0\'5csnext0 toc 4;\'7d\line
.\line
.\line
.\line
\{\-\'5cs17\'5cqc\'5csb240\'5csl240\'5ckeepn \'5cb\'5cf5\'5cfs28\'5clang1033 \'5csbasedon0\'5csnext17 head;\'7d\line
\{\-\'5cs18\'5cqj\'5csb240\'5csl240 \'5cb\'5cf5\'5cfs20\'5clang1033 \'5csbasedon0\'5csnext18 Company;\'7d\line
\{\-\'5cs19\'5cqj\'5csb120\'5csl240\'5ckeepn \'5ci\'5cf5\'5cfs20\'5clang1033 \'5csbasedon0\'5csnext19 Product;\'7d\line
\'7d
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 This portion of the style sheet defines four styles numbered 229 (named "toc 4"), 17 (named "head"), 18 (named "Company"), and 19 (named "Product"). Style sheets 17 through 19 assume that the same style will be applied to the next paragraph as well as the paragraph to which the style is currently assigned. None of these styles inherits the attributes of a previously defined style.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0176}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Topic information (RTF)}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 3R07H45}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} groups1;TopicInfo}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} groups;groups, footnote;RTF files;RTF files, topic information;topic files;topic files, about topic information in RTF files;topic information in RTF files;topics,;topics, about topic information in RTF files}
\b\fs24 Topic Information
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 After setting up the required RTF entries for the Help file, you define the topic information. Topics consist of plain text and graphics that the user sees, Help Workshop-specific information that is defined in topic footnotes, character and paragraph formatting information, and page break delimiters.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Font and Formatting Information
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Before any text is placed in the RTF file, the font name and font size must be specified. The \b \'5cf\plain\f1\fs16 n statement specifies the font name (n matches the font number defined in the font table). The \b \'5cfs\plain\f1\fs16 n statement specifies the font size (n is given in half-points). For example, using the sample font table just described, the following example defines the text as 10-point MS Sans Serif: 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{bmc bm4.bmp\}\tab \'5cf4\'5cfs20
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 If you want the text to have any special formatting characteristics, you must also define those before you write out the plain text. Help Workshop supports a number of character and paragraph formatting attributes that you can use to change the appearance and placement of text and graphics.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 The following example defines the topic title text as 14-point MS Serif with 17 points of space before, 6 points of space after, and 16 points of leading. The topic title paragraph is also indented 6 points from the left margin:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{bmc bm4.bmp\}\tab \'5cpard\'5cplain \'5cli120\'5csb340\'5csa120\'5csl-320 \'5cf3\'5cfs28
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \b Help Features in Footnote Groups
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 The following types of Help information are specified in \b \'5cfootnote\plain\f1\fs16  groups:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \uldb \f1\fs16 Topic IDs\plain\f1\fs16 {\v AN2912>tables}
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \uldb \f1\fs16 Topic titles\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 5WM68K>tables}
\par \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \uldb \f1\fs16 Browse sequences\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 142WH9O>tables}
\par \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \uldb \f1\fs16 Keyword index entries\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 1AV0ZGN>tables}
\par \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \uldb \f1\fs16 Help macros run on topic entry\plain\f1\fs16 {\v BA77J.>tables}
\par \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \uldb \f1\fs16 Build tags\plain\f1\fs16 {\v J6P1I>tables}
\par \f2 \'b7\f3\fs12 \tab \uldb \f1\fs16 Comments\plain\f1\fs16 {\v BPRKVR>tables}
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab \uldb Window type\plain\f1\fs16 {\v VKJ5IQ>tables}
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \b Help Features Embedded in Text
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 Some Help features are implemented using common RTF commands or special codes embedded within text. The following types of Help features can be embedded in text:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab \uldb Layout features like nonscrolling regions and nonwrapping text\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 1MHELPH>tables}
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab \uldb Hotspots for activating jumps, displaying pop-up windows, and running Help macros\plain\f1\fs16 {\v XRUN4K>tables}
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab \uldb Bitmaps\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 2.7R04N>tables}
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab \uldb Embedded panes for custom DLL objects\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 8F428Y>tables}
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \b Topic End
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 When there is more than one topic in an RTF file, each topic must end with a \b \'5cpage\plain\f1\fs16  statement.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 Ending the last topic in a file with a \b \'5cpage\plain\f1\fs16  statement is optional.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("RTF_SAMPLE_TOPIC;topic_info",0,"",`tables')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("RTF_SAMPLE_TOPIC;topic_info",0,"",`tables')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0183}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Topic IDs (RTF)}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} AN2912}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} tables}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} topic_info}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} groups;groups, topic IDs;RTF files;RTF files, topic IDs;topic IDs}
\b\fs24 Topic IDs
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Topics within a Help file are usually identified by a unique topic ID. The following group specifies a topic ID for a topic:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li715\ri125 \b #\{\-\'5cfootnote\plain\f1\fs16  topic ID\b \'7d
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx8995 \plain\f1\fs16 A topic ID is any string of up to 255 characters. You can use any character except \b #\plain\f1\fs16 , \b =\plain\f1\fs16 , \b >\plain\f1\fs16 , \b @\plain\f1\fs16 , \b !\plain\f1\fs16 , or \b %\plain\f1\fs16 . The first character of a topic ID cannot be a numeric character.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx8995 For example, this RTF entry defines the topic ID "main contents":
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{bmc bm4.bmp\}\tab #\{\-\'5cfootnote main contents\'7d
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("TopicInfo",0,"",`main')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("TopicInfo",0,"",`main')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0184}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Topic titles (RTF)}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 5WM68K}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} tables}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} topic_info}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} groups;groups, topic titles;RTF files;RTF files, topic titles;titles;titles, about title strings}
\b\fs24 Topic Titles
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Typically, a topic will also contain a topic title, which identifies the topic in Help dialog boxes. The following group specifies a topic title:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li715\ri125 \b $\{\-\'5cfootnote\plain\f1\fs16  title-text\b \'7d\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 A title string is any string of up to 50 characters. Any printable ASCII character may appear in a topic title, except the following reserved characters: # = + > @ * % ! 
\par Topic titles must not begin with a number. ASCII characters such as braces (\{\- \'7d), brackets ([ ]), and backslashes (\'5c) that are used as special characters in RTF must be prefixed by backslashes.
\par This example defines the title "Saving a Document":
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{bmc bm4.bmp\}\tab $\{\-\'5cfootnote Saving a Document\'7d
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("TopicInfo",0,"",`main')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("TopicInfo",0,"",`main')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0185}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Browse sequences (RTF)}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 142WH9O}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} tables}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} topic_info}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} browse sequences;groups;groups, browse sequences;RTF files;RTF files, browse sequences}
\b\fs24 Browse Sequences
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 A topic may belong to a single browse sequence, which is a group of topics the user can view in forward or backward sequence.
\par The following group assigns a topic to a browse sequence and to one or more topic groups:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li715\ri125 \b +\{\-\'5cfootnote\plain\f1\fs16  [sequence-name][\b :\plain\f1\fs16 sequence-number]\b \'7d\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 The sequence-name is the name of the browse sequence to which the topic is assigned. It may be omitted if the Help file has only one browse sequence.
\par The sequence-name may be followed by a sequence-number, which indicates where in the sequence the topic appears. In browse sequences, topics appear in order of sequence numbers. If no sequence number appears, topics in the sequence appear in their physical order within the file. If the [FILES] section of the Help project (.HPJ) file lists more than one RTF file, topics from the first RTF file appear first in the browse sequence, then topics from the second RTF file, and so on.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 A colon must immediately precede the sequence number, if it appears. If a sequence name also appears, a colon must separate the sequence name and sequence number.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("TopicInfo",0,"",`main')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("TopicInfo",0,"",`main')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0186}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Keyword entries (RTF)}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 1AV0ZGN}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} tables}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} topic_info}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} A-keywords;groups;groups, keyword entries;keywords;keywords, about keyword groups;K-keywords;RTF files;RTF files, keyword entries}
\b\fs24 Keyword Entries
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 There are three kinds of keyword entries: K-keywords, A-keywords, and multi-index keywords. Each type of entry has its own topic footnote.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b K-keywords
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 K-keywords, denoted by the custom footnote mark 'K,' are used for searches with the Index button. The Index tab in the Help Topics dialog box displays a list of the keywords defined for topics in the Help file. From the Index, the user can jump to any topic in which a keyword has been defined. K-keywords are also used by the KLink macro to provide inter-topic jumps to the topics having the keywords specified as the macro's parameters.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Multi-index keywords
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Multi-index keywords are denoted by any alpha character except 'A' and 'K.' They have identical index capabilities to K-keywords, but are intended for alternate indexes.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b A-keywords
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 A-keywords, denoted by the custom footnote mark 'A,' are used for \b ALink\plain\f1\fs16  macro jumps only. They do not appear in any index.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Examples
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The following group assigns one or more \scaps k\plain\f1\fs16 -keywords to a topic:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li715\ri125 \b K\{\-\'5cfootnote\plain\f1\fs16  keyword\b ;\plain\f1\fs16 [keyword\b ;\plain\f1\fs16 ]...\b \'7d
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The following group assigns one or more \scaps a\plain\f1\fs16 -keywords to a topic:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li715\ri125 \b A\{\-\'5cfootnote\plain\f1\fs16  keyword\b ;\plain\f1\fs16 [keyword\b ;\plain\f1\fs16 ]...\b \'7d
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The following group assigns one or more multi-index keywords to a topic for an index referenced to R-keywords:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li715\ri125 \b R\{\-\'5cfootnote\plain\f1\fs16  keyword\b ;\plain\f1\fs16 [keyword\b ;\plain\f1\fs16 ]...\b \'7d
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Keywords must be separated by semicolons (\b ;\plain\f1\fs16 ).
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("TopicInfo",0,"",`main')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("TopicInfo",0,"",`main')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0187}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Help macros run on topic entry (RTF)}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} BA77J.}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} tables}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} topic_info}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} groups;groups, macros run on topic entry;macros,;macros, running when a topic is opened;RTF files;RTF files, Help macros run on entry;running macros}
\b\fs24 Help Macros Run on Topic Entry
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Help can run commands automatically when the user jumps to a topic (from a hotspot, browse button, or search list).
\par The following group specifies macros to be run on topic entry:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li715\ri125 \b !\{\-\'5cfootnote \plain\f1\fs16 macro-string\b \'7d\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 The macro-string can be any Help macro documented in this authoring guide or registered in the \b [CONFIG]\plain\f1\fs16  section of the Help project (.HPJ) file.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("TopicInfo",0,"",`main')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("TopicInfo",0,"",`main')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0188}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Build tags (RTF)}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} J6P1I}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} build tags;groups;groups, build tags;RTF files;RTF files, build tags}
\b\fs24 Build Tags
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Build tags are labels used to exclude certain topics from a build. Topics without build tags are always included in the build. Topics with build tags are included or excluded using a build expression in the Help project (.HPJ) file.
\par The following group assigns one or more build tags to a topic:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li715\ri125 \b *\{\-\'5cfootnote\plain\f1\fs16  tag-name\b ;\plain\f1\fs16 [tag-name\b ;\plain\f1\fs16 ]...\b \'7d
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Multiple build tags must be separated by semicolons (\b ;\plain\f1\fs16 ).
\par Help Workshop supports two very different ways of processing build tags. If you use Help Workshop to specify the build tags in topics to include or exclude, then by default, any topic with a build tag will be excluded from the help file. If, however, you use another editor to add/edit the BUILD option and [BUILDTAGS] section, then all topics are included by default, whether or not they have a build tag.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("TopicInfo",0,"",`main')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("TopicInfo",0,"",`main')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0189}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Comments (RTF)}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} BPRKVR}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} tables}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} topic_info}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} comments;groups;groups, comments;Help Workshop;Help Workshop, comments ignored by;RTF files;RTF files, comments}
\b\fs24 Comments
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Comments are any text that you want to include with a topic for your own purposes. Comments are ignored by Help Workshop.
\par The following group assigns a comment to a topic:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li715\ri125 \b @\{\-\'5cfootnote \plain\f1\fs16 comment-text\b \'7d\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Because comments are ignored, the comment-text can have as many standard characters as you want, including accented characters and spaces.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("TopicInfo",0,"",`main')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("TopicInfo",0,"",`main')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:018a}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Window type (RTF)}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} VKJ5IQ}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} tables}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} topic_info}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} groups;groups, window type;RTF files;RTF files, window type;window types}
\b\fs24 Window Type
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Window types are used when you want to display the topic in a window other than the default window when it is accessed from the Index.
\par The following group assigns a window type to a topic:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li715\ri125 \b >\{\-\'5cfootnote\plain\f1\fs16  windowname\b \'7d\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("TopicInfo",0,"",`main')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("TopicInfo",0,"",`main')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:018b}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Layout features (RTF)}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 1MHELPH}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} tables}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} topic_info}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} layout features, specifying;RTF files;RTF files, layout features}
\b\fs24 Layout Features
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The following standard RTF commands are used to specify layout features in Help files:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1705\ri125\fi-1575\brdrb\brdrs\tx1705 \b Control Word\tab Meaning
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1705\ri125\fi-1575\tx1705 \uldb \plain\f1\uldb\fs16 \'5ckeepn\plain\f1\fs16 {\v keepn_rtf>main}\tab Makes affected text and pictures part of the nonscrolling region
\par \uldb \'5ckeep\plain\f1\fs16 {\v keep_rtf>main}\tab Makes affected text and pictures nonwrapping so they are truncated instead of wrapped if the window is resized
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("TopicInfo",0,"",`main')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("TopicInfo",0,"",`main')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:018c}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Hotspots (RTF)}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} XRUN4K}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} tables}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} topic_info}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} groups;groups, hotspots;hotspots;hotspots, about hotspots;RTF files;RTF files, hotspots}
\b\fs24 Hotspots
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 A hotspot is a region within a topic that performs an action when the user selects the region with the mouse. This action may be jumping to another topic, displaying a topic in a pop-up window, or running a Help macro.
\par The following group is used to create pop-up hotspots in a topic:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li715\ri125 \b \{\-\'5cul\plain\f1\fs16  hotspot text\b \'7d\{\-\'5cv \plain\f1\fs16 [\b %|*\plain\f1\fs16 ]topic-ID\b \'7d
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The hotspot text is the topic text that performs the action when the user selects it. This text may be one of the standard \'5c\b \{\-bm\plain\f1\fs16 x\b \'5c\'7d\plain\f1\fs16  RTF commands if the hotspot is a bitmap.
\par The percent sign (%) or asterisk (*) is used if you want to make the hotspot invisible (no green color, no underline) or just underlined (no green color).
\par The topic-ID identifies the topic to be displayed in the pop-up window.
\par The following groups are used to create jump or macro hotspots in a topic:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li715\ri125 \b \{\-\'5culdb\plain\f1\fs16  hotspot text\b \'7d\{\-\'5cv \plain\f1\fs16 [\b %|*\plain\f1\fs16 ]hotspot action\b \'7d
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Or, you can use this format:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li715\ri125 \b \{\-\'5cstrike\plain\f1\fs16  hotspot text\b \'7d\{\-\'5cv \plain\f1\fs16 [\b %|*\plain\f1\fs16 ]hotspot action\b \'7d
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The hotspot text is the topic text that performs the action when the user selects it. This text may be one of the standard \'5c\b \{\-bm\plain\f1\fs16 x\b \'5c\'7d\plain\f1\fs16  RTF commands if the hotspot is a bitmap.
\par The percent sign (%) or asterisk (*) is used if you want to make the hotspot invisible (no green color, no underline) or just underlined (no green color).
\par The hotspot action may be one of the following:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab A jump destination. This action has the following form:
\par \pard\keep\sb55\sl-235\li295\ri125\tx295 topic-ID[\b @\plain\f1\fs16 HLP-filename][\b >\plain\f1\fs16 window-name]
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li295\ri125\tx295 The topic-ID identifies the topic the hotspot jumps to. When present, the second parameter (preceded by an at sign) identifies a different Help file in which the jump destination appears. If the jump destination is to appear in a secondary window, \b >\plain\f1\fs16 window-type identifies the name of window in which the topic is to appear. The window-type must be defined in the [WINDOWS] section of the Help project (.HPJ) file.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab A Help macro. This action has the following form:
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li295\ri125\tx295 \b !\plain\f1\fs16 macro-string
\par The macro-string identifies the action Help performs when the user selects the hotspot. It can be any standard Help macro or any external DLL function registered in the \b [CONFIG]\plain\f1\fs16  section of the project file.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 If the hotspot text is invisible in the title, a percent sign (\b %\plain\f1\fs16 ) immediately precedes the hotspot action.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("TopicInfo",0,"",`main')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("TopicInfo",0,"",`main')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:018d}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Bitmaps (RTF)}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 2.7R04N}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} tables}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} topic_info}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} bitmaps,;bitmaps, adding to topics;graphics;graphics, adding to topics;RTF files;RTF files, bitmaps}
\b\fs24 Bitmaps
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Bitmaps can be inserted into a topic with a command that tells Help the name of the bitmap file and how to position it. This command has the following form:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li715\ri125 \b \'5c\{\-bm\plain\f1\fs16 [\b c |\plain\f1\fs16  \b l |\plain\f1\fs16  \b r\plain\f1\fs16 ] bitmapfile[\b ;\plain\f1\fs16  bitmapfile[\b ;\plain\f1\fs16 ...]]]\b \'5c\'7d\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 The \b \'5c\{\-bm\plain\f1\fs16 x\b \'5c\'7d\plain\f1\fs16  commands specify how the bitmap is aligned in the topic, as shown in the following table:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li1705\ri125\fi-1575\brdrb\brdrs\tx1705 \b Control Word\tab Meaning
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li1705\ri125\fi-1575\tx1705 \uldb \plain\f1\uldb\fs16 \'5c\{\-bmc\'5c\'7d\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 4AWD1BN>main}\tab Positions the bitmap using character alignment. The bitmap is handled as if it were another character and it appears at the position in the line indicated by the reference. Text follows the bitmap, positioned at the base of the bitmap.
\par \uldb \'5c\{\-bml\'5c\'7d\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 11233NT>main}\tab Positions the bitmap along the left margin, with text wrapping automatically along the right edge of the image.
\par \uldb \'5c\{\-bmr\'5c\'7d\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 11833NT>main}\tab Positions the bitmap along the right margin, with text wrapping automatically along the left edge of the image.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1705 The bitmap data is stored separately from the topic text, and a single copy of the bitmap is used for all the \'5c\{\-bmc\'5c\'7d, \'5c\{\-bml\'5c\'7d, and \'5c\{\-bmr\'5c\'7d commands displaying that bitmap. 
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
