{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} from_v2_overview;V2_CREATE_CNT}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} contents files;contents files, creating when converting from Viewer 2.0;creating;creating, contents files;Viewer 2.0;Viewer 2.0, creating}
\b\fs24 Create a Contents File
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 WinHelp version 4.0 supports the use of a \ul contents (.CNT) file,\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 2GB40S} a text file that specifies what topics display in the Contents tab in the \ul Help Topics dialog box.\plain\f1\fs16 {\v KMK38I} The Contents tab replaces the "contents topic" used in both former versions of WinHelp and Viewer version 2.0. The contents file also allows authors to create a combined index using the keywords in other Help (.HLP) files, and to specify which Help files to search when the user clicks a hotspot that runs the ALink or KLink macros.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Help Workshop can be used to create or edit contents files.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("BAS_CNT_OVERVIEW;BAS_CONTENTS_FILE_EDITOR;ALink;KLink")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("BAS_CNT_OVERVIEW;BAS_CONTENTS_FILE_EDITOR;ALink;KLink")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:019c}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Build the new Help file}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} V2_COMPILE_HELP_FILE}
{\up >}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up >} main}
\pard\keepn\sb115\sa115\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} from_v2_overview;V2_COMPILE_HELP_FILE}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} build;Help files;Viewer 2.0;Viewer 2.0, building Help files}
\b\fs24 Build the New Help File
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Once you have updated your topic (.RTF) files and project (.HPJ)files, use Help Workshop version 4.0 to compile the project file and build the Help (.HLP) file. Just click Compile on the File menu in HCW and specify the name of the project file.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("BAS_THE_HELP_COMPILER;BAS_TESTING_HELP_FILES")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("BAS_THE_HELP_COMPILER;BAS_TESTING_HELP_FILES")}
\par 
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE003b:0001}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Empty keyword string}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} HC1000}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} HC1000}
\b\cf2 HC1000:\plain\f1\b\fs16  Note: A keyword footnote has been specified without a keyword.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Problem: \plain\f1\fs16 There are no characters in the keyword footnote in the topic (.rtf) files.
\par \b Result: \plain\f1\fs16 Help Workshop ignores the keyword footnote. If there are no additional keyword footnotes, the topic will be inaccessible from the Index tab in the Help Topics dialog box.
\par \b Solution: \plain\f1\fs16 Add one or more keywords to the keyword footnote, and then recompile.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`BAS_ADDING_KEYWORDS')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`BAS_ADDING_KEYWORDS')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE003b:0002}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Duplicate keyword}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} HC1001}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} HC1001}
\b\cf2 HC1001:\plain\f1\b\fs16  Note: The keyword [\'a0] is already defined in this topic.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Problem: \plain\f1\fs16 The same keyword has be defined more than once in a topic.
\par \b Result: \plain\f1\fs16 Help Workshop ignores the duplicate keyword.
\par \b Solution: \plain\f1\fs16 Open the topic and remove the duplicate.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`BAS_ADDING_KEYWORDS')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`BAS_ADDING_KEYWORDS')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE003b:0003}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Using existing phrase table}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} HC1002}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} HC1002}
\b\cf2 HC1002:\plain\f1\b\fs16  Note: Using existing phrase table: [\'a0].
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Problem: \plain\f1\fs16 Help Workshop found an existing phrase (.ph) table for the Help file you are building, and the project (.hpj) file does not specify not to use the table.
\par \b Result: \plain\f1\fs16 Help Workshop uses the phrase table that was generated from an earlier build instead of creating a new table.
\par \b Solution: \plain\f1\fs16 To achieve the best phrase compression when compiling your Help file, you must delete the old key-phrase table before each recompilation, or clear the "Use old phrase file" option in the Compression tab in the Options dialog box of Help Workshop.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`OLDKEYPHRASE;BAS_COMPRESSION')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`OLDKEYPHRASE;BAS_COMPRESSION')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE003b:0004}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Hidden paragraph marker}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} HC1003}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} HC1003}
\b\cf2 HC1003:\plain\f1\b\fs16  Note: A paragraph mark is formatted as a hidden character.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Problem: \plain\f1\fs16 A paragraph mark has been formatted as hidden text. This often occurs when a hotspot is the last word in a paragraph.
\par \b Result: \plain\f1\fs16 Help Workshop ignores the paragraph mark, so the two paragraphs will run together.
\par \b Solution: \plain\f1\fs16 Reformat the paragraph marker as plain text in the topic file, and then recompile.
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Previous .BMP command incomplete}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} HC1004}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} HC1004}
\b\cf2 HC1004:\plain\f1\b\fs16  Note: A previous instance of [\'a0] does not contain [\'a0].
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Problem: \plain\f1\fs16 A \{\-bmx\'7d command specifying only one resolution version of a bitmap is followed later in the topic files by a \{\-bmx\'7d command specifying that version plus one or more additional versions.
\par \b Result: \plain\f1\fs16 WinHelp will treat the earlier single-resolution command as if it were the same as the command specifying multiple resolutions.
\par \b Solution: \plain\f1\fs16 Replace the single resolution command with a copy of the multiple-resolution command.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`BAS_MULT_COLOR_GRAPHICS;bmx')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`BAS_MULT_COLOR_GRAPHICS;bmx')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE003b:0005}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Parameter not unsigned number}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} HC1005}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} HC1005}
\b\cf2 HC1005:\plain\f1\b\fs16  Note: [\'a0] is not an unsigned number for the macro [\'a0]. The sign will be ignored.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Problem: \plain\f1\fs16 The parameter for this macro should be unsigned, but the number has been prefixed with a minus character.
\par \b Result: \plain\f1\fs16 Help Workshop will remove the minus sign when it creates the Help file.
\par \b Solution: \plain\f1\fs16 Remove the minus sign from the macro definition, and then recompile.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`syntax_more')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`syntax_more')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE003b:0006}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} ExecProgram used}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} HC1006}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} HC1006}
\b\cf2 HC1006:\plain\f1\b\fs16  Note: The ExecProgram macro has been used instead of ExecFile.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Problem: \plain\f1\fs16 The \b ExecProgram\plain\f1\fs16  macro has been used.
\par \b Result: \plain\f1\fs16 The ExecProgram macro ignores the restricted programs that can be set in Windows\'a095. It will not search the registry from programs, so some programs cannot be launched with this command.
\par \b Solution: \plain\f1\fs16 Replace instances of ExecProgram macro commands with ExecFile macro commands, and then recompile.
