\pard\sb75\sl-235\li85\ri125 Specifies the location and name of the Help file that you want to view.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 5_9F_8R}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li85\ri125 Opens the specified Help file, based on the settings you selected in this dialog box.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 8I0J_M}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li85\ri125 Opens the specified Help file as if it were called from the WinHelp API HELP_FINDER command.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} _QVCON}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li85\ri125 Displays the topic specified in the Mapped Topic IDs box as a pop-up.
\par \page
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li85\ri125 {\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 4OGMHMD}
Displays the specified Help file as a training card. Training cards are a set of Help topics in secondary windows that are configured to send information to and receive it from another program.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 3UI38E}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li85\ri125 Opens the specified Help file as if it were a double-clicked file icon or as if it were invoked from an MS-DOS command prompt.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 1CDSILW}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li85\ri125 Click this to locate the file you want to include
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 2FXO1Q}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li85\ri125 Refreshes the list of mapped topic IDs for the project (.hpj) file specified above. You should click this whenever you specify a different project file.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} FXFU0Y}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li85\ri125 Enter up to 8 characters for the name of the window type. This name can be used in jumps, macros, and the window footnote.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 11EDRE4}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li85\ri125 Procedure: This window type is normally used for displaying procedures. It is auto-sizing, contains three buttons on the button bar, and is positioned in the upper right corner of the screen.
\par Reference: This window type is normally used for displaying reference material. It is auto-sizing, contains three buttons on the button bar, and is positioned on the left side of the screen and takes up approximately two thirds of the width of the screen.
\par Error message: This window type is normally used for displaying error messages. It is auto-sizing, contains no buttons, and lets WinHelp determine the position (upper right corner of the screen unless the user changes the position).
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 42C369S}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li85\ri125 Provides a place for you to type the prefix in your project file that you want to replace.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 328BXCT}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li85\ri125 If this box is checked and Help Author is enabled, two new fields appear in the Topic Information dialog box, which appears when you use your right mouse button to click a topic, and then click Topic Information. The additional fields show which topic (.rtf) file the topic is in and what the topic ID is. This feature is especially useful for testing, debugging, and editing topics \plain\f0\fs16 \'97\f1   but it does increase the size of your Help file. Therefore, make sure this box is clear when you compile your file for the last time.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 95ONKB}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li85\ri125 Lists most of the project information for the Help file, including Windows, Configuration, and most of the Options information. You can use this information to create a project file, by saving the report with an .hpj extension, and opening it in Help Workshop as a project file. 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} HW.3Q8}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li85\ri125 Click this for more information about the settings in this dialog box.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 19OLO8B}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li85\ri125 Click this to include an ASCII text file that contains a list of defined window types.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} OYZ0US}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li85\ri125 An ASCII text file, called a \plain\f0\fs16 \'93\f1 project file,\plain\f0\fs16 \'94\f1  that contains information Help Workshop uses to combine topic (.rtf) files and other elements into a Help file.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 2MZQ100}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li85\ri125 An ASCII text file, called a \plain\f0\fs16 \'93\f1 contents file,\plain\f0\fs16 \'94\f1  that contains information Help Workshop uses to create contents and indexing information for a Help file.
\par 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} T.A_S1}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\ri125\tx535 \b \{bmlt bm15.bmp\}\tab Tips of the Day
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri355\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 Tips of the Day introduce new Help Workshop features that make it easier to create, compile, and test your Help files. Each tip provides information that will help you get the most out of Help Workshop. To turn Tips of the Day off or on, click Help, and then click Tip Of The Day. To print a Tip of the Day, use your right mouse button to click it, and then click Print Topic.
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} ZI0CV.}
\pard\sl-235\ri125\tx535 \b \{bmlt bm15.bmp\}\tab Tip: Including and excluding topics
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri355\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 You can exclude specific topics when you compile a Help file. This is useful if you want to create different versions of a help file based on specific criteria. For example, you can exclude incomplete topics or topics that are only relevant under specific circumstances. For more information, look up \plain\f0\fs16 \'93\f1 Build tags\plain\f0\fs16 \'94\f1  in Help for Help Workshop.
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 4KHKWB}
\pard\sl-235\ri125\tx535 \b \{bmlt bm15.bmp\}\tab Tip: Extracting information from a Help file
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri355\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 You can create jumps to topics in other Help files by determining what ALinks and KLinks were used in the file. To extract ALink and KLink information from a compiled Help file, click the File menu, and then click Report. For help on an item in the Report dialog box, click \{bmc bm0.bmp\} in its title bar, and then click the item.
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri355\tx535 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 3.WHVFP}
\pard\sl-235\ri125\tx535 \b \{bmlt bm15.bmp\}\tab Tip: Viewing WinHelp messages
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 Help Workshop provides information about almost every command a program sends to WinHelp, every macro that WinHelp runs, the topic number and title of every topic that appears, the command for every hotspot you click, and more. To view this information, click the View menu, and then click WinHelp Messages.
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 179QAQJ}
\pard\sl-235\ri125\tx535 \b \{bmlt bm15.bmp\}\tab Tip: Smarter compiling
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 You can compile a project file without opening it. To do this, click the File menu, and then click Compile. In the dialog box, you can choose settings that make compiling faster and testing easier. For example, you can temporarily turn off compression so files compile faster or include each topic's topic ID and the name of the .rtf file the topic is in. For help on an item in the Compile A Help File dialog box, click \{bmc bm0.bmp\} in its title bar, and then click the item.
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} CVTDVX}
\pard\sl-235\ri125\tx535 \b \{bmlt bm15.bmp\}\tab Tip: Specifying bitmaps for different display types
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 You can combine bitmaps with different color depths by specifying all the bitmaps in your topic (.rtf) file, separated by semicolons. WinHelp will choose the bitmap whose color depth most closely matches a user's display. For example:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li545\ri125\tx535 \b \{\-bmc\plain\f1\fs16  \b mono.bmp; 16.bmp; 256.bmp\'7d
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li545\ri125\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 For more information, see Help in Help Workshop.
\par \pard\sl-235\li545\ri125\tx535 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 1FX.JL3}
\pard\sl-235\ri125\tx535 \b \{bmlt bm15.bmp\}\tab Tip: Testing the jumps in your contents file
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 You can determine whether the jumps in your contents (.cnt) file are correct by clicking the Test menu, and then clicking Contents File. This command tests the syntax of the specified contents file, and then tests each jump. If an error occurs, a message that contains information about the incorrect jump appears. For more information, see Help in Help Workshop.
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} YGRC.F}
\pard\sl-235\ri125\tx535 \b \{bmlt bm15.bmp\}\tab Tip: Displaying general topic information
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 You can display information about each Help topic, in addition to more detailed error messages, by clicking the File menu and making sure Help Author is checked. This causes a topic number to appear in the title bar of each Help topic. It also provides two additional commands on the context menu that can help you test your files. For more information, see Help in Help Workshop.
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} D22V}
\pard\sl-235\ri125\tx535 \b \{bmlt bm15.bmp\}\tab Tip: Navigating within a Help file
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 To easily navigate within a Help file, click the File menu, and then make sure Help Author is checked. If a Help topic is open, you can move between topics by using key combinations. To move forward or backward one topic at a time, use \scaps ctrl+shift+right arrow\plain\f1\fs16  or \scaps ctrl+shift+left arrow. \plain\f1\fs16 To jump to the beginning or the end of your Help file, use \scaps ctrl+shift+home \plain\f1\fs16 or \scaps ctrl+shift+end\plain\f1\fs16 . To jump to a specific topic, use \scaps ctrl+shift+j\plain\f1\fs16 . For more information, see Help in Help Workshop.
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 11TC01R}
\pard\sl-235\ri125\tx535 \b \{bmlt bm15.bmp\}\tab Tip: Determining a topic's ID and source file
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 If the Help Author command on the File menu is checked, and you use your right mouse button to click any topic (including pop-ups), you can click Topic Information to view information about a topic. If the Include .Rtf Filename And Topic ID box in the Compile A Help File dialog box was checked when the Help file was compiled, information about the .rtf file a topic is in, in addition its topic ID also appears. For more information, see Help in Help Workshop.
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 41J4_7F}
\pard\sl-235\ri125\tx535 \b \{bmlt bm15.bmp\}\tab Tip: Jumping to specific topics
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 You can jump to a specific topic in a Help file by pressing \scaps ctrl+shift+j\plain\f1\fs16  in a topic window, and then specifying a topic ID or number. You can also run any macro by typing an exclamation mark (!), and then typing the short name of the macro.
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} JH.N6N}
\pard\sl-235\ri125\tx535 \b \{bmlt bm15.bmp\}\tab Tip: More flexibility in assigning topic IDs
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 You are no longer limited to using alphabetic and numeric characters for unmapped topic ID names. (Unmapped topic IDs identify topics that are not called from a program.) You can now use spaces, some punctuation, and extended characters in unmapped topic ID names. For more information, see Help in Help Workshop.
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 2AMEUNP}
\pard\sl-235\ri125\tx535 \b \{bmlt bm15.bmp\}\tab Tip: Viewing mapped Help topics
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 You can easily jump to every mapped topic ID in your project file by clicking the File menu, and then clicking Run WinHelp. After you specify Help (.hlp) and project (.hpj) filenames, and then click the Refresh button, all the mapped topic IDs appear in the Mapped Topic IDs list. You can view individual topics or view all topics in sequence. For more information, see context-sensitive Help in the View Help File dialog box.
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 54JNZXE}
\pard\sl-235\ri125\tx535 \b \{bmlt bm15.bmp\}\tab Tip: Adding the compile date to the Version dialog box
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 You can add the date on which your Help file was compiled to WinHelp's version dialog box. To do this, open your .hpj file, and then click the Options button. In the Display This Text In The Version Dialog Box area, add the following to the end of any text that appears there:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li545\ri125\tx535 \b %date\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li545\ri125\tx535 The date will appear in English and cannot be translated. 
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} H2KH2}
\pard\sl-235\ri125\tx535 \b \{bmlt bm15.bmp\}\tab Tip: Specifying a window type for individual topics
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 You can specify the window type that a topic should appear in when it is displayed from the Index or Find tab. To do this, use a greater-than sign (>) footnote in your .rtf file, and then specify the window type you want the topic to appear in. For example:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li545\ri125\tx535 \b > main
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li545\ri125\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 For more information, see Help in Help Workshop.
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 5BR5WS}
\pard\sl-235\ri125\tx535 \b \{bmlt bm15.bmp\}\tab Tip: Making a bitmaps background transparent
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 You can make the background of a 16-color bitmap transparent by adding the letter "t" to the bitmap statement in your .rtf file, as in the following example:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li545\ri125\tx535 \b \{\-bmlt 16color.bmp\'7d\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li545\ri125\tx535 For more information, see Help in Help Workshop.
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} A4B09Z}
\pard\sl-235\ri125\tx535 \b \{bmlt bm15.bmp\}\tab Tip: Associating macros with keywords
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 You can easily specify a macro that runs whenever a user chooses a particular keyword in the Help Index. To do this, open your .hpj file, and then click Options. Click the Macros tab, and then click Add. You can then specify the keyword and title that will appear on the Help Index tab and in the Topics Found dialog box. When a user double-clicks the keyword or title, WinHelp launches the macro. For help on an item in the Keyword Macros dialog box, click \{bmc bm0.bmp\} in its title bar, and then click the item.
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 55WJ_61}
\pard\sl-235\ri125\tx535 \b \{bmlt bm15.bmp\}\tab Tip: Displaying pop-ups if ALinks or KLinks fail
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 You can specify a pop-up topic that appears if an ALink or KLink jump fails. For example, if the destination file is unavailable, you can display information about how users can obtain or install the file. For more information, see Help in Help Workshop.
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 6XTI.R4}
\pard\sl-235\ri125\tx535 \b \{bmlt bm15.bmp\}\tab Tip: Specifying the background color for pop-ups
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 You can choose a background color for pop-up topics by using the SetPopupColor macro. To change all pop-up \plain\f0\fs16 \'96\f1  topic colors, open your project (.hpj) file, click Config, and then specify the SetPopupColor macro. To specify the color for an individual pop-up topic, specify the SetPopColor macro with the PopupId macro for the pop-up's hotspot. For more information, see Help in Help Workshop.
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 3L0X9VY}
\pard\sl-235\ri125\tx535 \b \{bmlt bm15.bmp\}\tab Tip: Getting Help on error messages
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 If you receive an error message while you compile a file and aren't sure what it means, look up the error in Help. Help provides a description of all error messages and recommends solutions. For example, if you receive error HC1003, look up "HC1003" in the Help Index for Help Workshop. 
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 07S6ZO}
\pard\sl-235\ri125\tx535 \b \{bmlt bm15.bmp\}\tab Tip: Localizing typographer's quotes
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 Help Workshop can convert the typographer's quotes (\plain\f0\fs16 \'93\'94\f1 )\plain\f0\fs16  \f1 in your .rtf file to quotation marks that are appropriate for specific languages. To localize these quotes, open your project (.hpj) file, and then click Options. Click the Sorting tab, and then specify a language. For more information, see Help in Help Workshop.
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 002Q9Q}
\pard\sl-235\ri125\tx535 \b \{bmlt bm15.bmp\}\tab Tip: Using bitmaps supplied by Help Workshop
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 You can use standard bitmaps that are supplied by Help Workshop. Although these bitmaps may not be in your bitmaps directory, you can specify them in your .rtf file. For more information, see Help in Help Workshop.
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 5.PB_MN}
\pard\sl-235\ri125\tx535 \b \{bmlt bm15.bmp\}\tab Tip: No need for quotation marks in macros
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 As a general rule, you do not need to use quotes in macros if they appear in either your topic file or project file. Help Workshop supplies all the quotes for you and determines which type of quote to use in nested macros.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li545\ri125\tx535 Help Workshop automatically converts all macros to their shortest form. You can use the long name of a macro to add legibility to your .rtf files without affecting the size of your Help file.
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 6SSR.LP}
\pard\sl-235\ri125\tx535 \b \{bmlt bm15.bmp\}\tab Tip: Running macros when a secondary window opens
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 You can specify macros that run the first time a secondary window opens. For example, you may want to specify macros that close other secondary windows or that add buttons to the button bar. To specify a macro for a secondary window, open your project (.hpj) file, click the Windows button, and then click the Macros tab. For help on an item in the Window Properties dialog box, click \{bmc bm0.bmp\} in its title bar, and then click the item.
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 22WHJZF}
\pard\sl-235\ri125\tx535 \b \{bmlt bm15.bmp\}\tab Tip: Viewing messages that programs send to WinHelp
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 You can determine exactly what Topic IDs a program sends to WinHelp by clicking the View menu in Help Workshop, and then clicking WinHelp Messages. If the project file has never been opened or compiled by Help Workshop, only the mapped numeric values appear. However, if the project file has been opened or compiled at least once, the Topic ID is displayed along with its mapped numeric value.
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} CIZWZ8}
\pard\sl-235\ri125\tx535 \b \{bmlt bm15.bmp\}\tab Tip: Specifying whether a window should auto-size
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 \plain\f1\fs16 You can set up topic windows so that their length is automatically adjusted to accommodate the amount of text in the topic. To do this, open your project (.hpj) file in Help Workshop, click the Windows button, and then select or clear the Auto-Size Height check box. For help on an item in the Window Properties dialog box, click \{bmc bm0.bmp\} in its title bar, and then click the item.
\par \pard\sl-235\li535\ri125\tx535 
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:00d2}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} To create a jump to a topic or pop-up topic}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} PRO_INSERT_JUMP}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} PRO_INSERT_JUMP}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} % (percent sign) in jumps;@ (at sign) in jumps;> (greater-than sign);> (greater-than sign), in jumps;adding;adding, jumps to topics;at sign (@) in jumps;colors;colors, hotspots;creating;creating, hotspots;creating, jumps;double-underline;greater-than sign (>);greater-than sign (>), in jumps;hotspots;hotspots, creating;hotspots, for jumps;interfile jumps;jumps;jumps, color of;jumps, specifying window type for;jumps, to a pop-up topic;jumps, to another Help file;jumps, to another topic;linking multiple Help files;percent sign (%) in jumps;pop-up windows;pop-up windows, creating jumps to;single-underline;topics,;topics, adding hotspots to;underline character style for hotspots}
\b To create a jump to a topic or pop-up topic
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 1\tab Place the insertion point directly after the text or bitmap that you want to be the \ul hotspot,\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 7BM6.K} and then type the topic ID of the topic you want to jump to. Do not put a space between the hotspot and the topic ID.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 2\tab Select the hotspot and then:
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li455\ri125\fi-155\tx455 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Apply the double-underline character style if you want another topic to be displayed.
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Apply the single-underline character style if you want a \ul pop-up topic,\plain\f1\fs16 {\v QAWJFN} to be displayed.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 3\tab Select the topic ID, and then apply the hidden character style.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \b Example
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li455\ri125\fi-155\tx455 \plain\f1\fs16 \{bmct bm16.bmp\}
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx455 \b Tips
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab If the hotspot text ends in a punctuation mark, include the mark when you apply the double-underline character style. Otherwise, a line break could cause the mark to appear at the beginning of a line.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab To display the hotspot in the default text color (nongreen), insert an asterisk (*) at the beginning of the topic ID.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li455\ri125\fi-155\tx455 \{bmct bm17.bmp\}
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab To display the hotspot in the default text color (nongreen), without an underline, insert a percent sign (%) at the beginning of the topic ID.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li455\ri125\fi-155\tx455 \{bmct bm18.bmp\}
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab To create a jump to a topic in another Help file, insert an at sign (@) and the name of the other Help file at the end of the topic ID.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li455\ri125\fi-155\tx455 \{bmct bm19.bmp\}
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab To specify a window type for the topic you jump to, insert a greater than sign (>) and the window name at the end of the topic ID.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li455\ri125\fi-155\tx455 \{bmct bm20.bmp\}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:00d3}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} To add a hotspot that runs a macro}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} PRO_INSERT_MACRO}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} PRO_INSERT_MACRO}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} ! (exclamation point);! (exclamation point), in macro hotspots;adding;adding, macros in topics;creating;creating, hotspots;exclamation point (!);exclamation point (!), in macro hotspots;hotspots;hotspots, creating;hotspots, for macros;macros,;macros, adding hotspots for;macros, running from a hotspot;running macros;topics,;topics, adding hotspots for macros}
\b To add a hotspot that runs a macro
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 1\tab Place the insertion point directly after the text or bitmap reference that you want to be the \ul hotspot,\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 7BM6.K} and then type an exclamation point (!). Do not leave a space between the exclamation point and the hotspot.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 2\tab Type the macro command. Multiple macros can be specified by separating them with a colon (:) or semicolon(;).
\par 3\tab Select the hotspot, and then apply the double-underline character style.
\par 4\tab Select the exclamation point and the macro command, and then apply the hidden character style.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \b Examples
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 \{bmct bm21.bmp\}
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \{bmct bm22.bmp\}
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \{button ,AL(`MACRO_REF_OVR;BAS_ASSOCIATIVE_JUMPS')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`MACRO_REF_OVR;BAS_ASSOCIATIVE_JUMPS')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:00d4}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} To create a bitmap that contains multiple hotspots}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} PRO_MULT_HTSPT_GRPHC}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} PRO_MULT_HTSPT_GRPHC}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} adding;adding, hotspots to bitmaps;bitmaps;bitmaps, creating multiple hotspots in;creating;creating, multiple-hotspot bitmaps;graphics;graphics, creating multiple hotspots in;Hotspot Editor;Hotspot Editor, creating multiple-hotspot bitmaps;hotspots;hotspots, creating;hotspots, in graphics;jumps;jumps, in graphics;multiple-hotspot bitmaps}
\b To create a bitmap that contains multiple hotspots
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 \{bmc bm4.bmp\}\tab Click here  \uldb \{bmct bm3.bmp\}{\v !EF(`shed.exe',`',1)}\plain\f1\fs16   to start Hotspot Editor.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 For information about how to create a bitmap that contains multiple hotspots, click the Help menu in Hotspot Editor.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:00d5}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} To add a bitmap to a topic}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} PRO_ADD_PICTURE}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} PRO_ADD_PICTURE}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} adding;adding, bitmaps to topics;aligning;aligning, bitmaps in topics;bitmaps;bitmaps, adding to topics;graphics;graphics, adding to topics;topics,;topics, adding bitmaps to}
\b To add a bitmap to a topic
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 1\tab Place the insertion point where you want to display the bitmap.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 2\tab To add a single instance of a bitmap, simply copy and paste it. 
\par \tab If you will use \ul multiple instances\plain\f1\fs16 {\v E08QKF} of the bitmap, create a link to its file by using the following syntax:
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li295\ri125\tx295 \b \{\-bm\plain\f1\fs16 x filename.bmp\b \'7d
\par \plain\f1\fs16 For x, specify one or two of the values in the table below. For filename.bmp, specify the name of your bitmap file.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li895\ri125\fi-625\brdrb\brdrs\tx895 \b Value\tab Description
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li895\ri125\fi-625\tx895 c\plain\f1\fs16 \tab Aligns the bitmap as a text character.
\par \b l\plain\f1\fs16 \tab Aligns the bitmap with the left margin.
\par \b r\plain\f1\fs16 \tab Aligns the bitmap with the right margin.
\par \b t\plain\f1\fs16 \tab Used with any of the above values, this indicates that the white pixels of the bitmap should be converted to the solid color closest to the background color of the window. This can be used only with 16-color bitmaps.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx895 \b Note
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab You can specify multiple bitmaps by separating their names with a semicolon. In this case, WinHelp displays the bitmap that most closely matches the number of colors that can be displayed on a user's computer. For more information, click Related Topics.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \{button ,AL(`PRO_MULT_COLOR_GRAPHICS;PRO_COMP_RESOLUTIONS;BAS_ADDING_GRAPHICS;BAS_MULT_RESOLUTION')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`PRO_MULT_COLOR_GRAPHICS;PRO_COMP_RESOLUTIONS;BAS_ADDING_GRAPHICS;BAS_MULT_RESOLUTION')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:00d6}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} To add video or animation to a topic}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} PRO_ADD_VIDEO}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} PRO_ADD_VIDEO}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} adding;adding, multimedia to topics;animation;animation, adding to topics;multimedia;multimedia, adding to topics;sound, adding to topics;topics,;topics, adding multimedia to;video;video, adding to topics}
\b To add video or animation to a topic
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 1\tab Place the insertion point where you want to add the multimedia file.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 2\tab Type the reference in the following syntax:
\par \pard\sb55\sl-235\li295\ri125\tx295 \b \{\-mci \plain\f1\fs16 filename.ext\b \'7d\plain\f1\fs16 
\par For filename.ext, specify the name of the multimedia file you want to add.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \b Note
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab You can specify options for the multimedia file and can align the embedded window. For more information, see the \uldb mci\plain\f1\fs16 {\v J8.SKN} command reference.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:00d7}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} To configure a bitmap for multiple color depths}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} PRO_MULT_COLOR_GRAPHICS}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} PRO_MULT_COLOR_GRAPHICS}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} bitmaps;bitmaps, color depth;color depth;graphics;graphics, color depth;multiple color depth graphics}
\b To configure a bitmap for multiple color depths
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 1\tab Create a bitmap file for each \ul color depth\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 1NQNUGQ} that you want to make available.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 2\tab Place the insertion point where you want the bitmap to be displayed, and then create a bitmap statement that includes each filename. Separate filenames with semicolons, as shown in the example. 
\par \tab WinHelp automatically uses the bitmap file that is most appropriate for a user's computer.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \b Example
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f1\fs16 \{\-bml\'a0dog_16.bmp;dog_256.bmp;dog_mono.bmp\'7d
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \{button ,AL(`PRO_ADD_PICTURE;BAS_MULT_COLOR_GRAPHICS;BAS_MULT_RESOLUTION;BAS_ADDING_GRAPHICS')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`PRO_ADD_PICTURE;BAS_MULT_COLOR_GRAPHICS;BAS_MULT_RESOLUTION;BAS_ADDING_GRAPHICS')}
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} E08QKF}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 If you use a bitmap in more than one place in your Help file, use a bitmap statement to create a link to it instead of copying and pasting the image. This reduces the size of your Help file because only one copy of the bitmap needs to be included in the file.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 9UIBLJ}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 The absolute position is a setting that tells WinHelp that the coordinate values you specify for a window definition are to reflect the number of pixels, regardless of screen resolution. As a result, the size and position of the window will vary widely on different monitors, but the text in the windows will always wrap at the same places. If this setting is not specified, WinHelp adjusts the settings for the resolution of the monitor on which the Help file is displayed, and the window size and position will be roughly the same on all monitors, regardless of resolution.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} ABYXEJ}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 An accelerator key is a keystroke that provides a keyboard equivalent to commands displayed on menus or a button bar.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 7V8V.U}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 An ALink macro provides a link to topics by means of keywords listed in the A-footnotes of topic (.rtf) files. When a user clicks a hotspot that runs an ALink macro specifying a keyword, WinHelp jumps to the topic that contains the keyword, or, if more than one topic contains the same keyword, WinHelp displays the Topics Found dialog box listing the titles of the topics. Keywords used in A-footnotes are reserved for use by ALink macros only.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 2GB40S}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 A contents (.cnt) file provides the information for the Contents tab, such as the titles of topics. You can also use a contents file to group multiple files, and to specify additional files to search in ALink and KLink macros. The contents file is specified in the project (.hpj) file.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} FO6MEW}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 An authorable button is a button in the text area of a Help window that can be used as a hotspot or to run macros. You can specify the text label for an authorable button.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} MFKK8E}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Browse buttons are right-arrow (>>) and left-arrow (<<) buttons that the user clicks to display the next topic or the previous topic in a browse sequence.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 6KLNWH}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 A browse code is a number or character string in the A-footnote of a topic to specify the topic's position in a browse sequence.  The topics are sorted in ascending order by using browse codes. 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 1SRKR1R}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 A browse sequence is a group of topics that the user can display one at a time, forward or backward, by clicking the browse buttons.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 12MF62E}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 A build tag is an optional label that you use to specify whether a topic should be included in or excluded from a specific build. Build tags let you prepare several different Help files from a single set of topic files. After you have assigned build tags to topics, you can specify in the project (.hpj) file which topics to include in the build. 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} C02ROW}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 A citation is a message that you specify to appear at the end of the text when a user copies or prints a topic.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 1NQNUGQ}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Color depth is the number of solid colors a computer can display on its monitor at one time.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} JNVVI2}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 A context menu is the menu that appears when the user clicks the right mouse button in a Help window.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 2O07FH3}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 A context number (or map number) is a unique value you assign to a topic that you want another program to call directly (as in the case of context-sensitive Help). The program passes this value to WinHelp to display the associated topic.  You specify context numbers for topics in the [MAP] section of the project (.hpj) file. Context numbers are used by the JumpContext macro.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 6R9AD_}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Custom buttons are buttons on a Help window's button bar created by using the CreateButton macro.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 2KN4_IS}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 The default Help file is the file WinHelp searches for the topic IDs listed in the contents (.cnt) file (unless the topic statement specifies another help file). The default Help file is specified in the contents file.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 32JI7C9}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 The default topic is the topic WinHelp displays whenever the user initiates a jump to a topic that is unavailable. For Help files that do not have an associated contents (.cnt) file, WinHelp displays the default topic as the first topic when the user first opens the Help file and when the Contents button is clicked. If you do not specify a default topic, WinHelp uses the first topic of the first file listed in the project (.hpj) file.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 2BTJW15}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 An entry macro is a macro that you specify to run whenever a user displays a topic. You specify an entry macro for a topic in an exclamation mark (!) footnote in the topic (.rtf) file. You can define a series of entry macros by separating them with colons or semicolons. Multiple macros are run in the order they are listed.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} .NSQ_T}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 A footnote is used in a topic to provide a unique topic identifier,\b  \plain\f1\fs16 identify index keywords, and provide other special information to Help Workshop.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} ATV8VK}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Full-text search is the ability to search for any word or phrase contained in Help file topics. Users can initiate a full-text search by using the Find tab in the Help Topics dialog box.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} OYZM9}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 A hash number is a unique number generated from a topic ID. It is this number, and not the topic ID itself, that WinHelp uses. You can use the JumpHash macro to jump to a topic identified by a hash number, or you can use the Report command to list the hash numbers of all topics in a Help file.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} PZJ46U}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Help Author mode is a way of running a Help file for testing purposes, providing the author with special navigational ability and other information about the structure of topics, links, windows, and macros. The Help Author command is available on the Help Workshop File menu.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} B6EHF_}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 A Help makefile contains a list of project (.hpj) files that you want to compile. Help Workshop compiles the project files in the order they are listed. Help makefiles have an .hmk extension.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} _B12QW}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 A nonscrolling region is a specified portion at the top of a topic that always remains visible, even if the user scrolls to the bottom of a long topic. The nonscrolling region is separated from the scrolling region by a thin, black line, and it can contain text, bitmaps, and hotspots. You specify a nonscrolling region by applying the Keep With Next paragraph style (or equivalent) to the paragraph(s) in the topic (.rtf) file.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} KMK38I}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 The Help Topics dialog box serves as the initial interface for the entire Help system. Typically, it contains Contents, Index, and Find tabs. The Help Topics dialog box appears when Help is run by using the HELP_FINDER command of the WinHelp API, or when a user double-clicks a Help file that is associated with a contents (.cnt) file that contains information for the Contents tab.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 2EOL3C}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 High Contrast is a display option that directs Windows to use colors and fonts that are designed for easy reading. Users can set this option on the Display tab in the Accessibility Options program in Control Panel.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} NJZ4W5}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 The history is a list of topics displayed in the main Help window, in the order the user viewed them. To see this list, click the Options menu, and then click Display History Window. This list is kept separately from the history list used by the Back button (and macro).
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 7BM6.K}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 A hotspot is an area on a screen that the user can click to jump to another topic or pop-up window, or to execute one or more macros.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 9ML77Q}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 A keyword is a word or phrase associated with a topic, usually for indexing purposes. The same keyword can be associated with several topics. You assign keywords to topics in footnotes in the topic (.rtf) file.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 1R9H33X}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 A KLink macro provides a link to topics by means of keywords listed in the K-footnotes of topic (.rtf) files. Keywords used in K-footnotes are also used in the index, so a KLink jump to a keyword has the same effect as clicking that keyword in the index. By contrast, ALink macros use keywords listed in A-footnotes, and these keywords are reserved for use by the ALink macro only. When a user clicks a hotspot that runs a KLink macro, WinHelp displays the Topics Found dialog box listing all the titles of topics associated with the K-keywords specified by the macro. The user can then jump to the desired topic by double-clicking the topic title.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} O8.Q2}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 The main Help window, unlike a secondary window, has a menu and a default button bar, and it cannot be autosized. WinHelp has default settings for the main window, but you can customize it by specifying it as "main" in the [WINDOWS] section of the project (.hpj) file. Only one main window can be displayed at a time.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 2MZ3DCP}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Multi-index keywords are words or phrases listed in special topic footnotes for use in indexes other than the one designated in the K-footnotes. With the exception of the A-keywords, these keywords can be accessed only by a program calling WinHelp with the HELP_MULTIKEY command.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} DOQEEK}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 A second-level index entry is a subset of a first-level index entry. On the Index tab, second-level index entries appear indented.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 2ZK4PT}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 A secondary window, unlike a main window, does not have a menu bar. Secondary windows must be specified in the [WINDOWS] section of the project (.hpj) file. The user can display up to nine secondary windows at one time.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 7.61TY}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 A topic ID is a string that identifies a topic or a location within a topic to display.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} L00JF5}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 A transparent bitmap is a 16-color bitmap in which WinHelp replaces the white pixels with the color of the background of the current Help window. Typically, marking a bitmap as transparent enables it to blend in better with the background.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 8AINQO}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx8815 Training cards are a set of Help topics in secondary windows that you can configure to communicate with another program. Authors can design training cards that display different topics based on what the user does within that other program.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} QAWJFN}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 A pop-up topic is a topic that appears in a pop-up window. A pop-up topic can contain text, graphics, multimedia files, or hotspots. Typically, you use pop-up topics to convey additional information, such as the definition of a term or the description of a dialog box component. 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 8XSV6X}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 A pop-up window is a window in which a pop-up topic is displayed. Pop-up windows have no menu or button bars and appear on top of the topic from which they are called. Pop-up windows disappear when a user clicks anywhere on the screen. A pop-up window can contain text, graphics, multimedia files, or hotspots. However, if you have a hotspot in a pop-up window, the first pop-up window closes when the user clicks the hotspot. WinHelp can display only one pop-up window at a time.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:007c}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} About project files}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} idh_BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1525 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES;BAS_HPJ}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} files,;files, .hpj;files, about project files;hpj files, see project files;project files;project files, about project files}
\b About project files
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1525 \plain\f1\fs16 The project (.hpj) file is an ASCII text file that is used to compile your Help file. The project file contains all the information Help Workshop needs to combine topic (.rtf) files and other elements into a Help file.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1525 You use Help Workshop to create and modify project files. When you create a new project file, the minimum settings you need are already made for you. The remaining settings depend on the size and complexity of your Help file.
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx1525 Each section and option in the project file has a different purpose, and each can be used to improve the effectiveness and usability of your Help file. For more information about the project files settings that are available in Help Workshop, open a project (.hpj) file or create a new one, and then do one of the following:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab For Help on items in dialog boxes, click \{bmc bm0.bmp\} at the top of the dialog box, and then click the item.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab For Help on items in a window, click the item or its label by using your right mouse button, and then click What's This.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \{button ,AL(`BAS_HPJ;NEW_AUTHOR_HPJ;PRO_HPJ')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`BAS_HPJ;NEW_AUTHOR_HPJ;PRO_HPJ')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:007d}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} About the contents file}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 3X_CONTENTS_DESIGN}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} 3X_CONTENTS_DESIGN;BAS_CNT;BAS_CNT_OVERVIEW;BAS_CONTENTS_CHECKLIST;DESIGN}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} books;books, described;contents files;contents files, about contents files;files,;files, .cnt;files, about contents files;headings;headings, described}
\b About the contents file
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The contents (.cnt) file is an ASCII text file that provides the instructions for the Contents tab in the Help Topics dialog box, and directs WinHelp to display the keywords of specified Help files on the Index and Find tabs. 
\par You design your table of contents by specifying the following in your contents file. 
\par \uldb \{bmc bm23.bmp\} Headings\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %S.O02O}
\par \uldb \{bmc bm23.bmp\} Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %2.PJRZS}
\par \uldb \{bmc bm23.bmp\} Commands\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %ODRKC3}
\par To create and edit contents files, use Help Workshop. For more information, click Related Topics.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Note
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab The Contents tab does not appear in the \ul Help Topics dialog box\plain\f1\fs16 {\v KMK38I} unless the contents file contains at least one topic that jumps to a Help file on a user's computer. The valid jump must be present in the contents file when a user first opens the associated Help file.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \{button ,AL(`BAS_CNT_31;3X_CONTENTS_DESIGN;NAVIGATION_DESIGN;CONTENTS_DESIGN;MULTIPLE_HELP_DESIGN;BAS_CNT;MORE_ABOUT_CNT_FILES;CONTENTS_DESIGN')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`BAS_CNT_31;3X_CONTENTS_DESIGN;NAVIGATION_DESIGN;CONTENTS_DESIGN;MULTIPLE_HELP_DESIGN;BAS_CNT;MORE_ABOUT_CNT_FILES;CONTENTS_DESIGN')}
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} S.O02O}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Headings
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Headings are represented by book icons and can contain a group of related topics and other headings. Users display the contents of a heading by double-clicking it.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 2.PJRZS}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Topics
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Topics are represented by page icons and either display a topic or run a macro when a user double-clicks them. Along with the topic title and topic ID, you can specify which Help file a topic is in, and which window type you want the topic to appear in.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} ODRKC3}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Commands
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Commands specify the scope and appearance of your table of contents and index, including:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The name of the default Help file (and window)
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The title to display in the Help Topics dialog box
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The names of Help files whose keywords you want to include on the Index tab and whose text you want to include on the Find tab of the Help Topics dialog box
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The names of Help files WinHelp should search for \ul keywords\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 9ML77Q} if the \ul ALink\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 7V8V.U} and \ul KLink\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 1R9H33X} macros are used in topics
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The names and locations of other tabs to display in the Help Topics dialog box.
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Overview: Compiling Help files}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 2HHH9US}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} building, see compiling;compiling;compiling, overview;compiling, with compression;compression;Help files;Help files, compiling;Help Workshop;Help Workshop, compiling Help files;project files;project files, compiling}
\b 
\par Compiling Help files
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 You create Help files by compiling the project file. This brings together all the information in your project (.hpj) file, topic (.rtf) files, bitmap (.bmp) files, and DLL data files.
\par When you compile your Help file, you can choose from several compression options that make your Help file smaller. The greater the compression, the longer it takes to compile your file. You can temporarily turn off compression to reduce the amount of time it takes to compile.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("BAS_THE_HELP_COMPILER;BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES;PRO_HPJ_COMPRESSION")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("BAS_THE_HELP_COMPILER;BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES;PRO_HPJ_COMPRESSION")}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:007e}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Features for testing Help files}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} idh_BAS_TESTING_HELP_FILES}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} BAS_HCW;BAS_TESTING_HELP_FILES;HCW_ERRORS;HELP_AUTHOR;REPORT;TEST_API;TEST_CNT;TEST_MACROS}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} Compare macro;compiler messages;compiler messages, monitoring;Help files;Help files, testing;Help system;Help system, features for testing;Help Workshop;Help Workshop, features for testing Help files;Help Workshop, monitoring messages;macros,;macros, Compare;messages;messages, monitoring WinHelp messages;monitoring WinHelp messages;Test Contents File command;testing;testing, about testing Help files;WinHelp messages}
\b Features for testing Help files
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 WinHelp and Help Workshop have the following testing features that make it easier to test your Help files:
\par \uldb \{bmc bm23.bmp\} Help Author mode\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %16NZXVI}
\par \uldb \{bmc bm23.bmp\} Monitoring WinHelp messages\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %7ZNLR5}
\par \uldb \{bmc bm23.bmp\} Test Contents File command\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %AMSXP0}
\par \uldb \{bmc bm23.bmp\} Compare macro\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %34BRZY7}
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL("Test;Compare;BAS_HELP_AUTHOR_MODE;BAS_COMPILE_MSG;NEW_COMPILE")\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL("Test;Compare;BAS_HELP_AUTHOR_MODE;BAS_COMPILE_MSG;NEW_COMPILE")}
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 16NZXVI}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Help Author mode
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 If a check mark appears beside the Help Author command on the File menu in Help Workshop, a line enabling Help Author features is added to your Win.ini file. Help Author mode provides additional information about the topics in a Help file, and enables you to more easily navigate from one topic to the next. 
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`PRO_HELPAUTHOR;BAS_HELP_AUTHOR_MODE')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`PRO_HELPAUTHOR;BAS_HELP_AUTHOR_MODE')}
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 34BRZY7}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Compare macro
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The Compare macro enables you to display side-by-side instances of two Help files. This macro is especially useful for comparing original and translated versions of the same Help file. You can run the Compare macro while you are viewing your Help by pressing \scaps ctrl+shift+j\plain\f1\fs16 , which displays the Jump dialog box.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`Compare')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`Compare')}
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} AMSXP0}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Test Contents File command
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 You can test your contents (.cnt) file in Help Workshop by clicking the Test menu, and then clicking Contents File. Help Workshop checks to make sure that the syntax in your contents file is correct. Help Workshop then jumps to every topic specified in the contents file and displays a message if one of the jumps does not work.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`PRO_TEST_CNT')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`PRO_TEST_CNT')}
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 7ZNLR5}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Monitoring WinHelp messages
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 You can view WinHelp messages to determine whether actions in a Help file are working correctly. Using this feature, you can monitor WinHelp API calls, context-sensitive calls, which macros are being run, hotspot jumps, which topics and pop-ups are current, and which configuration (.gid) file is being read.
\par To monitor WinHelp messages in Help Workshop, click the View menu, and then click WinHelp Messages. Then open a Help file.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Tips
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab Messages are added to the log file at the insertion point, so if you move the insertion point during a session, make sure you return it to the end of the text.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Help Workshop tracks WinHelp messages for all instances of WinHelp. Make sure that only one instance of WinHelp is running.
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125\tx295 \{button ,AL(`PRO_TRACK_WINHELP_MSGS')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`PRO_TRACK_WINHELP_MSGS')}
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:007f}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} About Help Author mode}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} BAS_HELP_AUTHOR_MODE}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} BAS_HELP_AUTHOR_MODE;HELP_AUTHOR}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} Ask On Hotspots command;Help Author mode;Help Author mode, about Help Author mode;Help files;Help files, navigating in;Help topics,;Help topics, displaying information about;hotspots;hotspots, Ask On Hotspots command;hotspots, displaying information about;jumps;jumps, displaying hotspot information;navigating in Help files;Topic Information command;topic numbers, using to display topics;topics,;topics, displaying information about}
\b About Help Author mode
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 You can display information about a Help topic in addition to more detailed error messages by clicking the File menu in Help Workshop, and then making sure Help Author is checked. Help Author mode provides the following features:
\par \uldb \{bmc bm23.bmp\} Topic numbers\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %76ZAYA}
\par \uldb \{bmc bm23.bmp\} Easier navigation\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %CIVCB5}
\par \uldb \{bmc bm23.bmp\} Information about topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %12F4E2F}
\par \uldb \{bmc bm23.bmp\} Information about hotspots\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %1P_D_XO}
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`BAS_TESTING_HELP_FILES;BAS_COMPILE_MSG;')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`BAS_TESTING_HELP_FILES;BAS_COMPILE_MSG;N')}
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 76ZAYA}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Topic numbers
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 If Help Author is enabled, title bar text is replaced by unique topic numbers that identify each topic's position in the Help file. The first topic in the first topic (.rtf) file that is listed in your project (.hpj) file appears as topic number one. Subsequent topics are listed in the order specified in your project file. The number for a topic may change if the sequence of topics in your topic file changes or if you add or remove topics. To display a specific topic by its number, press \scaps ctrl+shift+j\plain\f1\fs16  in a topic, and the type the topic number.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} CIVCB5}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Easier navigation
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 If Help Author is enabled, you can use key combinations to navigate within your Help file. If a Help topic is open, you can move to the following or preceding topic by pressing \scaps ctrl+shift+right arrow\plain\f1\fs16  or \scaps ctrl+shift+left arrow. \plain\f1\fs16 To move to the beginning or end of your Help file, press \scaps ctrl+shift+home \plain\f1\fs16 or \scaps ctrl+shift+end.\plain\f1\fs16 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 12F4E2F}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Information about topics
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 If Help Author is enabled, a Topic Information command appears when you click a topic by using your right mouse button. Clicking this command displays the topic's title (as specified by its $ footnote), any macros specified by an entry macro (!) footnote, the current window type, and the Help filename and path. Additional information appears in this dialog box if you selected the Include .Rtf Filename And Topic ID In Help File check box in the Compile a Help File dialog box before you compiled. This adds the name of the .rtf file that contains the topic and the topic's ID to the Topic Information dialog box.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 1P_D_XO}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Information about hotspots
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 If Help Author is enabled, an Ask On Hotspots command appears when you click a topic by using your right mouse button. If a check mark appears beside this command, WinHelp does not run the hotspot jump or macro when you click it. Instead, it displays the hidden text associated with the hotspot jump or macro. You can then choose to run the jump or macro, or return to the topic.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Note
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab The Ask On Hotspots command might not work correctly if there are no keywords in your Help file.
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0080}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Compiler messages}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} BAS_COMPILE_MSG}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} BAS_COMPILE_MSG}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} compiler messages;compiler messages, about compiler messages;error handling;Help Workshop;Help Workshop, messages, described;messages;messages, about compiler messages;notes;warning messages}
\b Compiler messages
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Windows\'a095 can display up to 64K of compiler messages (Windows\'a0NT can display up to 1 MB). However, if you specify a log file in which to save messages, there is no size limit for the file. For more information about a message and how to resolve it, use the Index or Find tab in Help Workshop Help, and look up the corresponding message ID, for example "HC1003." While you compile your Help file, Help Workshop may display messages of the following types:
\par \ul \ul \{bmc bm23.bmp\}\ul  Notes\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %3ZJF2}
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \ul \ul \{bmc bm23.bmp\}\ul  Warnings\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %113Q8O6}
\par \ul \ul \{bmc bm23.bmp\}\ul  Errors\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %10E5O5H}
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`BAS_PROJ_FILE_EDITOR;BAS_THE_HELP_COMPILER;EXEC_HCW;EXEC_HCRTF;PRO_HPJ_ERRORLOG;PRO_HPJ_ERRORLOG')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`BAS_PROJ_FILE_EDITOR;BAS_THE_HELP_COMPILER;EXEC_HCW;EXEC_HCRTF;PRO_HPJ_ERRORLOG;PRO_HPJ_ERRORLOG')}
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 3ZJF2}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Notes are conditions that you should be aware of. They will probably not cause serious problems when you open your Help file. For example, "HC1003: Note: A paragraph mark is formatted as a hidden character."
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 113Q8O6}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Warnings are conditions that will result in a defective Help file. For example, "HC3059: Warning: A hotspot is specified without a macro or topic ID."
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 10E5O5H}
\pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 Errors are conditions that prevent the Help file from compiling. For example, "HC5005: Error: The file cannot be found."
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0081}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Checklist for translating Help files}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} BAS_TRANSLATING}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} BAS_HPJ;BAS_TRANSLATING}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} contents files;contents files, translating;Help files;Help files, translating;Help system;Help system, localizing;localizing;localizing, Help files;project files;project files, localizing;testing;testing, translated Help files;translating;translating, Help files}
\b Checklist for translating Help files
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 WinHelp can display Help files compiled in any of 29 different languages. In addition, WinHelp provides tools for translating a Help file from one language to another while retaining the same structure.
\par You typically carry out the following tasks sequentially when you translate Help files:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \uldb 1\tab Translate topic (.rtf) files\plain\f1\fs16 {\v OGO6SZ}\uldb 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 2\tab Change settings in project (.hpj) files\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 42CA8G8}\uldb 
\par 3\tab Translate contents (.cnt) files\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 59DTMP}\uldb 
\par 4\tab Compare original and translated versions\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 1BQ.K66}
\par \pard\sl-115\li265\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`test;BAS_SORT_LANGUAGE;BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES;BAS_PROJ_FILE_EDITOR;BAS_CNT_OVERVIEW;BAS_CONTENTS_FILE_EDITOR;BAS_TESTING_HELP_FILES;BAS_PROJECT_FILE_CHECKLIST;BAS_CONTENTS_CHECKLIST;BAS_THE_HELP_COMPILER;translate_hpj')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`test;BAS_SORT_LANGUAGE;BAS_ABOUT_HPJ_FILES;BAS_PROJ_FILE_EDITOR;BAS_CNT_OVERVIEW;BAS_CONTENTS_FILE_EDITOR;BAS_TESTING_HELP_FILES;BAS_PROJECT_FILE_CHECKLIST;BAS_CONTENTS_CHECKLIST;BAS_THE_HELP_COMPILER;translate_hpj')}
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} OGO6SZ}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Translate topic (.rtf) files
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Create copies of the original topic files before you translate the text. You will probably want to translate all the text in topics, including \ul K-keywords,\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 9ML77Q} titles, and the text on \ul authorable buttons.\plain\f1\fs16 {\v FO6MEW} When translating K-keywords, retain one-to-one relationships for the sake of any \ul KLink\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 1R9H33X} macros in the Help file. Be sure that keywords specified in KLink macros are updated to specify translated keywords. Be sure to retain the original \ul topic IDs\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 7.61TY} in the # \ul footnotes,\plain\f1\fs16 {\v .NSQ_T} any hidden jump identifiers, browse tags, \ul build tags,\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 12MF62E} and macros. 
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 42CA8G8}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Change settings in project (.hpj) files 
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Create a copy of the original project file. In Help Workshop, open the new project file, and then check the Translation command on the File menu. Most settings that should not be translated become unavailable. Make any necessary changes, including:
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The sorting order for keywords
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The default character set
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab The default fonts
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Any path changes to point to the translated topic files
\par \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab Whether the topic (.rtf) files use a double-byte character set (DBCS)
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 59DTMP}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Translate contents (.cnt) files
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 Create a copy of the original contents files. In Help Workshop, open the new contents file, and then check the Translation command on the File menu. Any settings that should not be translated become unavailable. Change headings and topic titles as needed.
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} 1BQ.K66}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Compare original and translated versions
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 The Compare macro enables you to view two Help files at once. This enables you to view the original topics and the corresponding translated topics side-by-side. To run the Compare macro, press \scaps ctrl+shift+j\plain\f1\fs16  when a topic is open, and then type the following:
\par \b !compare("filename.hlp")\plain\f1\fs16 
\par For filename.hlp, substitute the name of the Help file you want to compare with the file that is open.\b 
\par \page
{\up +}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up +} BROWSE0027:0082}
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} Customizing topic windows}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} BAS_HPJ_CREATE_WINDOW}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 {\up A}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up A} BAS_HPJ;BAS_HPJ_CREATE_WINDOW}
{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} customizing;customizing, Help windows;Help system;Help system, customizing topic windows;Help windows;Help windows, customizing;secondary windows;secondary windows, customizing;topic windows, customizing;windows,;windows, customizing}
Customizing topic windows
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 WinHelp includes a predefined window called the main window, which has a menu bar and button bar. You can customize the main window or create new \ul secondary windows.\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 2ZK4PT}
\par You can define as many as 255 window types (including the main window) in your project (.hpj) file. WinHelp can display up to 10 windows at a time (the main window and nine secondary windows). You can customize the following window properties:
\par \uldb \{bmc bm23.bmp\} Size and position\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %.T1IMB}
\par \uldb \{bmc bm23.bmp\} Background color\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %IQNGV4}
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \uldb \{bmc bm23.bmp\} Title bar text\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %J7HORR}
\par \uldb \{bmc bm23.bmp\} Button bar\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %6ORX.S.}
\par \uldb \{bmc bm23.bmp\} Menus and menu commands\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %.SVEAR}
\par \uldb \{bmc bm23.bmp\} Stay-on-top status\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %54MJKZG}
\par \uldb \{bmc bm23.bmp\} Automatic window sizing\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %U0U8PP}
\par \uldb \{bmc bm23.bmp\} Macros that run when a window opens\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %2KL9_I6}
\par \pard\sb45\sl-115\li295\ri125\fi-185\brdrb\brdrs\tx295 
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \{button ,AL(`BAS_AUTH_MENU;BAS_CONFIG_MACRO;NAVIGATION_DESIGN;MACRO_REF_OVR;BAS_AUTH_BTN;BAS_AUTH_BTN;WINDOW_DESIGN')\} \uldb Related Topics\plain\f1\fs16 {\v %!AL(`BAS_AUTH_MENU;BAS_CONFIG_MACRO;NAVIGATION_DESIGN;MACRO_REF_OVR;BAS_AUTH_BTN;BAS_AUTH_BTN;WINDOW_DESIGN')}
\par \page
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} .T1IMB}
\pard\sb115\sa35\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Changing a window's size and position
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 You can specify the size and position of a window by opening your project (.hpj) file in Help Workshop, and then clicking the Windows button. Size and position settings are on the Position tab. 
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Tip
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab For help on an item in the Window Properties dialog box, click \{bmc bm0.bmp\} in its title bar, and then click the item.
