{\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} configuration macros;Help files;Help files, adding configuration macros;Help system;Help system, using macros to configure;macros,;macros, running when a Help file is opened;running macros}
\b Specifying macros that apply to your entire Help file
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li115\ri125 \plain\f1\fs16 You can specify macros that run whenever a user opens a Help file. For example, you can use macros to specify optional buttons, menus, or menu items for the main window and to access programs and capabilities outside the Help system. To do this, open your project (.hpj) file in Help Workshop, and then click the Config button.
\par \pard\sb115\sl-235\li115\ri125 \b Tips
\par \pard\sb75\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \plain\f2\fs16 \'b7\f1 \tab For help on an item in the Configuration Macros dialog box, click \{bmc bm0.bmp\} in its title bar, and then click the item.
\par \pard\sb45\sl-235\li295\ri125\fi-185\tx295 \f2 \'b7\f1 \tab You can also assign macros to individual window types by opening your project (.hpj) file in Help Workshop, clicking the Windows button, and then clicking the Macros tab. Any macros you assign to the main window will override macros assigned to the main window in the Help Configuration dialog box. However, any macros you assign to a \ul secondary window\plain\f1\fs16 {\v 2ZK4PT} apply only to that window type.
